### Summary

A missing or partially available head block/header will cause a full chain reset for a Geth node (potentially forcing a full resync) as the node startup logic will call bc.Reset() when rawdb.ReadHeadBlockHash or GetHeaderByHash or the head block lookup returns empty/nil, allowing an attacker or a transient DB inconsistency to trigger a destructive recovery path.

Contract: go-ethereum/core/blockchain.go

Structured: A missing or inconsistent on-disk head (root cause) will cause a destructive chain reset (impact) for Geth node operators (affected party) as node startup logic will call bc.Reset() when any of the head keys/objects are missing (actor: DB corruption, mis-pruning, or crafted/induced state) and thus force a full reset/rebuild of the chain (attack/recovery path).

### Root Cause

In case it’s a mistake in the code:
- In https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/blob/master/core/blockchain.go#L421 the startup path unconditionally calls bc.Reset() when the head block hash is missing (rawdb.ReadHeadBlockHash(bc.db) returning empty), treating any missing head key as irrecoverable corruption.

- In https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/blob/master/core/blockchain.go#L596-L607 and https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/blob/master/core/blockchain.go#L1155 the function loadLastState() similarly calls bc.Reset() when the head header is missing or the head block cannot be retrieved. These direct calls lead to a destructive reset.

- In https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/blob/master/core/blockchain.go#L1167 and https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/blob/master/core/blockchain.go#L1181 the Reset() → ResetWithGenesisBlock() → SetHead(0) chain is used to purge and reinitialise the chain, which is an aggressive recovery measure invoked automatically during startup when relatively small or local inconsistencies are detected.

Code excerpt (relevant parts):
```go
func NewBlockChain(...)(...){
    ...
    if err := bc.loadLastState(); err != nil {
        return nil, err
    }
    ...
}

func (...) loadLastState() error {
    ...
    head := rawdb.ReadHeadBlockHash(bc.db)
    if head == (common.Hash{}) {
        // Corrupt or empty database, init from scratch
        log.Warn("Empty database, resetting chain")
        return bc.Reset() // <===@
    }
    headHeader := bc.GetHeaderByHash(head)
    if headHeader == nil {
        // Corrupt or empty database, init from scratch
        log.Warn("Head header missing, resetting chain", "hash", head)
        return bc.Reset()  // <===@
    }
    ...
}

// Reset purges the entire blockchain, restoring it to its genesis state.
func (...) Reset() error {
    return bc.ResetWithGenesisBlock(bc.genesisBlock) // <===@
}

func (...) ResetWithGenesisBlock(...) error {
    // Dump the entire block chain and purge the caches
    if err := bc.SetHead(0); err != nil { // <===@
        return err
    }
    ...
    rawdb.WriteBlock(batch, genesis)
    if err := batch.Write(); err != nil {
        log.Crit("Failed to write genesis block", "err", err) // <===@
    }
    bc.writeHeadBlock(genesis)
    ...
    return bc.initializeHistoryPruning(0) // <===@
}

```
Why this is a mistake (conceptual):
The design decision to automatically and destructively reset the chain on any missing head-related DB key is dangerous. Missing keys can be caused by transient I/O errors, partial writes, pruning edge-cases, or even benign local filesystem activity. Automatically purging and reinitializing the chain without safer recovery attempts or an operator confirmation risks causing unnecessary full resyncs and potential data loss of locally stored ancients/state.

### Internal Pre-conditions

Numbered conditions required to trigger the destructive path:

1. The node process starts and executes NewBlockChain(...) which calls bc.loadLastState().
2. rawdb.ReadHeadBlockHash(bc.db) returns the zero hash ((common.Hash{})) or bc.GetHeaderByHash(head) returns nil for the value returned by the head read.
3. There is no intermediate recovery path executed before bc.Reset() is returned (i.e., the code path reaches the return bc.Reset() statements as-is).
4. bc.Reset() executes successfully (i.e., SetHead(0) succeeds and the DB batch writes succeed), leading to a full reinitialization to genesis.

(Short: node startup + missing head hash/header/block body -> immediate bc.Reset() -> destructive reset.)

### External Pre-conditions

Conditions dependent on external systems/protocols:
1. A transient disk I/O failure, partial DB write, or corrupted single DB key (e.g., head block key or head header key) occurs before node restart.
2. A node operator has enabled pruning/snapshotting such that the head block body might be missing (pruned) due to incorrect/prior configuration and the node's startup assumptions are violated.
3. An attacker who can modify on-disk DB files (local/host compromise) can remove or tamper with the head/hash keys to force the node to reset (not a network-only attacker — requires local access or induced corruption).

### Attack Path

1. Trigger condition set: An adversary or an environmental fault causes the node's on-disk DB to have a missing/cleared head block hash key or head header key. This could be due to:
 - local filesystem corruption, or
 - a misconfigured pruning routine, or
 - an operator/runbook action that accidentally deleted the key.
2. Node restart: Operator restarts Geth (or node restarts for other reasons). During initialization, NewBlockChain() is called.
3. loadLastState() detection: loadLastState() calls rawdb.ReadHeadBlockHash(bc.db). The returned value is zero/absent or GetHeaderByHash() returns nil.
4. Immediate destructive response: Because the code treats that absence as irrecoverable corruption, it logs a warning and calls bc.Reset().
5. Complete reinitialization: bc.Reset() → ResetWithGenesisBlock() → SetHead(0) is executed. The chain head is truncated, caches are cleared and genesis is written, leading the node to behave as if starting from genesis and force a full resync / re-sync from peers or snap sync. If ancients were present, they may be truncated depending on SetHead semantics; this can cause extended downtime and additional load on the network as the node re-downloads data.

### Impact

- Geth node operators (affected party) will suffer an approximate operational impact of: forced full resync / downtime; worst case  if SetHead(0) or initializeHistoryPruning(0) misbehaves, local ancients or historical data may be truncated, forcing even longer recovery. The time and bandwidth cost depends on chain sync method (could be hours to days).
- Network-level impact: If an operator/automated system is able to trigger this across many Geth installations (e.g., via a mispackaged upgrade, or shared script), many nodes could simultaneously force resyncs  this increases load on peers and could degrade service availability for users served by these nodes. With Geth being ~41% of execution clients, a wide-scale occurrence could approach High severity (availability impact) depending on breadth.
- Attacker gains: If an attacker has local filesystem access to many nodes, they could cause widespread node downtime (griefing). The attacker does not gain ETH directly; the impact is availability/operational.

### PoC

add this function in blockchain_test.go:
```go
// Tests that loadLastState resets the chain to genesis if the head is missing.
func TestLoadLastStateResetsToGenesis(t *testing.T) {
	var (
		key, _  = crypto.HexToECDSA("b71c71a67e1177ad4e901695e1b4b9ee17ae16c6668d313eac2f96dbcda3f291")
		address = crypto.PubkeyToAddress(key.PublicKey)
		funds   = big.NewInt(1000000000000000)
		gspec   = &Genesis{
			Config:  params.TestChainConfig,
			Alloc:   types.GenesisAlloc{address: {Balance: funds}},
			BaseFee: big.NewInt(params.InitialBaseFee),
		}
	)

	// Create an empty in-memory database (no head written)
	db := rawdb.NewMemoryDatabase()

	// Instantiate blockchain, which calls loadLastState()
	bc, err := NewBlockChain(db, gspec, ethash.NewFaker(), DefaultConfig())
	if err != nil {
		t.Fatalf("failed to create blockchain: %v", err)
	}
	defer bc.Stop()

	// At this point loadLastState should have called Reset(),
	// forcing the blockchain to point to genesis.
	head := bc.CurrentBlock()
	if head.NumberU64() != 0 {
		t.Fatalf("expected head to be genesis (0), got %d", head.NumberU64())
	}
	if head.Hash() != gspec.ToBlock(nil).Hash() {
		t.Fatalf("expected genesis hash %x, got %x", gspec.ToBlock(nil).Hash(), head.Hash())
	}
	t.Logf("Blockchain successfully reset to genesis: number=%d hash=%x", head.NumberU64(), head.Hash())
}
```

### Mitigation

High-level mitigations (recommended)
1. Do not auto-reset on missing head keys. Replace destructive bc.Reset() calls at startup with a non-destructive fail-open or degraded startup mode that:
  - returns a clear error to the caller (so operator decides action), or
  - attempts safe recovery paths before reset (see below).
2. Attempt non-destructive recovery first:
  - Check the HeadHeader/headers DB and try to reconstruct head from headers-only (headers are cheaper and often intact).
  - Attempt to retrieve missing block bodies from the ancient store/freezer before deciding to reset.
  - If Snap/Freezer root exists (rawdb.ReadSnapshotRoot), attempt setHeadBeyondRoot recovery path (as used elsewhere in code), or attempt a peer fetch for missing bodies (defer reset until peer fetch fails after retries/timeouts).
3. Require explicit operator consent for a destructive reset. Introduce a config option or CLI flag such as --force-db-reset or --allow-automatic-reset which must be set to enable automatic Reset on startup. Default behavior: log the problem and abort start (or start in headers-only / light mode).
4. Back up data before aggressive operations. If reset/SetHead will truncate ancients, snapshot/backup the freezer/ancients directory before truncation; if backup fails, abort.
5. Improve logging and monitoring. Emit explicit audit log and metric for “startup-triggered-reset” with enough context for operators to triage.

Concrete code-level fix (suggested patch outline)

Replace the direct return bc.Reset() calls inside loadLastState() with a safer handling flow: try non-destructive recovery, and if that fails, return a descriptive error (and let NewBlockChain decide). Example patch sketch:
```diff
@@
-    head := rawdb.ReadHeadBlockHash(bc.db)
-    if head == (common.Hash{}) {
-        // Corrupt or empty database, init from scratch
-        log.Warn("Empty database, resetting chain")
-        return bc.Reset()
-    }
+    head := rawdb.ReadHeadBlockHash(bc.db)
+    if head == (common.Hash{}) {
+        // Head key missing. Try non-destructive recovery first, then
+        // fail startup and require operator/flag to perform a reset.
+        log.Warn("Empty head block hash in DB - attempting safe recovery", "action", "headers-only")
+        if err := bc.attemptSafeHeadRecovery(); err != nil {
+            // Do not reset automatically. Return error to caller so operator can decide.
+            return fmt.Errorf("missing head block hash and safe recovery failed: %w", err)
+        }
+        // attemptSafeHeadRecovery should set up bc state appropriately (headers-only)
+    }
@@
-    if headHeader == nil {
-        // Corrupt or empty database, init from scratch
-        log.Warn("Head header missing, resetting chain", "hash", head)
-        return bc.Reset()
-    }
+    if headHeader == nil {
+        // Missing header for the head hash: try to recover header from header-trie or peers.
+        log.Warn("Head header missing - attempting header re-fetch/rebuild", "hash", head)
+        if err := bc.attemptHeaderRecovery(head); err != nil {
+            return fmt.Errorf("head header missing and header recovery failed: %w", err)
+        }
+        headHeader = bc.GetHeaderByHash(head)
+        if headHeader == nil {
+            return errors.New("head header missing after recovery attempt")
+        }
+    }

```

Add new helper methods (pseudocode responsibilities):
1. func (bc *BlockChain) attemptSafeHeadRecovery() error:
  - Try to set bc.currentBlock/hc from available headers (headers-only mode) or rebuild head using ReadHeadHeaderHash as fallback. Do not delete DB.
2. func (bc *BlockChain) attemptHeaderRecovery(head common.Hash) error
  - Try to rehydrate header from header database, or contact peers to fetch header (with timeout/retry), or use freezer/ancients to reconstruct.

Top-level behavior change:NewBlockChain() should check the error returned by loadLastState() and if it's a ErrCorruptDatabase-like sentinel, do not automatically call bc.Reset() on behalf of the operator. Instead return the error, log an actionable message: "DB missing head; to reset use --force-db-reset or run go-ethereum with recovery tool X". If the operator explicitly passed a --force-db-reset flag, then NewBlockChain() may perform bc.Reset() as a last resort.

Minimal safe change (if behavioural change must be minimal)

If maintainers prefer a smaller change, require an explicit config flag (e.g., cfg.AllowAutoReset == true) before invoking bc.Reset():
```diff
-    if head == (common.Hash{}) {
-        log.Warn("Empty database, resetting chain")
-        return bc.Reset()
-    }
+    if head == (common.Hash{}) {
+        log.Warn("Empty database")
+        if bc.cfg.AllowAutoReset {
+            log.Warn("Auto-reset is enabled, resetting chain")
+            return bc.Reset()
+        }
+        return errors.New("head block hash missing; auto-reset disabled by config")
+    }

```

This is defensive and preserves backward compatibility for operators who intentionally allow auto-reset, but prevents accidental destructive resets by default.

### Summary

The [MaxSlot calculation at L115](https://github.com/Consensys/teku/blob/3edcac12446f08fe0969de70575b1c7a87e9ae33/networking/eth2/src/main/java/tech/pegasys/teku/networking/eth2/rpc/beaconchain/methods/DataColumnSidecarsByRangeMessageHandler.java#L115) is not protected for overflowing (which throws ArithmeticException).
```java
  public UInt64 getMaxSlot() {
    return getStartSlot().plus(getCount()).minusMinZero(1);
  }
```
The prior [validation](https://github.com/Consensys/teku/blob/3edcac12446f08fe0969de70575b1c7a87e9ae33/networking/eth2/src/main/java/tech/pegasys/teku/networking/eth2/rpc/beaconchain/methods/DataColumnSidecarsByRangeMessageHandler.java#L91) does not cover the case where someone sends:

```text
  DataColumnSidecarsByRangeRequestMessage {
      startSlot: UInt64.MAX_VALUE - 100,  // Near max value
      count: 200,                         // Causes startSlot + count to overflow
      columns: [0]                        // Single column, passes multiplication check
  }
```

This will eventually be caught in the RPC handler as shown below, but it would be ideal to handle the error more gracefully.

https://github.com/Consensys/teku/blob/3edcac12446f08fe0969de70575b1c7a87e9ae33/networking/eth2/src/main/java/tech/pegasys/teku/networking/eth2/rpc/core/Eth2IncomingRequestHandler.java#L116
```java
  private void handleRequest(
      final Optional<Eth2Peer> peer,
      final TRequest request,
      final ResponseCallback<TResponse> callback) {
    try {
      requestHandled.set(true);
      final Optional<RpcException> requestValidationError =
          localMessageHandler.validateRequest(protocolId, request);
      if (requestValidationError.isPresent()) {
        callback.completeWithErrorResponse(requestValidationError.get());
        return;
      }
      localMessageHandler.onIncomingMessage(protocolId, peer, request, callback);
    } catch (final StreamClosedException e) {
      LOG.trace("Stream closed before response sent for request {}", protocolId, e);
      callback.completeWithUnexpectedError(e);
    } catch (final Throwable t) {
      LOG.error("Unhandled error while processing request {}", protocolId, t);
      callback.completeWithUnexpectedError(t);
    }
  }
```

