### Summary

An uninitialized channel field will cause a gossip publishing failure / silent runtime error for Teku networking as a developer/operator will attempt to publish messages before subscribing and thereby encounter IllegalStateException("Gossip channel not available") or fire-and-forget failures where gossip never occurred.

Affected file: teku/blob/master/networking/eth2/src/main/java/tech/pegasys/teku/networking/eth2/gossip/AbstractGossipManager.java

### Root Cause

In https://github.com/Consensys/teku/blob/master/networking/eth2/src/main/java/tech/pegasys/teku/networking/eth2/gossip/AbstractGossipManager.java#L47-L124 the channel field is declared and left as Optional.empty() and publishing code assumes the channel will already be present:
```java
public abstract class AbstractGossipManager<T extends SszData> implements GossipManager {
  private static final Logger LOG = LogManager.getLogger();

  private final GossipNetwork gossipNetwork;
  private final GossipEncoding gossipEncoding;

  private final Eth2TopicHandler<T> topicHandler;

  private Optional<TopicChannel> channel = Optional.empty(); // <==
  private final GossipFailureLogger gossipFailureLogger;
  private final Function<T, Optional<UInt64>> getSlotForMessage;

  protected AbstractGossipManager(... ) {
    ...
  }

  protected SafeFuture<Void> publishMessageWithFeedback(final T message) {
    return channel // <==
        .map(c -> c.gossip(gossipEncoding.encode(message)))
        .orElse(SafeFuture.failedFuture(new IllegalStateException("Gossip channel not available")))
        .handle( ... );
  }

  @Override
  public void subscribe() {
    if (channel.isEmpty()) { // <==
      channel = Optional.of(gossipNetwork.subscribe(topicHandler.getTopic(), topicHandler));
    }
  }

  @Override
  public void unsubscribe() {
    if (channel.isPresent()) { // <==
      channel.get().close();
      channel = Optional.empty();
    }
  }
}

```
The code relies on callers to call subscribe() before any publish* call. If publishMessageWithFeedback is called when channel is empty, it returns a failed future with the generic IllegalStateException. The codebase also exposes a fire-and-forget publishMessage which calls publishMessageWithFeedback(...).finishStackTrace()  this can hide or delay visibility of the error if the future is not explicitly awaited.

This is a coding/design inconsistency (lazy initialization without clear contract/enforcement), likely introduced by design that decouples subscription lifecycle from the manager but without defensive checks or clear documentation.

### Internal Pre-conditions

1. Developer / Operator must call publishMessage(...) or publishMessageWithFeedback(...) before calling subscribe() on the GossipManager.
2. The runtime environment must not have previously called subscribe() (i.e., channel remains Optional.empty()).
3. The caller may not await the returned future from publishMessageWithFeedback, so failures may be missed (fire-and-forget code path).

### External Pre-conditions

None. This is an internal code lifecycle / initialization issue and does not require any external protocol state changes.

### Attack Path

This is not a remote exploit; it is a local initialization / lifecycle issue. Reproduction steps:
- A component constructs an AbstractGossipManager (or a subclass instance) but does not call subscribe().
- The component calls publishMessage(message) (fire-and-forget) or publishMessageWithFeedback(message) and either ignores the resulting future or the caller is not prepared to handle the failed future.
- Because channel is Optional.empty(), publishMessageWithFeedback returns a failed future with IllegalStateException("Gossip channel not available"). If the future is not awaited, the error is only logged by the gossip failure logger (or possibly lost), and the message is never gossiped.

### Impact

he node cannot publish gossip messages (attestations, blocks, sidecars, etc.) until subscribe() has been called; published messages attempted before subscription will fail or be silently ignored if the returned future is not awaited. This can lead to:
- Missed propagation of critical messages (reduced liveness / degraded participation).
- Confusing runtime errors (Gossip channel not available) that are easy to misdiagnose.
- Increased operator time-to-recovery during startup or in tests.

### PoC

...

### Mitigation

Make publishMessageWithFeedback explicitly require subscription and return a clear, descriptive exception if not subscribed. Add an assertion or IllegalStateException with actionable message. Also avoid fire-and-forget; encourage awaiting the future.
```java
protected SafeFuture<Void> publishMessageWithFeedback(final T message) {
  if (channel.isEmpty()) {
    return SafeFuture.failedFuture(
        new IllegalStateException("Gossip channel not available: must call subscribe() before publishing"));
  }
  return channel
      .map(c -> c.gossip(gossipEncoding.encode(message)))
      .orElseThrow(); // unreachable now
  ...
}
```
If appropriate for the lifecycle, automatically subscribe when publishing if not already subscribed. This may hide lifecycle mistakes so use carefully.
```java
protected SafeFuture<Void> publishMessageWithFeedback(final T message) {
  if (channel.isEmpty()) {
    // auto-subscribe (synchronized if needed)
    channel = Optional.of(gossipNetwork.subscribe(topicHandler.getTopic(), topicHandler));
  }
  return channel.map(c -> c.gossip(gossipEncoding.encode(message)))
      .orElse(SafeFuture.failedFuture(new IllegalStateException("Gossip channel not available")))
      .handle(...);
}
```

### Summary

Returning an uncompleted SafeFuture on shutdown will cause a hang / indefinite wait for callers and degrade availability for Teku infrastructure as a caller (developer/operator or internal component) will call runAsync/runAfterDelay after shutdown and then block or wait forever on the returned future.

Affected file: teku/infrastructure/async/src/main/java/tech/pegasys/teku/infrastructure/async/ScheduledExecutorAsyncRunner.java

### Root Cause

In https://github.com/Consensys/teku/blob/master/infrastructure/async/src/main/java/tech/pegasys/teku/infrastructure/async/ScheduledExecutorAsyncRunner.java#L71-L114 the code returns new SafeFuture<>() when shutdown is in progress and otherwise allocates a SafeFuture that may never be completed if the executor rejects the task or shutdown races occur:
```java
public <U> SafeFuture<U> runAsync(final ExceptionThrowingFutureSupplier<U> action) {
    if (shutdown.get()) {
      LOG.debug("Ignoring async task because shutdown is in progress");
      return new SafeFuture<>();
    }
    final SafeFuture<U> result = new SafeFuture<>(); // <==
    try {
      workerPool.execute(createRunnableForAction(action, result));
    } catch (final Throwable t) {
      handleExecutorError(result, t); // <==
    }
    return result;
  }

  public <U> SafeFuture<U> runAsync(final ExceptionThrowingFutureSupplier<U> action) {
    if (shutdown.get()) {
      LOG.debug("Ignoring async task because shutdown is in progress");
      return new SafeFuture<>(); // <==
    }
    final SafeFuture<U> result = new SafeFuture<>(); // <==
    try {
      workerPool.execute(createRunnableForAction(action, result));
    } catch (final Throwable t) {
      handleExecutorError(result, t); // <==
    }
    return result;
  }

  @Override
  @SuppressWarnings("FutureReturnValueIgnored")
  public <U> SafeFuture<U> runAfterDelay(
      final ExceptionThrowingFutureSupplier<U> action, final Duration delay) {
    if (shutdown.get()) {
      LOG.debug("Ignoring async task because shutdown is in progress");
      return new SafeFuture<>(); // <==
    }
    final SafeFuture<U> result = new SafeFuture<>(); // <==
    try {
      scheduler.schedule(
          () -> {
            try {
              workerPool.execute(createRunnableForAction(action, result));
            } catch (final Throwable t) {
              handleExecutorError(result, t);
            }
          },
          delay.toMillis(),
          TimeUnit.MILLISECONDS);
    } catch (final Throwable t) {
      handleExecutorError(result, t); // <==
    }
    return result;
  }

```
Because the method returns a newly created SafeFuture that is never completed (neither success nor failure) when shutdown is active or when a RejectedExecutionException is ignored due to shutdown, callers that get()/join() the future will block indefinitely.

This is a coding/contract mistake: asynchronous API calls must either complete their returned Future (success or exceptional) or document clearly that they may never complete  the latter is not acceptable for internal critical infrastructure.

### Internal Pre-conditions

1. {Operator/Component} calls shutdown() on the ScheduledExecutorAsyncRunner, setting shutdown to true.
2. {Developer/Component} subsequently (accidentally or due to race) calls runAsync(...) or runAfterDelay(...) while shutdown.get() == true.
3. The caller either blocks waiting on the returned SafeFuture (e.g., join()/get()) or expects completion to continue shutdown/cleanup logic.

### External Pre-conditions

None. This is an internal lifecycle / API contract bug and does not rely on external protocol or network state.

### Attack Path

- {Operator} triggers graceful shutdown of the runner: runner.shutdown().
- A background component (or test harness) calls runner.runAsync(someAction) after shutdown. Because shutdown.get() is true, the method returns new SafeFuture<>() that is never completed.
- The caller performs future.join() (or similar) to wait for the task to finish (common during cleanup) and blocks indefinitely  system shutdown/cleanup hangs.

Alternative reproduction:
shutdown is in progress; caller calls runAfterDelay(...). runAfterDelay returns new SafeFuture<>(). Caller awaits it -> indefinite block.

### Impact

1. Components that wait on the returned futures may hang indefinitely, causing:
2. Node shutdown or restart to never complete (process stuck).
3. Resource leaks or orchestrator-level failures (container not stopping, healthchecks failing).
4. Increased operational burden and incident time-to-recovery.

### PoC

ScheduledExecutorAsyncRunnerTest.java:

```java
@SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
  @Test
  public void runAsync_shouldReturnUncompletedFutureWhenShutdownInProgress() {
    // Arrange
    asyncRunner.shutdown();

    final ExceptionThrowingFutureSupplier<String> action = mock(ExceptionThrowingFutureSupplier.class);

    // Act
    final SafeFuture<String> result = asyncRunner.runAsync(action);

    // Assert
    verify(action, never()).get(); // never executed
    assertThat(result).isNotDone(); // future remains empty / never completes
  }

  @SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
  @Test
  public void runAfterDelay_shouldReturnUncompletedFutureWhenShutdownInProgress() {
    // Arrange
    asyncRunner.shutdown();

    final ExceptionThrowingFutureSupplier<String> action = mock(ExceptionThrowingFutureSupplier.class);

    // Act
    final SafeFuture<String> result = asyncRunner.runAfterDelay(action, Duration.ofMillis(10));

    // Assert
    verify(action, never()).get(); // never executed
    assertThat(result).isNotDone(); // future remains empty / never completes
  }

```

### Mitigation

1. Do not return an uncompleted future. When shutdown is in progress, immediately return a failed future (e.g., RejectedExecutionException) so callers know the action was rejected.
2. Always complete the returned future either with result or exceptionally in all code paths (including shutdown).
3. If ignoring RejectedExecutionException because of shutdown, still complete the SafeFuture exceptionally so callers do not hang.
4. Graceful shutdown: prefer shutdown() followed by a bounded awaitTermination(timeout) before calling shutdownNow() to avoid abruptly cancelling important tasks.

Example minimal patch (fail-fast + complete exceptionally):
```diff
--- a/infrastructure/async/src/main/java/tech/pegasys/teku/infrastructure/async/ScheduledExecutorAsyncRunner.java
+++ b/infrastructure/async/src/main/java/tech/pegasys/teku/infrastructure/async/ScheduledExecutorAsyncRunner.java
@@
   public <U> SafeFuture<U> runAsync(final ExceptionThrowingFutureSupplier<U> action) {
-    if (shutdown.get()) {
-      LOG.debug("Ignoring async task because shutdown is in progress");
-      return new SafeFuture<>();
-    }
-    final SafeFuture<U> result = new SafeFuture<>(); // <==
+    if (shutdown.get()) {
+      LOG.debug("Rejecting async task because shutdown is in progress");
+      return SafeFuture.failedFuture(new RejectedExecutionException("AsyncRunner is shutting down"));
+    }
+    final SafeFuture<U> result = new SafeFuture<>();
     try {
       workerPool.execute(createRunnableForAction(action, result));
     } catch (final Throwable t) {
       handleExecutorError(result, t); // <==
     }
     return result;
   }
@@
   public <U> SafeFuture<U> runAfterDelay(
       final ExceptionThrowingFutureSupplier<U> action, final Duration delay) {
-    if (shutdown.get()) {
-      LOG.debug("Ignoring async task because shutdown is in progress");
-      return new SafeFuture<>(); // <==
-    }
-    final SafeFuture<U> result = new SafeFuture<>(); // <==
+    if (shutdown.get()) {
+      LOG.debug("Rejecting delayed async task because shutdown is in progress");
+      return SafeFuture.failedFuture(new RejectedExecutionException("AsyncRunner is shutting down"));
+    }
+    final SafeFuture<U> result = new SafeFuture<>();
     try {
       scheduler.schedule(
           () -> {
             try {
               workerPool.execute(createRunnableForAction(action, result));
             } catch (final Throwable t) {
               handleExecutorError(result, t);
             }
           },
           delay.toMillis(),
           TimeUnit.MILLISECONDS);
     } catch (final Throwable t) {
       handleExecutorError(result, t); // <==
     }
     return result;
   }
@@
   private <U> void handleExecutorError(final SafeFuture<U> result, final Throwable t) { // <==
-    if (t instanceof RejectedExecutionException && shutdown.get()) {
-      LOG.trace("Ignoring RejectedExecutionException because shutdown is in progress", t);
-    } else {
-      result.completeExceptionally(t);
-    }
+    // Always complete exceptionally so callers don't hang.
+    if (t instanceof RejectedExecutionException && shutdown.get()) {
+      LOG.trace("RejectedExecutionException during shutdown", t);
+    } else {
+      LOG.error("Execution error in ScheduledExecutorAsyncRunner", t);
+    }
+    result.completeExceptionally(t);
   }

```
Additional improvements (recommended)
- Use shutdown() + awaitTermination(timeout) pattern before calling shutdownNow() to attempt graceful completion of running tasks and avoid abrupt cancellations.
- Consider using delay.toNanos() and TimeUnit.NANOSECONDS for more accurate scheduling and to avoid overflow for large durations.
- Consider making thread factory threads daemon (or at least document rationale) to avoid JVM shutdown delays, or ensure explicit lifecycle management.
- Add concurrency tests to ensure no races between shutdown() and run*() calls.

### Summary

There can be a mismatch b/w the actual proposer and computed proposer in flows which internally invoke `get_beacon_proposer_indices` since effective balance updates can occur in between

### Root Cause

The `get_beacon_proposer_indices` computes the proposer indices of the passed in epoch using the relevant formula rather than reading from the cached proposer lookahead array. This function is used in multiple flows where a mistmatch b/w the actual proposer and the computed proposer in this manner can occur

Eg: Data column verification

The `verify_proposer_and_signature` internally invokes the `get_beacon_proposer_indices` function and hence calculates the proposer using the latest effective balance while the actual proposer would've been chosen using the cached proposer_lookahead which uses the effective balance of 1 epoch before

https://github.com/sigp/lighthouse/blob/5928407ce45b539082874ca1f9c5e3e0704f5d85/beacon_node/beacon_chain/src/data_column_verification.rs#L688

```rs
        let epoch = state.current_epoch();
        let proposers = state.get_beacon_proposer_indices(epoch, &chain.spec)?;
```

### Internal Pre-conditions

The effective balance of some validators (those that are involved in the algorithm) should change such that the proposer algorithm picks up a new proposer (eg: if proposer A's effective balance gets increased, then it could be chosen as the proposer now)

### External Pre-conditions

none

### Attack Path

1. At slot == 100 block is produced by proposer A (proposer A was determined based on the proposer_lookahead array which in turn depends on the effective balances as of one epoch ago)
2. The effective balance of another proposer B was increased during the current epoch start causing them to be computed as the beacon proposer inside get_beacon_proposer_indices
3. Now the block won't be finalized since nodes will reject the data column submissions due to `ProposalSignatureInvalid` error

### Impact

Issue is present in lighthouse containing > 33% and hence the chain won't finalize

