		PendingPartialWithdrawals:     pendingPartialWithdrawals,
		PendingConsolidations:         pendingConsolidations,
		ProposerLookahead:             proposerLookahead,
	}

	// Need to cast the beaconState to use in helper functions
	post, err := state_native.InitializeFromProtoUnsafeFulu(s)
	if err != nil {
		return nil, errors.Wrap(err, "failed to initialize post fulu beaconState")
	}
```

(For contrast) DB (de)serialization does enforce the fixed length. On DB read, Prysm first SSZ-unmarshals (which fixes the length) and then calls the unsafe initializer

```go
// beacon-chain/db/kv/state.go
protoState := &ethpb.BeaconStateFulu{}
		if err := protoState.UnmarshalSSZ(enc[len(fuluKey):]); err != nil {
			return nil, errors.Wrap(err, "failed to unmarshal encoding for Fulu")
		}
		ok, err := s.isStateValidatorMigrationOver()
		if err != nil {
			return nil, err
		}
		if ok {
			protoState.Validators = validatorEntries
		}
		return statenative.InitializeFromProtoUnsafeFulu(protoState)
```

SSZ marshal & unmarshal guard the vector at exactly 64 (derived from `2 * SlotsPerEpoch = 2 * 32` at codegen time)

```go
// proto/prysm/v1alpha1/fulu.ssz.go  (Marshal)
if size := len(b.ProposerLookahead); size != 64 {
    err = ssz.ErrVectorLengthFn("--.ProposerLookahead", size, 64)
    return
}

// proto/prysm/v1alpha1/fulu.ssz.go  (Unmarshal)
b.ProposerLookahead = ssz.ExtendUint64(b.ProposerLookahead, 64)
for ii := 0; ii < 64; ii++ { ... }
```

> So: upgrade path = no length check, DB path = checked by SSZ.

## Impact

State root divergence on/after the Fulu upgrade if a mis-sized vector slips in. The Merkle root uses the actual length of the lookahead slice. A wrong length directly changes the field root and thus the overall state root

```go
// beacon-chain/state/stateutil/proposer_lookahead_root.go
func ProposerLookaheadRoot(lookahead []primitives.ValidatorIndex) ([32]byte, error) {
    chunks := make([][32]byte, (len(lookahead)*8+31)/32)          // length drives chunk count
    ...
    return ssz.MerkleizeVector(chunks, uint64(len(chunks))), nil   // and vector size
}
```

…and that field root is included when hashing state fields for Fulu

```go
// beacon-chain/state/state-native/hasher.go
proposerLookaheadRoot, err := stateutil.ProposerLookaheadRoot(state.proposerLookahead)
...
fieldRoots[types.ProposerLookahead.RealPosition()] = proposerLookaheadRoot[:]

```

The result is a client that (by design or by chance) enforces the invariant will reject the state. Prysm (via the unsafe upgrade path) would accept it, creating a cross-client split potential.

Downstream logic assumes the length is fixed. Indexing into the lookahead (e.g., computing proposer for future slots) implicitly relies on the expected size. A shorter or longer slice can cause wrong proposer selection or later panics in code that expects a full window.

Today, the generator builds exactly `(MinSeedLookahead+1) * SlotsPerEpoch` entries:

```go
// beacon-chain/core/helpers/beacon_committee.go
lookAhead := make([]uint64, 0, uint64(params.BeaconConfig().MinSeedLookahead+1)*uint64(params.BeaconConfig().SlotsPerEpoch))
for i := range params.BeaconConfig().MinSeedLookahead + 1 {
    proposerIndices, err := PrecomputeProposerIndices(state, indices, epoch+i)
    ...
    for _, proposerIndex := range proposerIndices {
        lookAhead = append(lookAhead, uint64(proposerIndex))
    }
}

// PrecomputeProposerIndices always returns exactly SlotsPerEpoch items
proposerIndices := make([]primitives.ValidatorIndex, params.BeaconConfig().SlotsPerEpoch)

```

That makes a mis-size unlikely today, but the upgrade path’s lack of validation is still a consensus foot-gun. A future refactor, config mismatch, or test-net experiments could introduce the wrong length, and it would slip through upgrade silently


## POC
Place test in `getters_setters_lookahead_test.go` 
```go
