## Recommendation
Add a size check in `InitializeFromProtoUnsafeFulu`. Before building the `BeaconState`, assert:

```csharp
expected := int(params.BeaconConfig().SlotsPerEpoch) * int(params.BeaconConfig().MinSeedLookahead+1)
if len(st.ProposerLookahead) != expected { return nil, errors.New("invalid proposer lookahead length") }
```

This keeps the speed (no deep validation) but locks in the consensus‑critical invariant.

## Summary

An early non atomic pre-check (`isFirstValidForSlotProposerIndexAndColumnIndex`) allows two concurrent validation calls for the same tuple to both proceed into the heavy proof/KZG path.
Concurrent threads will cause duplicate expensive validation work for the same `DataColumnSidecar`, impacting the computation usage.

## Root Cause

In`validate`, before any heavy checks, the code does:
https://github.com/Consensys/teku/blob/1e30a468b859af66aa5db647fedc648f74d69c7e/ethereum/statetransition/src/main/java/tech/pegasys/teku/statetransition/validation/DataColumnSidecarGossipValidator.java#L204-L208

```java
    if (!isFirstValidForSlotProposerIndexAndColumnIndex(dataColumnSidecar, blockHeader)) {
      LOG.trace(
          "DataColumnSidecar is not the first valid for its slot and index. It will be dropped.");
      return completedFuture(InternalValidationResult.IGNORE);
    }
```


`isFirstValidForSlotProposerIndexAndColumnIndex` is a `contains` on
receivedValidDataColumnSidecarInfoSet:

```
  private boolean isFirstValidForSlotProposerIndexAndColumnIndex(
      final DataColumnSidecar dataColumnSidecar, final BeaconBlockHeader blockHeader) {
    return !receivedValidDataColumnSidecarInfoSet.contains(
        new SlotProposerIndexAndColumnIndex(
            blockHeader.getSlot(), blockHeader.getProposerIndex(), dataColumnSidecar.getIndex()));
  }
```

Then, the validator performs the expensive operations:
- verifying the sidecar’s inclusion proof (`verifyDataColumnSidecarInclusionProof`)
- verifying KZG proofs (`miscHelpersFulu.verifyDataColumnSidecarKzgProofs(kzg, dataColumnSidecar)`)
- and checking proposer/signature validity

Finally there is a final `add` which enforces uniqueness, but the wasted work has already happened.

```java
    if (!receivedValidDataColumnSidecarInfoSet.add(
        new SlotProposerIndexAndColumnIndex(
            blockHeader.getSlot(), blockHeader.getProposerIndex(), dataColumnSidecar.getIndex()))) {
      return SafeFuture.completedFuture(
          ignore(
              "DataColumnSidecar is not the first valid for its slot and index. It will be dropped."));
    }
```


Because the early check is a separate `contains` and is not atomic with `add`, two concurrent validations can both pass the pre-check and run all expensive work, with only one ultimately being accepted at the final `add`.

The early `isFirstValidForSlotProposerIndexAndColumnIndex` pre-check at the top of `validate` is redundant: it introduces a race and extra work without having any impact on correctness.

## Internal Pre-conditions

- 2+ threads within the same process concurrently call the validator for the same `DataColumnSidecar` key ( i.e.  same slot, proposer and columnIndex).
- The early pre-check returns `false` for both callers - i.e. no prior acceptance recorded.
- Both threads proceed to the expensive verification path concurrently.
- One thread finishes the final `add` earlier and succeeds (`ACCEPT`); the other thread later performs `add` and loses (IGNORE).

## External Pre-conditions

None

## Attack Path
- 2+ peers gossip the exact same `DataColumnSidecar` to the node at nearly the same time.
- Teku’s GossipSub handler enqueues one validation task per inbound peer. Both tasks target the same (slot, proposer_index, column_index, blockRoot) key and run on separate executor threads.
- Each task calls `isFirstValidForSlotProposerIndexAndColumnIndex`. Since neither has yet inserted the key into `receivedValidDataColumnSidecarInfoSet`, both see it is not present and proceed.
- Both tasks independently run the expensive checks: verifying the inclusion proof, running KZG proof verification, and other validations.
- The first task to complete inserts the key into `receivedValidDataColumnSidecarInfoSet.add`. That call succeeds, and the sidecar is marked `ACCEPTED`.
- The second task reaches the same `add` call. It now returns false as the key already exists. That task exits with `IGNORE`.
- The client wasted CPU cycles: both tasks paid the cost of heavy cryptographic checks when only one result was ever usable.


## Impact

Wasted CPU work due to the duplicate expensive KZG/proof verification, and slightly worse latency.


## PoC

Paste this test, which reproduces the steps described in the attack path, in `https://github.com/Consensys/teku/blob/1e30a468b859af66aa5db647fedc648f74d69c7e/ethereum/statetransition/src/test/java/tech/pegasys/teku/statetransition/validation/`

Run with `./gradlew :ethereum:statetransition:test`.

The `kzgCalls == 2` assertion proves duplicate expensive work occurred

```java
