### Mitigation

Update Erigon’s EstimateGas logic to align with consensus rules defined in EIP-7825. Specifically, after computing hi (the binary search upper bound), introduce a fork-aware cap.

### Summary

Uncaught KZG exception handling inconsistency will cause a consensus client crash for Ethereum beacon node operators as a malicious proposer will submit a block with corrupted data column proofs that reach block verification.


### Root Cause

In packages/beacon-node/src/chain/validation/dataColumnSidecar.ts the block validation helper `validateDataColumnsSidecars` forwards aggregated column data to `kzg.asyncVerifyCellKzgProofBatch` and re-throws the raw exception instead of converting it into a handled `DataColumnSidecarError`. Unlike the gossip validation path (which wraps errors in `DataColumnSidecarGossipError` per https://github.com/ethereum/consensus-specs/blob/340d23358a0cdb4f4b547226dadd36d1cf775f20/specs/fulu/p2p-interface.md#verify_data_column_sidecar_kzg_proofs), this inconsistency lets malformed proofs crash block verification invoked by verifyBlocksDataAvailability.


### Internal Pre-conditions

1. [Beacon proposer needs to win a slot] Slot owner produces a block that references blob KZG commitments covering the malformed data column proofs.
2. [Malicious proposer needs to craft KZG inputs] Malicious block builder mutates the blob proof bytes so that `kzg.asyncVerifyCellKzgProofBatch` rejects them while the header and commitment hashes remain consistent.

### External Pre-conditions

1. [PeerDAS network needs standard operation] Gossip and req/resp dissemination allow the malformed block to reach the target beacon node before fork choice finalizes a conflicting block.

### Attack Path

1. Malicious proposer constructs a validly signed block whose `blobKzgCommitments` match the block body but whose associated data column sidecars have corrupted `kzgProofs` values.
2. The proposer (or builder) submits the block to the beacon network; honest nodes import the payload and call `verifyBlocksDataAvailability`.
3. `verifyBlocksDataAvailability` invokes `validateDataColumnsSidecars`, which aggregates the corrupted proofs and calls `kzg.asyncVerifyCellKzgProofBatch`.
4. The KZG batch verifier throws an exception; because the exception is re-thrown as a raw `Error`, the process terminates instead of returning a handled rejection, crashing the beacon node.


### Impact

The beacon node process terminates causing the operator to miss attestations, sync committees, and proposer duties until manual recovery. Attack profitability is griefing-focused—the attacker forfeits the slot’s rewards but can repeatedly deny service as long as they control block construction for won slots.


### PoC

Run commands:
- `yarn vitest run --project=unit packages/beacon-node/test/unit/chain/validation/poc_uncaught_kzg_exception_in_block_verification.test.ts`

