```


### Mitigation

- Enforce versioned-hash comparison and `verify_kzg_for_data_column_list` at the adapter boundary before wrapping custody columns, rejecting EL responses that fail the check.
- Refine typing so that only verified custody columns can be published (e.g., separate `Unverified` vs `KzgVerified` variants) to prevent mocks from bypassing guards.
- Update tests: keep this canary but expect the publish to be blocked once guards exist, and add integration coverage that ensures swapped EL answers surface a clear verification error without side effects.
- Emit telemetry when EL responses violate expectations so operators can detect misbehaving relays.

### Summary

Missing gossip-equivalent validation and EL response hash verification in getDataColumnsFromExecution lets a compromised execution engine return tampered blobs that the beacon node republishes without verification. Peers still run gossip validation and drop the invalid sidecars, so network integrity remains intact, but this path wastes bandwidth/CPU and opens a localized liveness degradation DoS vector.

### Root Cause

In `packages/beacon-node/src/util/dataColumns.ts::getDataColumnsFromExecution` the client reuses blob data from the execution layer without first re-running the gossip validation pipeline (`validateDataColumnsSidecars` / `verifyDataColumnSidecar`) before invoking `ChainEvent.publishDataColumns`. The same function also trusts `executionEngine.getBlobs` responses without asserting that returned blobs still match the `versionedHashes` derived from the requested KZG commitments. The Fulu Distributed Blob Publishing specification states that clients must apply the same validation and anti-equivocation protections as the gossip path and stop importing when the EL returns a subset or mismatch of blobs (`ERR_EL_BLOB_MISSING`); skipping those checks before publish violates that parity and lets tampered payloads propagate.

```ts
// packages/beacon-node/src/util/dataColumns.ts::getDataColumnsFromExecution (excerpt)
const versionedHashes: Uint8Array[] = commitments.map(kzgCommitmentToVersionedHash);

// Get blobs from execution engine
metrics?.peerDas.getBlobsV2Requests.inc();
const timer = metrics?.peerDas.getBlobsV2RequestDuration.startTimer();
const blobs = await executionEngine.getBlobs(blockCache.fork, versionedHashes);
timer?.();

// Execution engine was unable to find one or more blobs
if (blobs === null) {
  return false;
}
metrics?.peerDas.getBlobsV2Responses.inc();

// Publish columns if and only if subscribed to them
const sampledColumns = custodyConfig.sampledColumns.map((columnIndex) => dataColumnSidecars[columnIndex]);

// for columns that we already seen, it will be ignored through `ignoreDuplicatePublishError` gossip option
emitter.emit(ChainEvent.publishDataColumns, sampledColumns);
```

### Internal Pre-conditions

1. The beacon node runs Fulu with PeerDAS enabled and relies on `getDataColumnsFromExecution` to backfill missing sampled columns from the execution engine.
2. The node has a populated `custodyConfig.sampledColumns` set and observes a block whose required columns are still absent from `blockCache.cachedData.dataColumnsCache`.
3. The local execution engine connection is considered trusted by configuration so the client automatically republishes EL-provided data.

### External Pre-conditions

1. The connected execution engine instance (or the host running it) is malicious or compromised and can forge blob payloads or swap data after commitments are calculated.
2. Network peers accept published columns from this beacon node, expecting them to have passed the standard gossip validation pipeline.

### Attack Path

1. The attacker compromises the local execution engine and waits for the beacon node to process a Fulu block that lacks all sampled data columns.
2. When `getDataColumnsFromExecution` requests blobs via `executionEngine.getBlobs`, the malicious EL returns tampered blob contents and mismatched proofs while still acknowledging the request.
3. Because the beacon node omits `verifyDataColumnSidecar` checks and does not compare returned blobs against the requested versioned hashes, it emits `ChainEvent.publishDataColumns` with the attacker-controlled payloads.
4. Honest peers receive invalid columns from an ostensibly honest publisher, waste resources attempting to validate them, and discard them, reducing availability for attesters and exposing a denial-of-service vector.

### Impact

Peers continue to enforce gossip validation, so the protocol’s global safety stays intact even if a beacon node republishes tampered columns. However, malicious EL responses force honest peers to spend bandwidth and CPU on invalid payloads and can delay data availability for the affected slot, creating a DoS angle against local liveness and attester readiness. Under Sherlock’s severity matrix this is **Medium severity (Impact: medium due to resource exhaustion and localized liveness degradation; Likelihood: medium because an attacker can point their node at a malicious or compromised EL).**

### PoC

### Unit PoC – missing validation before publish
`packages/beacon-node/test/unit/util/poc_get_data_columns_from_execution_missing_validation.test.ts`

```bash
yarn vitest run packages/beacon-node/test/unit/util/poc_get_data_columns_from_execution_missing_validation.test.ts
```

```ts
import {afterEach, beforeEach, describe, expect, it, vi} from "vitest";
import {createChainForkConfig, defaultChainConfig} from "@lodestar/config";
import {ChainForkConfig} from "@lodestar/config";
import {ForkName} from "@lodestar/params";
import {deneb, fulu, ssz} from "@lodestar/types";
import {fromHex} from "@lodestar/utils";

import {ChainEvent, ChainEventEmitter} from "../../../src/chain/emitter.js";
import {getEmptyBlockInputCacheEntry} from "../../../src/chain/seenCache/seenGossipBlockInput.js";
import {BlockInputCacheType} from "../../../src/chain/seenCache/seenGossipBlockInput.js";
import {CustodyConfig, getDataColumnsFromExecution} from "../../../src/util/dataColumns.js";
import {kzg} from "../../../src/util/kzg.js";
import type {IExecutionEngine} from "../../../src/execution/engine/interface.js";
import {generateRandomBlob, transactionForKzgCommitment} from "../../utils/kzg.js";
import {validateDataColumnsSidecars} from "../../../src/chain/validation/dataColumnSidecar.js";

/**
 * Vulnerability: getDataColumnsFromExecution bypasses the gossip validation pipeline
 * when publishing EL-sourced columns. The function emits data columns without invoking
 * verifyDataColumnSidecar checks that would normally guarantee structural and cryptographic
 * soundness.
 *
 * Attack Vector: A malicious execution engine can supply tampered column payloads that are
 * forwarded to the network, while downstream verification rejects them.
 */
describe("PoC: getDataColumnsFromExecution publishes columns without validation", () => {
  let config: ChainForkConfig;
  let custodyConfig: CustodyConfig;
  let emitter: ChainEventEmitter;
  let blockCache: BlockInputCacheType;

  beforeEach(() => {
    config = createChainForkConfig({
      ...defaultChainConfig,
      ALTAIR_FORK_EPOCH: 0,
      BELLATRIX_FORK_EPOCH: 0,
      CAPELLA_FORK_EPOCH: 0,
      DENEB_FORK_EPOCH: 0,
      ELECTRA_FORK_EPOCH: 0,
      FULU_FORK_EPOCH: 0,
      SAMPLES_PER_SLOT: 4,
      CUSTODY_REQUIREMENT: 4,
    });

    const nodeId = fromHex("cdbee32dc3c50e9711d22be5565c7e44ff6108af663b2dc5abd2df573d2fa83f");
    custodyConfig = new CustodyConfig({nodeId, config});
    expect(custodyConfig.sampledColumns.length).toBeGreaterThan(0);

    emitter = new ChainEventEmitter();
    blockCache = getEmptyBlockInputCacheEntry(ForkName.fulu, 1);
  });

  afterEach(() => {
    vi.restoreAllMocks();
  });

  function buildFuluBlock(commitments: deneb.KZGCommitment[]): fulu.SignedBeaconBlock {
    const signedBlock = ssz.fulu.SignedBeaconBlock.defaultValue();
    signedBlock.message.slot = 1;
    signedBlock.message.body.blobKzgCommitments.length = 0;
    signedBlock.message.body.executionPayload.transactions.length = 0;

    for (const commitment of commitments) {
      signedBlock.message.body.blobKzgCommitments.push(commitment);
      signedBlock.message.body.executionPayload.transactions.push(transactionForKzgCommitment(commitment));
    }

    return signedBlock;
  }

  it("poc_get_data_columns_from_execution_missing_validation: publishes invalid columns without running verification", async () => {
    const blob = generateRandomBlob();
    const commitment = kzg.blobToKzgCommitment(blob);
    const signedBlock = buildFuluBlock([commitment]);
    blockCache.block = signedBlock;

    const {proofs} = kzg.computeCellsAndKzgProofs(blob);
    const tamperedBlob = blob.slice();
    const tamperedView = new DataView(tamperedBlob.buffer, tamperedBlob.byteOffset, tamperedBlob.byteLength);
    const originalElement = tamperedView.getUint32(0);
    tamperedView.setUint32(0, originalElement + 1);

    const executionEngine = {
      // Returns blob data that no longer matches the accompanying proofs.
      getBlobs: vi.fn().mockResolvedValue([{blob: tamperedBlob, proofs}]),
    } as unknown as IExecutionEngine;

    const emitSpy = vi.spyOn(emitter, "emit");

    const result = await getDataColumnsFromExecution(
      config,
      custodyConfig,
      executionEngine,
      emitter,
      blockCache,
      null
    );

    expect(result).toBe(true);
    expect(executionEngine.getBlobs).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(1);
    expect(emitSpy).toHaveBeenCalledWith(ChainEvent.publishDataColumns, expect.any(Array));

    const emittedColumns = emitSpy.mock.calls[0][1] as fulu.DataColumnSidecars;
    expect(emittedColumns.length).toBe(custodyConfig.sampledColumns.length);

    const blockRoot = ssz.fulu.BeaconBlock.hashTreeRoot(signedBlock.message);
    await expect(
      validateDataColumnsSidecars(
        signedBlock.message.slot,
        blockRoot,
        signedBlock.message.body.blobKzgCommitments,
        emittedColumns,
        null
      )
    ).rejects.toThrow(/Invalid data column sidecars/);
  });

});
```

### Unit PoC – missing response hash verification
`packages/beacon-node/test/unit/util/poc_get_data_columns_from_execution_blob_hash_mismatch.test.ts`

```bash
yarn vitest run packages/beacon-node/test/unit/util/poc_get_data_columns_from_execution_blob_hash_mismatch.test.ts
```

```ts
import {beforeEach, describe, expect, it, vi} from "vitest";
import {createChainForkConfig, defaultChainConfig, type ChainForkConfig} from "@lodestar/config";
import {ForkName} from "@lodestar/params";
import {fulu, ssz} from "@lodestar/types";
import {fromHex} from "@lodestar/utils";

import {ChainEvent, ChainEventEmitter} from "../../../src/chain/emitter.js";
import {getEmptyBlockInputCacheEntry} from "../../../src/chain/seenCache/seenGossipBlockInput.js";
import type {BlockInputCacheType} from "../../../src/chain/seenCache/seenGossipBlockInput.js";
import {CustodyConfig, getDataColumnsFromExecution} from "../../../src/util/dataColumns.js";
import {kzg} from "../../../src/util/kzg.js";
import type {IExecutionEngine} from "../../../src/execution/engine/interface.js";
import {generateRandomBlob, transactionForKzgCommitment} from "../../utils/kzg.js";
import {validateDataColumnsSidecars} from "../../../src/chain/validation/dataColumnSidecar.js";
import {kzgCommitmentToVersionedHash} from "../../../src/util/blobs.js";

/**
 * Vulnerability: getDataColumnsFromExecution trusts execution engine blob responses without
 * verifying that returned blobs match the requested versioned hashes computed earlier.
 *
 * Attack Vector: A malicious execution engine can provide arbitrary blob contents that do not
 * correspond to the requested commitments, leading the beacon node to publish invalid data columns
 * to the network while downstream validation fails.
 */

describe("PoC: getDataColumnsFromExecution EL response validation bypass", () => {
  let config: ChainForkConfig;
  let custodyConfig: CustodyConfig;
  let blockCache: BlockInputCacheType;
  let emitter: ChainEventEmitter;
  let originalBlob: Uint8Array;

  beforeEach(() => {
    config = createChainForkConfig({
      ...defaultChainConfig,
      ALTAIR_FORK_EPOCH: 0,
      BELLATRIX_FORK_EPOCH: 0,
      CAPELLA_FORK_EPOCH: 0,
      DENEB_FORK_EPOCH: 0,
      ELECTRA_FORK_EPOCH: 0,
      FULU_FORK_EPOCH: 0,
      SAMPLES_PER_SLOT: 4,
      CUSTODY_REQUIREMENT: 4,
    });

    const nodeId = fromHex("cdbee32dc3c50e9711d22be5565c7e44ff6108af663b2dc5abd2df573d2fa83f");
    custodyConfig = new CustodyConfig({nodeId, config});
    emitter = new ChainEventEmitter();
    blockCache = getEmptyBlockInputCacheEntry(ForkName.fulu, 1);

    originalBlob = generateRandomBlob();
    const block = buildFuluBlock(config, [originalBlob]);
    blockCache.block = block;
  });

  function buildFuluBlock(cfg: ChainForkConfig, blobs: Uint8Array[]): fulu.SignedBeaconBlock {
    const block = ssz.fulu.SignedBeaconBlock.defaultValue();
    block.message.slot = 1;
    block.message.body.blobKzgCommitments.length = 0;
    block.message.body.executionPayload.transactions.length = 0;

    for (const blob of blobs) {
      const commitment = kzg.blobToKzgCommitment(blob);
      block.message.body.blobKzgCommitments.push(commitment);
      block.message.body.executionPayload.transactions.push(transactionForKzgCommitment(commitment));
    }

    return block;
  }

  it("poc_get_data_columns_from_execution_blob_hash_mismatch: publishes mismatch without verifying versioned hash", async () => {
    if (!blockCache.block) {
      throw new Error("expected block setup");
    }

    const requestedCommitment = blockCache.block.message.body.blobKzgCommitments[0];
    const requestedHash = kzgCommitmentToVersionedHash(requestedCommitment);

    const maliciousBlob = originalBlob.slice();
    const maliciousView = new DataView(maliciousBlob.buffer, maliciousBlob.byteOffset, maliciousBlob.byteLength);
    const originalElement = maliciousView.getUint32(0);
    maliciousView.setUint32(0, originalElement + 1);

    const maliciousCommitment = kzg.blobToKzgCommitment(maliciousBlob);
    const maliciousProofs = kzg.computeCellsAndKzgProofs(maliciousBlob).proofs;

    let capturedVersionedHashes: Uint8Array[] | null = null;
    const executionEngine = {
      getBlobs: vi.fn().mockImplementation(async (_fork, versionedHashes) => {
        capturedVersionedHashes = versionedHashes;
        return [{blob: maliciousBlob, proofs: maliciousProofs}];
      }),
    } as unknown as IExecutionEngine;

    const emitSpy = vi.spyOn(emitter, "emit");

    const result = await getDataColumnsFromExecution(
      config,
      custodyConfig,
      executionEngine,
      emitter,
      blockCache,
      null
    );

    expect(result).toBe(true);
    expect(executionEngine.getBlobs).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(1);
    expect(capturedVersionedHashes).not.toBeNull();
    expect(Array.from(capturedVersionedHashes![0])).toEqual(Array.from(requestedHash));

    const maliciousHash = kzgCommitmentToVersionedHash(maliciousCommitment);
    expect(Array.from(capturedVersionedHashes![0])).not.toEqual(Array.from(maliciousHash));

    expect(emitSpy).toHaveBeenCalledWith(ChainEvent.publishDataColumns, expect.any(Array));

    const emittedColumns = emitSpy.mock.calls[0][1] as fulu.DataColumnSidecars;
    const blockRoot = ssz.fulu.BeaconBlock.hashTreeRoot(blockCache.block.message);

    await expect(
      validateDataColumnsSidecars(
        blockCache.block.message.slot,
        blockRoot,
        blockCache.block.message.body.blobKzgCommitments,
        emittedColumns,
        null
      )
    ).rejects.toThrow(/Invalid data column sidecars/);
  });
});
```

### Mitigation

Add verification parity with the gossip pipeline before emitting EL-sourced columns: recompute hashes and run `validateDataColumnsSidecars` / `verifyDataColumnSidecar` on each column, dropping the batch if any proof or commitment mismatch arises. Additionally, compare each blob returned by `executionEngine.getBlobs` against the requested `versionedHashes` (e.g., re-derive the KZG commitment and hash) and treat mismatches as `ERR_EL_BLOB_MISSING`, ensuring the node refuses to publish unverified data.

### Summary

Both Teku and Prysm still hard-code BLOB_SCHEDULE entries to contain only EPOCH and MAX_BLOBS_PER_BLOCK. When the canonical Fusaka/BPO config introduces the spec-required TARGET_BLOBS_PER_BLOCK and BASE_FEE_UPDATE_FRACTION fields (EIP-7892), each client aborts while parsing the schedule. Together they account for ~52 % of validators, so publishing the official configuration or activating the next BPO causes a >33 % validator outage.

### Root Cause

- **Teku:** SpecConfigReader.blobScheduleFromList throws if any map has keys other than EPOCH and MAX_BLOBS_PER_BLOCK, leading to an IllegalArgumentException.

- **Prysm:** yaml.UnmarshalStrict populates BeaconChainConfig.BlobSchedule, whose entries only define those two legacy fields. The strict decoder raises an "unknown field" error as soon as the schedule includes TARGET_BLOBS_PER_BLOCK or BASE_FEE_UPDATE_FRACTION.

https://github.com/Consensys/teku/blob/53e35b6d78dddd7cb4c53302d10b9efaa03efffe/ethereum/spec/src/main/java/tech/pegasys/teku/spec/config/SpecConfigReader.java#L265-L285

https://github.com/OffchainLabs/prysm/blob/02dca852516553d88a3140d8ba3ac4362137aa71/config/params/loader.go#L56

https://github.com/OffchainLabs/prysm/blob/02dca852516553d88a3140d8ba3ac4362137aa71/config/params/config.go#L351-L358

### Internal Pre-conditions

- Teku or Prysm must ingest a network configuration that contains a BLOB_SCHEDULE.

### External Pre-conditions

- The network (or local operator) supplies a spec-compliant Fusaka/BPO schedule containing the additional fields mandated by EIP-7892—exactly what future mainnet configs will do.

### Attack Path

1. Publish or load the official Fusaka configuration with the augmented BLOB_SCHEDULE.
2. During startup, Teku throws IllegalArgumentException: Map does not look like a blob schedule; Prysm's strict YAML loader errors with "unknown field TARGET_BLOBS_PER_BLOCK".
3. Both clients exit before reaching steady state, taking ~52 % of validators offline.

### Impact

Validator operators on Teku (~21 %) and Prysm (~31 %) cannot start their beacon nodes. An adversary (or simply the scheduled upgrade) knocks out >33 % of validators, meeting the contest's High severity threshold.

### PoC

```java
// TekuBpoSchedulePoC.java
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.LinkedHashMap;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.Map;

public class TekuBpoSchedulePoC {

  private record BlobScheduleEntry(String epoch, String maxBlobsPerBlock) {}

  @SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
  private static Object blobScheduleFromList(final Object o) {
    final List<BlobScheduleEntry> blobSchedule = new ArrayList<>();
    final List<?> schedule = (List<?>) o;
    for (Object entry : schedule) {
      if (entry instanceof Map) {
        final Map<String, String> data = (Map<String, String>) entry;
        if (!data.containsKey("EPOCH")
            || !data.containsKey("MAX_BLOBS_PER_BLOCK")
            || data.size() != 2) {
          throw new IllegalArgumentException("Map does not look like a blob schedule");
        }
        blobSchedule.add(
            new BlobScheduleEntry(data.get("EPOCH"), data.get("MAX_BLOBS_PER_BLOCK")));
      } else {
        throw new IllegalArgumentException("Could not parse entry blob schedule");
      }
    }
    return blobSchedule;
  }

  public static void main(String[] args) {
    Map<String, String> minimalEntry = new LinkedHashMap<>();
    minimalEntry.put("EPOCH", "1024");
    minimalEntry.put("MAX_BLOBS_PER_BLOCK", "18");

    Map<String, String> specEntry = new LinkedHashMap<>();
    specEntry.put("EPOCH", "1024");
    specEntry.put("MAX_BLOBS_PER_BLOCK", "18");
    specEntry.put("TARGET_BLOBS_PER_BLOCK", "12");
    specEntry.put("BASE_FEE_UPDATE_FRACTION", "5007716");

    System.out.println("=== Parsing minimal (legacy) entry ===");
    blobScheduleFromList(List.of(minimalEntry));
    System.out.println("Parsed successfully\n");

    System.out.println("=== Parsing spec-compliant entry with additional fields ===");
    try {
      blobScheduleFromList(List.of(specEntry));
      System.out.println("Parsed successfully (unexpected)");
    } catch (IllegalArgumentException e) {
      e.printStackTrace(System.out);
    }
  }
}
```

## Run instructions

1. `javac TekuBpoSchedulePoC.java`
2. `java TekuBpoSchedulePoC`

