### Mitigation

- Update Teku's loader to accept all EIP-7892 fields, propagate them through the fork schedule, and ignore unknown keys rather than throwing.

- Extend Prysm's BlobScheduleEntry (and associated validation) to handle the new parameters, replacing the strict two-key check with schema-aware parsing.

### Summary

Nethermind's block production path lacks EIP-7934 block size validation, while the sync path correctly enforces it. This allows attackers to spam transactions, causing Nethermind execution clients (approximately 38% of the network, according to the statistics in the contest rule) to produce oversized blocks that are rejected by the network, resulting in missed block proposals for validators using Nethermind.

### Root Cause

The block validation logic has two separate paths:

1. Sync path (`ValidateSuggestedBlock`): Contains EIP-7934 size check

```csharp
int encodedSize = block.EncodedSize ?? _blockDecoder.GetLength(block, RlpBehaviors.None);
if (spec.IsEip7934Enabled && encodedSize > spec.Eip7934MaxRlpBlockSize)
{
    if (_logger.IsDebug) _logger.Debug($"{Invalid(block)} RLP encoded size of {encodedSize} bytes exceeds the max limit of {spec.Eip7934MaxRlpBlockSize} bytes");
    errorMessage = BlockErrorMessages.ExceededBlockSizeLimit(spec.Eip7934MaxRlpBlockSize);
    return false;
}
```

Lines of code: https://github.com/NethermindEth/nethermind/blob/babc3c4fa48a313bf76d2f4de3ed3983023b08a0/src/Nethermind/Nethermind.Consensus/Validators/BlockValidator.cs#L60-L136

2. Production path (`ValidateProcessedBlock`): No size validation

```csharp
public bool ValidateProcessedBlock(Block processedBlock, TxReceipt[] receipts, Block suggestedBlock, out string? error)
{
    if (processedBlock.Header.Hash == suggestedBlock.Header.Hash)
    {
        error = null;
        return true;  // No size check performed
    }
    // Only checks state root, gas used, bloom, etc.
}
```

Lines of code: https://github.com/NethermindEth/nethermind/blob/babc3c4fa48a313bf76d2f4de3ed3983023b08a0/src/Nethermind/Nethermind.Consensus/Validators/BlockValidator.cs#L149-L232

### Internal Pre-conditions

1. EIP-7934 (Osaka fork) is activated
2. Node is configured as a block validator (with ETH staked)

### External Pre-conditions

1. The attacker can submit transactions to Nethermind's transaction pool
2. Block production is triggered (validator's turn to propose)

### Attack Path

1. Attacker floods Nethermind's transaction pool with large transactions (e.g., large calldata with very high base fee and gas tip)
2. Block production call stack: [BlockProducerBase's BuildBlock](https://github.com/NethermindEth/nethermind/blob/babc3c4fa48a313bf76d2f4de3ed3983023b08a0/src/Nethermind/Nethermind.Consensus/StandardBlockProducerRunner.cs#L36) → [BlockProducerBase's TryProduceNewBlock](https://github.com/NethermindEth/nethermind/blob/babc3c4fa48a313bf76d2f4de3ed3983023b08a0/src/Nethermind/Nethermind.Consensus/Producers/BlockProducerBase.cs#L88) → [BlockProducerBase's ProduceNewBlock](https://github.com/NethermindEth/nethermind/blob/babc3c4fa48a313bf76d2f4de3ed3983023b08a0/src/Nethermind/Nethermind.Consensus/Producers/BlockProducerBase.cs#L121) → [BlockProducerBase's ProcessPreparedBlock](https://github.com/NethermindEth/nethermind/blob/babc3c4fa48a313bf76d2f4de3ed3983023b08a0/src/Nethermind/Nethermind.Consensus/Producers/BlockProducerBase.cs#L140) → [BlockchainProcessor's Process](https://github.com/NethermindEth/nethermind/blob/babc3c4fa48a313bf76d2f4de3ed3983023b08a0/src/Nethermind/Nethermind.Consensus/Producers/BlockProducerBase.cs#L193) → [BlockchainProcessor's ProcessBranch](https://github.com/NethermindEth/nethermind/blob/babc3c4fa48a313bf76d2f4de3ed3983023b08a0/src/Nethermind/Nethermind.Consensus/Processing/BlockchainProcessor.cs#L462) → [BranchProcessor's Process](https://github.com/NethermindEth/nethermind/blob/babc3c4fa48a313bf76d2f4de3ed3983023b08a0/src/Nethermind/Nethermind.Consensus/Processing/BlockchainProcessor.cs#L559) → BlockProcessor's ProcessOne ([here](https://github.com/NethermindEth/nethermind/blob/babc3c4fa48a313bf76d2f4de3ed3983023b08a0/src/Nethermind/Nethermind.Consensus/Processing/BranchProcessor.cs#L121) or [here](https://github.com/NethermindEth/nethermind/blob/babc3c4fa48a313bf76d2f4de3ed3983023b08a0/src/Nethermind/Nethermind.Consensus/Processing/BranchProcessor.cs#L133)) → [BlockProcessor's ValidateProcessedBlock](https://github.com/NethermindEth/nethermind/blob/babc3c4fa48a313bf76d2f4de3ed3983023b08a0/src/Nethermind/Nethermind.Consensus/Processing/BlockProcessor.cs#L63) → [BlockValidator's ValidateProcessedBlock](https://github.com/NethermindEth/nethermind/blob/babc3c4fa48a313bf76d2f4de3ed3983023b08a0/src/Nethermind/Nethermind.Consensus/Processing/BlockProcessor.cs#L74) (no block size check as per [implementation](https://github.com/NethermindEth/nethermind/blob/babc3c4fa48a313bf76d2f4de3ed3983023b08a0/src/Nethermind/Nethermind.Consensus/Validators/BlockValidator.cs#L149-L232))
3. Nethermind execution client produces oversized block
4. Consensus client receives the block via Engine API
5. Two possible scenarios:
   * Scenario A: Consensus client trusts execution client,  signs and broadcasts the invalid block → Other nodes' execution clients reject it during sync → Block is not included in canonical chain → Invalid transactions remain in the pool, causing repeated failures in subsequent block proposals
   * Scenario B: Consensus client performs additional validation and rejects the block → Validator fails to propose any block → Invalid transactions remain in the pool, causing repeated failures in subsequent block proposals
6. Since the flooded transactions are not removed from the transaction pool (they appear valid to Nethermind), the validator will repeatedly fail to produce valid blocks every time it's selected to propose, until the transactions expire or are manually removed (e.g., by node operators)

### Impact

1. Validator Penalties: 38% (as the statistics in the contest rule) of validators (Nethermind nodes) fail to produce valid blocks
2. Network Degradation: Reduced block production rate during attacks, affecting the total network throughput due to empty slots
3. Economic Loss: Affected validators lose block rewards

### PoC

Add this test to the [`BlockValidatorTests`](https://github.com/NethermindEth/nethermind/blob/babc3c4fa48a313bf76d2f4de3ed3983023b08a0/src/Nethermind/Nethermind.Blockchain.Test/Validators/BlockValidatorTests.cs#L20) test class of [`BlockValidatorTests.cs`](https://github.com/NethermindEth/nethermind/blob/babc3c4fa48a313bf76d2f4de3ed3983023b08a0/src/Nethermind/Nethermind.Blockchain.Test/Validators/BlockValidatorTests.cs) (e.g., behind existing tests) to demonstrate the vulnerability:

```csharp
[Test]
public void ValidateProcessedBlock_MissesEip7934BlockSizeValidation_Vulnerability()
{
    // Setup - EIP-7934 enabled
    ISpecProvider specProvider = new CustomSpecProvider(((ForkActivation)0, Osaka.Instance));
    BlockValidator validator = new(
        new TxValidator(TestBlockchainIds.ChainId),
        Always.Valid,
        Always.Valid,
        specProvider,
        LimboLogs.Instance);

    BlockHeader parent = Build.A.BlockHeader.TestObject;
    Block oversizedBlock = Build.A.Block
        .WithParent(parent)
        .WithEncodedSize(Eip7934Constants.DefaultMaxRlpBlockSize + 1) // Oversized block
        .TestObject;

    // Sync path correctly rejects oversized blocks
    bool syncResult = validator.ValidateSuggestedBlock(oversizedBlock, parent, out string? syncError);
    Assert.That(syncResult, Is.False);
    Assert.That(syncError, Does.Contain("ExceededBlockSizeLimit"));

    // Production path incorrectly accepts the same oversized block - THIS IS THE BUG
    bool productionResult = validator.ValidateProcessedBlock(
        oversizedBlock,
        System.Array.Empty<TxReceipt>(),
        oversizedBlock,
        out string? productionError);
    Assert.That(productionResult, Is.True, "VULNERABILITY: Production path accepts oversized blocks");
}
```

From the project root directory:
```bash
cd src/Nethermind/Nethermind.Blockchain.Test
dotnet test -c Release
```

The above test will pass, indicating that the `ValidateProcessedBlock` does not check the block size limt.

### Mitigation

Add size validation in `ValidateProcessedBlock`:

```csharp
public bool ValidateProcessedBlock(Block processedBlock, TxReceipt[] receipts, Block suggestedBlock, out string? error)
{
    // Add size check for produced blocks
    IReleaseSpec spec = _specProvider.GetSpec(processedBlock.Header);
    if (spec.IsEip7934Enabled)
    {
        int encodedSize = processedBlock.EncodedSize ?? _blockDecoder.GetLength(processedBlock, RlpBehaviors.None);
        if (encodedSize > spec.Eip7934MaxRlpBlockSize)
        {
            error = BlockErrorMessages.ExceededBlockSizeLimit(spec.Eip7934MaxRlpBlockSize);
            if (_logger.IsError) _logger.Error($"Produced block exceeds size limit: {encodedSize} > {spec.Eip7934MaxRlpBlockSize}");
            return false;
        }
    }

    // Existing validation logic...
    if (processedBlock.Header.Hash == suggestedBlock.Header.Hash)
    {
        error = null;
        return true;
    }

    // ...
}
```

Or add size validation earlier in the production pipeline, e.g., in `ProcessPreparedBlock`.

Additionally, implement real-time block size tracking during block building - monitor the cumulative size as transactions are added and finalize the block when approaching the size limit to prevent oversized blocks from being created in the first place. Alternatively, based on the validation fixes above, evict the last transaction when the size limit is exceeded to ensure the block stays within the allowed size.

### Summary

The missing blob content verification in `DataColumnSidecarELRecoveryManagerImpl` will cause corrupted data column gossip for Teku validators as a malicious Execution Layer will satisfy the count-only check with forged blobs.


### Root Cause

In `ethereum/statetransition/src/main/java/tech/pegasys/teku/statetransition/datacolumns/util/DataColumnSidecarELRecoveryManagerImpl.java`'s `fetchMissingBlobsFromLocalEL` path the recovery flow only validates the number of `BlobAndCellProofs` returned by `engineGetBlobAndCellProofsList` and never re-computes each blob's versioned hash, so arbitrary payloads cross the trust boundary unchanged.


### Internal Pre-conditions

1. [Validator runs Teku with DBP recovery enabled] `DataColumnSidecarELRecoveryManagerImpl` must enqueue a recovery task for a block whose blob sidecars were missing on gossip so the node queries the Execution Layer.
2. [Async recovery executes synchronously] The queued `fetchMissingBlobsFromLocalEL` action has to run while the compromised EL response remains cached so the forged payloads reach `publishRecoveredDataColumnSidecars`.

### External Pre-conditions

1. [Execution Layer endpoint is hostile or compromised] The EL can answer `engineGetBlobAndCellProofsList(versionedHashes, slot)` requests with attacker-crafted blob payloads while preserving the list length.
2. [Target block remains canonical] Consensus continues to build on the block so Teku keeps serving its data columns to custody subscribers.

### Attack Path

1. Attacker withholds or delays the slot's blob sidecars so Teku creates a recovery task and schedules `fetchMissingBlobsFromLocalEL` for that block.
2. When Teku calls `engineGetBlobAndCellProofsList`, the malicious EL returns the correct number of entries but swaps each `Blob` for mutated data that no longer matches the requested versioned hashes.
3. Teku accepts the response, constructs `DataColumnSidecar`s from the forged blobs, and publishes them to the custody subnets because no hash validation occurs before `dataColumnSidecarPublisher.accept(...)`.

### Impact

The Teku validator and any downstream custody subscribers receive and propagate invalid data column sidecars for the affected slot, breaking the Fulu data-availability guarantee and exposing the operator to custody penalties or reputation loss because their node gossips columns that fail to match beacon chain commitments.

