    tests::validation_should_fail_in_v4_test

test result: FAILED. 0 passed; 1 failed; 0 ignored; 0 measured; 2 filtered out; finished in 0.01s
```

### Mitigation

_No response_

### Summary

The gas cost for Nethermind's ModExp precompile is the `long.MaxValue` when any of its lengths exceed 1024. This diverges from the other implementations where the gas cost does not return the max value when the any length exceeds 1024.

### Root Cause

In Nethermind's ModExp precompile, the gas cost is set to [`long.MaxValue`](https://github.com/NethermindEth/nethermind/blob/master/src/Nethermind/Nethermind.Evm.Precompiles/ModExpPrecompile.cs#L93-L96) when any of the lengths exceeds 1024.

```c#
private static long DataGasCostInternal(ReadOnlySpan<byte> inputData, IReleaseSpec releaseSpec)
{
    (uint baseLength, uint expLength, uint modulusLength) = GetInputLengths(inputData);
    if (ExceedsMaxInputSize(releaseSpec, baseLength, expLength, modulusLength))
    {
        return long.MaxValue;
    }
    // ... snip ...
}
```

In Geth, there is no short-circuit logic that returns the max value when the length exceeds 1024. 
references:
1. ModExp's [RequiredGas()](https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/blob/master/core/vm/contracts.go#L561-L607)
2. [osakaModExpGas()](https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/blob/master/core/vm/contracts.go#L539-L558)

Besu also has the same behavior as Geth.
1. [modExpGasCost()](https://github.com/hyperledger/besu/blob/main/evm/src/main/java/org/hyperledger/besu/evm/gascalculator/OsakaGasCalculator.java#L92-L120)

There will be tests provided in the POC section to prove that Nethermind's behavior diverges from the other Execution Clients.

### Internal Pre-conditions

None

### External Pre-conditions

None

### Attack Path

1. A user sends a transaction that calls the ModExp precompile with base length of 1025, mod length of 0, and exp length of 0. The gas provided for the transaction is 50,000.
2. When the transaction is executed in a Besu client, the ModExp call fails and consumes gas worth 2^63 - 1 (long.MaxValue). This uses up all the gas of the transaction and it reverts with an OOG error.
3. When the transaction is executed in a Geth or Besu client, the ModExp call fails and consumes gas worth only 33,282. The user's transaction will still have some gas left over.
4. The difference in gas consumed can lead to a state root or receipts root divergence and a network split. 
5. The chain can halt due to not meeting the consensus threshold of 66% of nodes. Nethermind accounts for 38% of the nodes.

### Impact

The difference in gas consumed can lead to a state root or receipts root divergence and a network split. The chain can halt due to not meeting the consensus threshold of 66% of nodes. Nethermind accounts for 38% of the nodes.

### PoC

Add the following test to Geth. The test below will succeed, which shows that Geth will return 33,282 gas cost for the ModExp precompile call where base length is 1025 and all other lengths are 0.

