### Summary

In `generateWork`, the Ethereum Geth client calculates and validates the size of withdrawals using `Size()`, which returns the in-memory struct size rather than the actual RLP-encoded size. 

Additionally, the withdrawal size is added to work.size using `Size()`, which can misrepresent the actual encoded block size. This may result in blocks being proposed that exceed the protocol-level maximum block size as defined in EIP-7934, violating consensus rules.

### Root Cause

1. `Size()` computes only the in-memory size of Withdrawal structs, ignoring RLP encoding overhead.
https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/blob/bacc1504baa6ede16e8541d74b141d4dac763e3a/miner/worker.go#L118-L122

```go

func (miner *Miner) generateWork(genParam *generateParams, witness bool) *newPayloadResult {
	work, err := miner.prepareWork(genParam, witness)
	if err != nil {
		return &newPayloadResult{err: err}
	}

	// Check withdrawals fit max block size.
	// Due to the cap on withdrawal count, this can actually never happen, but we still need to
	// check to ensure the CL notices there's a problem if the withdrawal cap is ever lifted.
	maxBlockSize := params.MaxBlockSize - maxBlockSizeBufferZone
@>	if genParam.withdrawals.Size() > maxBlockSize {
		return &newPayloadResult{err: errors.New("withdrawals exceed max block size")}
	}
	// Also add size of withdrawals to work block size.
@>	work.size += uint64(genParam.withdrawals.Size())
     ...
```
https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/blob/bacc1504baa6ede16e8541d74b141d4dac763e3a/core/types/withdrawal.go#L54-L57

```go
    func (s Withdrawals) Size() int {
    	return withdrawalSize * len(s)
    }
```

Both the size validation `(if genParam.withdrawals.Size() > maxBlockSize)` and the addition to work.size (work.size += uint64(genParam.withdrawals.Size())) use this inaccurate value.


