It will pass the handshake even the sentry 1 with malformed messages, e.g. empty LatestBlockHash and wrong block range.

### Mitigation

Recommend to validate the peer info during handshake.

### Summary

All clients are upgraded in preparation for the Osaka Fork, which leaves the latest clients running in the previous Prague fork for some epochs. During this pre-Osaka phase, the Besu client introduces the max blobs per transaction check. This diverges from the other clients, such as Geth and Nethermind, causing a network split where Besu rejects blob transactions with more than 6 blobs while Geth and Nethermind accept these blog transactions as long as they are less than 9 blobs.

### Root Cause

In Besu's [`validateBlobTransaction()`](https://github.com/hyperledger/besu/blob/198fc4ab6e95304f2e8bcc0b1bee5b8e8c6f6cc4/ethereum/core/src/main/java/org/hyperledger/besu/ethereum/mainnet/MainnetBlobsValidator.java#L124-L128), the max blobs per transaction check introduced in [EIP-7594](https://eips.ethereum.org/EIPS/eip-7594) is implemented. 

> Additionally, a limit of 6 blobs per transaction is introduced. Clients MUST enforce this limit when validating blob transactions at submission time, when received from the network, and during block production and processing.

However, it does not check if the Fork is Osaka or if PeerDas is enabled for the spec. This check, meant to be introduced in Osaka, will already be active pre-Osaka. 

```java
private ValidationResult<TransactionInvalidReason> validateBlobTransaction(
    final Transaction transaction) {
  // ... snip ...
  if (blobGasCost > gasLimitCalculator.transactionBlobGasLimitCap()) {
    final String error =
        String.format("Blob transaction has too many blobs: %d", versionedHashes.size());
    return ValidationResult.invalid(TransactionInvalidReason.TOTAL_BLOB_GAS_TOO_HIGH, error);
  }
```

This behavior differs from Geth and Nethermind. In [Geth](https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/blob/0977a02ec1eec2d0d85236c33b0e8878b703f890/core/state_transition.go#L376-L378), the max blobs per tx check is only enabled when the fork is Osaka.

```golang
func (st *stateTransition) preCheck() error {
	// ... snip ...
	if msg.BlobHashes != nil {
		//  ... snip ..
		if isOsaka && len(msg.BlobHashes) > params.BlobTxMaxBlobs {
			return ErrTooManyBlobs
		}
```

In [Nethermind](https://github.com/NethermindEth/nethermind/blob/ed2dcf00216c408f21ddfb0ce641e472a9f4c111/src/Nethermind/Nethermind.Specs/ReleaseSpec.cs#L113), the check is enabled but the value compared against is the `MaxBlobCount` while Osaka/EIP7854 is disabled.
```c#
// src/Nethermind/Nethermind.Specs/ReleaseSpec.cs
public ulong MaxBlobsPerTx => IsEip7594Enabled ? Math.Min(Eip7594Constants.MaxBlobsPerTx, MaxBlobCount) : MaxBlobCount;
```

Since the [`MaxBlobCount`](https://github.com/ethereum/consensus-specs/blob/6e97d88f6bf5e77459dc89581d52faf1f51688a7/specs/electra/beacon-chain.md?plain=1#L209) is 9 prior to Osaka, Nethermind's behavior is effectively the same as Geth's. 

| Name                          | Value       | Description                                                                                                      |
| ----------------------------- | ----------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `MAX_BLOBS_PER_BLOCK_ELECTRA` | `uint64(9)` | *[New in Electra:EIP7691]* Maximum number of blobs in a single block limited by `MAX_BLOB_COMMITMENTS_PER_BLOCK` |


### Internal Pre-conditions

None

### External Pre-conditions

None

### Attack Path

1. As part of the upgrade/fork process, all clients are upgraded in preparation for Osaka.
2. A user then submits a blob transaction with 7 blobs.
3. Since this is valid, a proposer includes this blob transaction in the block they propose.
4. Since the blob tx has 7 blobs, all Besu clients that process this block will reject the blob transaction and the block because the blob transaction fails the max blobs per tx validation.
5. Geth and Nethermind clients, however, will accept this blob transaction and the proposed block. This leads to a network split.

### Impact

There is a network split due to all Besu clients rejecting the blob transaction with 7 blobs, while other clients like Geth and Nethermind accept it.

