### Summary

The missing Fulu cutoff in `getCoreTopicsAtFork` will cause ongoing blob_sidecar gossip overhead for Lodestar validators as the gossip core continues to publish Deneb topics post-Fulu.


### Root Cause

In `packages/beacon-node/src/network/gossip/topic.ts` (`getCoreTopicsAtFork`) the topic builder still appends blob sidecar subscriptions whenever the fork sequence is at least Deneb. Because the Fulu sequence number is greater than Deneb, nodes that have shifted into Fulu never drop the legacy blob topics. This contradicts the PeerDAS handoff described in the Fulu rollout notes ("PeerDAS required dropping Deneb blob gossip topics at the Fulu boundary") and keeps gossip traffic that the Fulu spec wants rebalanced toward data column sidecars.

```ts
  // After Deneb also track blob_sidecar_{subnet_id}
  if (ForkSeq[fork] >= ForkSeq.deneb) {
    const {config} = networkConfig;
    const subnetCount = isForkPostElectra(fork)
      ? config.BLOB_SIDECAR_SUBNET_COUNT_ELECTRA
      : config.BLOB_SIDECAR_SUBNET_COUNT;

    for (let subnet = 0; subnet < subnetCount; subnet++) {
      topics.push({type: GossipType.blob_sidecar, subnet});
    }
  }
```

### Internal Pre-conditions

1. Lodestar node enables PeerDAS features and relies on `getCoreTopicsAtFork` when updating subscriptions.
2. The chain has progressed to the Fulu fork (or any later fork) where PeerDAS replaces Deneb blob gossip.
3. The node operates with default `subscribeAllSubnets` settings, so the core topic list is authoritative for gossip subscriptions.

### External Pre-conditions

1. The upstream network has activated the Fulu fork, making PeerDAS the expected data availability mechanism.
2. Validators continue to announce Deneb blob transactions, ensuring the stale subscriptions still receive traffic.


### Attack Path

1. Allow a Lodestar validator to advance from Deneb into Fulu while running the current gossip topic code.
2. Invoke the core topic subscription refresh (e.g., during fork transition or peer discovery updates).
3. Observe that blob sidecar topics remain subscribed and continue to consume gossip bandwidth, blocking the PeerDAS rebalancing expected after Fulu.

### Impact

Validators and sentry nodes keep participating in dense blob gossip despite PeerDAS activation. This wastes bandwidth and connection slots and undermines the spec requirement that Fulu nodes rebalance toward data column sidecars (Fulu rollout notes).

### PoC

**Unit test** `packages/beacon-node/test/unit/network/gossip/poc_gossip_core_topics_continue_subscribing_to_blob_sidecar_subnets_after_the_fulu_fork_wasting_bandwidth_and_preventing_peerdas_topic_rebalancing_mandated_by_the_spec.test.ts`

Expected result: the assertion `expect(blobTopics.length).toBe(0)` fails, proving blob topics remain subscribed at Fulu.

```bash
npx vitest run --project unit packages/beacon-node/test/unit/network/gossip/poc_gossip_core_topics_continue_subscribing_to_blob_sidecar_subnets_after_the_fulu_fork_wasting_bandwidth_and_preventing_peerdas_topic_rebalancing_mandated_by_the_spec.test.ts
```

```ts
import {describe, expect, it} from "vitest";
import {createBeaconConfig} from "@lodestar/config";
import {config as defaultChainConfig} from "@lodestar/config/default";
import {ForkName, ZERO_HASH} from "@lodestar/params";
import {NetworkConfig} from "../../../../src/network/networkConfig.js";
import {GossipType} from "../../../../src/network/gossip/interface.js";
import {getCoreTopicsAtFork} from "../../../../src/network/gossip/topic.js";

describe(
  "PoC: gossip core topics keep blob_sidecar subscriptions into fulu",
  () => {
    it(
      "poc_gossip_core_topics_continue_subscribing_to_blob_sidecar_subnets_after_the_fulu_fork_wasting_bandwidth_and_preventing_peerdas_topic_rebalancing_mandated_by_the_spec",
      () => {
        const config = createBeaconConfig(
          {
            ...defaultChainConfig,
            DENEB_FORK_EPOCH: 1,
            FULU_FORK_EPOCH: 2,
            ELECTRA_FORK_EPOCH: 3,
          },
          ZERO_HASH
        );

        const networkConfig = {
          nodeId: new Uint8Array(32),
          config,
          custodyConfig: {
            sampledSubnets: [0, 1, 2],
          },
        } as unknown as NetworkConfig;

        const topics = getCoreTopicsAtFork(networkConfig, ForkName.fulu, {});

        const blobTopics = topics.filter((topic) => topic.type === GossipType.blob_sidecar);
        const dataColumnTopics = topics.filter((topic) => topic.type === GossipType.data_column_sidecar);

        expect(dataColumnTopics.length).toBeGreaterThan(0);
        expect(blobTopics.length).toBe(0);
      }
    );
  }
);
```

### Mitigation

Gate the blob sidecar push behind a strict Deneb-only window, e.g., `if (ForkSeq[fork] >= ForkSeq.deneb && ForkSeq[fork] < ForkSeq.fulu)`, or restructure the topic builder to return the complete per-fork topic set (mirroring the Lighthouse fix noted in the Fulu rollout notes) so that crossing the Fulu boundary automatically drops the Deneb blob subscriptions.

## Snippet
https://github.com/sigp/lighthouse/blob/e5b4983d6baf85770fe4539a565d8a2dd462bc53/beacon_node/beacon_chain/src/beacon_chain.rs#L4729-L4733

## Finding description
In `beacon_node/beacon_chain/src/beacon_chain.rs`, there is a fallback path in the `get_pre_payload_attributes` function that performs a full clone of the `beacon_state` object whenever certain conditions are met. The `beacon_state` object is a very large data structure, storing almost the entire Beacon Chain state (thousands of validators, balances, epoch contexts, etc.). `clone()`ing an object of this size would consume significant memory and repeatedly overload the CPU under high load, which would cause the node to lag, freeze, or crash if called repeatedly under unhealthy network conditions.
```rust
let Some(proposer_index) = self.with_proposer_cache(
    shuffling_decision_root,
    proposal_epoch,
    |proposers| proposers.get_slot::<T::EthSpec>(proposal_slot).map(|p| p.index as u64),
    || {
        if head_epoch + self.config.sync_tolerance_epochs < proposal_epoch {
            warn!(
                msg = "this is a non-critical issue that can happen on unhealthy nodes or \
                       networks",
                %proposal_epoch,
                %head_epoch,
                "Skipping proposer preparation"
            );

            // Don't skip the head forward too many epochs. This avoids burdening an
            // unhealthy node.
            //
            // Although this node might miss out on preparing for a proposal, they should
            // still be able to propose. This will prioritise beacon chain health over
            // efficient packing of execution blocks.
            Err(Error::SkipProposerPreparation)
        } else {
            let head = self.canonical_head.cached_head();
            Ok((
                head.head_state_root(),
                head.snapshot.beacon_state.clone(), // <<-- issue here
            ))
        }
    },
```
The root of the problem lies in the fallback path in the proposer cache in `get_pre_payload_attributes`. Due to the lack of optimization or lazy loading mechanisms, the entire `beacon_state` is directly copied on each fallback, instead of only reading the necessary parts.

Fusaka aims to reduce resource overhead, but the full fallback clone of `beacon_state` actually adds significant overhead (CPU + memory). If this happens frequently, validators require more resources to stay in sync, contradicting Fusaka's vision of an inclusive and lightweight validator. Instead of making validators lighter, this risks making them heavy when entering the fallback path, thus reducing their effectiveness.

## Impact
A malicious peer can repeatedly send stale blocks or blocks from the old chain to a target node. Each such message forces the node to verify and triggers a cache miss in proposer tasks, which is the code in the fallback path that repeatedly executes `beacon_state.clone()`. This results in drastically increased memory and CPU consumption, leading to node lag, thrashing, or OOM.

For example, a node may become desynchronized due to slow connections, delayed gossip (slow block propagation), long reorgs, or inter-region partitions. In these cases, nodes often encounter a `proposal_epoch` that is higher than the `head_epoch`, triggering repeated fallbacks and clones while trying to catch up with the chain state. This also leads to resource exhaustion.

## Scenario Considerations
1. Attack initiation: A malicious peer targets a node or group of nodes by continuously sending stale blocks or blocks from an old parent.
2. A cache miss occurs: When the node receives the message, the `proposal_epoch` computed for a specific slot does not match, or the proposer's cache does not contain an entry for the requested `shuffling_decision_root`, resulting in a cache miss in the proposer's cache mechanism.
3. Fallback path entry: Due to the cache miss, the fallback closure is called in `get_pre_payload_attributes`. The condition remains within the synchronization tolerance, at which point the code executes:
```rust
Ok((
    head.head_state_root(),
    head.snapshot.beacon_state.clone(),
))
```
This involves deep cloning the entire `BeaconState`.
4. Repeated resource spikes: The attacker continues to send more stale blocks (or the network remains slow, allowing this process to repeat), causing nodes to clone `beacon_state` multiple times per slot or multiple slots. Each clone allocates tens of MB (depending on the state size), copies large structures, and triggers memory/CPU-intensive activity.
5. Performance degradation/crashes: The accumulation of repeated clones causes GC pressure, swapping, or OOM on nodes. Nodes become slow or crash, failing to complete proposer preparation for upcoming slots.
6. Missed proposals & liveness impact: Affected nodes fail to submit proposals or properly package payload execution. If a large operator or large number of nodes are affected (e.g., >5% of validators), the number of optimized blocks decreases and network finality slows.

## POC
```rust
#[cfg(test)]
mod beacon_chain_dos_tests {
    use crate::test_utils::BeaconChainHarness;
    use std::time::Instant;
    use types::{EthSpec, FixedBytesExtended, Hash256, MainnetEthSpec};

    /// Test that demonstrates DoS issue via resource exhaustion 
    /// caused by repeated beacon_state cloning in proposer preparation fallback path
    #[tokio::test]
    async fn test_proposer_cache_dos_issue() {
        // Setup beacon chain with many validators to create large beacon_state
        let validator_count = 6000;
        let harness = BeaconChainHarness::builder(MainnetEthSpec)
            .default_spec()
            .deterministic_keypairs(validator_count)
            .fresh_ephemeral_store()
            .build();

        let chain = harness.chain.clone();

        // Advance chain to make state more complex
        for _ in 0..5 {
            harness.advance_slot();
        }

        let start_time = Instant::now();
        let iterations = 20;

        // Simulate repeated cache misses that force beacon_state cloning
        for i in 0..iterations {
            // Create different shuffling_decision_root each time to force cache miss
            let fake_decision_root = Hash256::from_low_u64_be(i as u64 + 12345);
            let current_slot = chain.slot().unwrap();
            let future_epoch = current_slot.epoch(MainnetEthSpec::slots_per_epoch()) + 3;

            // This will trigger the expensive fallback path in with_proposer_cache
            // which calls state_provider() and clones the beacon_state
            let _result: Result<Option<u64>, crate::BeaconChainError> = chain.with_proposer_cache(
                fake_decision_root,
                future_epoch,
                |proposers| {
                    proposers.get_slot::<MainnetEthSpec>(future_epoch.start_slot(MainnetEthSpec::slots_per_epoch()))
                        .map(|p| Some(p.index as u64))
                        .map_err(|e| crate::BeaconChainError::from(e))
                },
                || {
                    // This is the expensive fallback that clones beacon_state
                    let head = chain.canonical_head.cached_head();
                    Ok((head.head_state_root(), head.snapshot.beacon_state.clone()))
                }
            );
        }

        let total_time = start_time.elapsed();
        let avg_time_per_iteration = total_time / (iterations as u32);

        // Verify DoS conditions:
        // 1. Each iteration should take significant time due to large state cloning
        assert!(
            avg_time_per_iteration.as_millis() > 5,
            "Average time per iteration should show performance impact from cloning large beacon_state. \
             Got {:?}, expected >5ms with {} validators",
            avg_time_per_iteration, validator_count
        );

        // 2. Total time should demonstrate cumulative impact
        assert!(
            total_time.as_millis() > 100,
            "Total time should demonstrate cumulative DoS impact. \
             Got {:?} for {} iterations, expected >100ms",
            total_time, iterations
        );

        // 3. Verify this is exploitable (fast enough for practical attack)
        assert!(
            total_time.as_secs() < 10,
            "Attack should be fast enough to be practical. \
             Got {:?}, should complete in <10 seconds",
            total_time
        );
    }
}
```

## Recommendation
Use a reference or pointer (borrowed reference) to `beacon_state` if you're only reading data. Alternatively, extract only the subset of data needed for proposer preparation, not the entire state.

### Summary
A missing guard in the fork-version selection logic causes a default Lighthouse node to broadcast the Fulu fork version while the fork remains unscheduled, so peers that clamp far-future forks terminate the gossip handshake due to mismatched metadata.

### Root Cause
In `consensus/types/src/chain_spec.rs`, `ChainSpec::next_fork_version` returns the fork version associated with the next scheduled upgrade without checking whether the configured epoch equals the `FAR_FUTURE_EPOCH` sentinel, so the discovery metadata jumps ahead to the Fulu version even when no rollout is planned.

Reference: Prysm patch https://github.com/OffchainLabs/prysm/pull/15799 (drops unscheduled forks to keep ENR fork versions aligned and documents identical discovery failures).

### Internal Pre-conditions
1. Lighthouse runs with the default mainnet `ChainSpec::mainnet()` configuration where `fulu_fork_epoch` is implicitly set to `far_future_epoch`.
2. The node computes ENR fork IDs for Electra-era slots via `ChainSpec::enr_fork_id`, using `next_fork_version` as-is.

### External Pre-conditions
1. Counterparty consensus clients enforce discovery validation rules that clamp the next fork version when the advertised epoch equals the far-future sentinel.
2. The Lighthouse node attempts to join or maintain gossipsub and discovery sessions with those peers.

### Attack Path
1. A Lighthouse node boots with the default mainnet configuration and publishes ENRs derived from that spec.
2. Peers calculate the expected fork version for the same slot and detect that the advertised next version disagrees with the far-future epoch.
3. Peers reject the ENR and refuse the connection, shrinking Lighthouse’s usable peer set and degrading block propagation and attestation duties.

### Impact
This is an interoperability regression that reduces peer diversity rather than a direct network-safety failure. Peers that validate fork metadata before completing the handshake drop the Lighthouse node, shrinking its active set until it finds replacements (typically other Lighthouse or tolerant clients). The result is slower block and attestation gossip and elevated risk of temporary missed duties, but the network converges once alternative peers are discovered.

Under the Sherlock rubric this maps to Informational severity (at most Low): impact is limited to the Lighthouse operator’s connectivity, and likelihood is effectively certain while Fulu remains unscheduled because the default mainnet spec ships with the far-future sentinel.

This failure mode is not unique to Lighthouse: Prysm maintainers filed https://github.com/OffchainLabs/prysm/pull/15799 on October 2, 2025 after observing the same far-future fork advertisement causing peer rejection, underscoring the cross-client nature of the regression.

To keep Fusaka/Fulu rollouts safe, clients must ensure that fork metadata only advances once epochs are anchored; otherwise discovery-layer divergence persists into the Fulu staging period.

### PoC
Path: `consensus/types/src/poc_when_fulu_fork_epoch_is_far_future_epoch_we_still_emit_fulu_as_next_fork_version_violating_sr_xl_001_peers_that_clamp_far_future_forks_reject_our_enr.rs`
Run (currently expected to fail on unpatched Lighthouse, signalling the bug): `cargo test -p types poc_when_fulu_fork_epoch_is_far_future_epoch_we_still_emit_fulu_as_next_fork_version_violating_sr_xl_001_peers_that_clamp_far_future_forks_reject_our_enr`

```rust
//! Regression test: fails today because Fulu stays as the advertised next fork even when the epoch is FAR_FUTURE. Apply the clamp patch and it will pass.

use types::chain_spec::ChainSpec;
use types::eth_spec::MainnetEthSpec;
use types::fork_name::ForkName;
use types::EthSpec;

#[test]
fn poc_when_fulu_fork_epoch_is_far_future_epoch_we_still_emit_fulu_as_next_fork_version_violating_sr_xl_001_peers_that_clamp_far_future_forks_reject_our_enr() {
    // Arrange: emulate the mainnet spec advertising Fulu at FAR_FUTURE_EPOCH.
    let mut spec = ChainSpec::mainnet();
    spec.fulu_fork_epoch = Some(spec.far_future_epoch);

    let electra_epoch = spec
        .electra_fork_epoch
        .expect("mainnet spec configures an Electra fork");
    let slot = electra_epoch.start_slot(MainnetEthSpec::slots_per_epoch());

    // Act: compute ENR fork metadata for a slot where Electra is active.
    let current_fork = spec.fork_name_at_slot::<MainnetEthSpec>(slot);
    assert_eq!(
        current_fork,
        ForkName::Electra,
        "Electra must remain the active fork for the chosen slot",
    );

    let advertised_next = spec.next_fork_version::<MainnetEthSpec>(slot);
    let expected_current = spec.fork_version_for_name(current_fork);

    // Assert: next_fork_version should not jump ahead to Fulu when its epoch is far future.
    assert_eq!(
        advertised_next, expected_current,
        "next_fork_version should clamp to the active fork when the next fork epoch is FAR_FUTURE_EPOCH",
    );
}
```

