This demonstrates a single ByRoot request can hold the handler for >1s under realistic per-read costs, sufficient to argue one-node degradation (=>0.01%). This does not alter protocol logic, it demonstrates the consequence of missing admission control before work.

### Mitigation

- Add an up-front admission check to ByRoot mirroring ByRange:
```go
// At the start of dataColumnSidecarByRootRPCHandler:
if err := s.rateLimiter.validateRequest(stream, rateLimitingAmount); err != nil {
    s.writeErrorResponseToStream(responseCodeInvalidRequest, p2ptypes.ErrRateLimited.Error(), stream)
    return err
}
```
Keep s.rateLimiter.add(stream, …) for post-hoc accounting, but do not rely on it for admission. Also optionally match ByRange’s batching behavior for consistency (avoid asymmetric throttling semantics).

### Summary

Missing size check in sync path will cause a persistent fork for Besu validators as a malicious peer can serve an oversized block body via ETH block bodies during sync.

### Root Cause

In [MainnetBlockValidator.java:123-129](https://github.com/hyperledger/besu/blob/4d2d58548113459e5e07bf81b718127fac7d93f9/ethereum/core/src/main/java/org/hyperledger/besu/ethereum/MainnetBlockValidator.java#L123-L129), the normal import path rejects any block whose RLP size exceeds `maxRlpBlockSize`:
```java
public BlockProcessingResult validateAndProcessBlock(...) {
  final int blockSize = block.getSize();
  // @audit Rejects oversized block
  if (blockSize > maxRlpBlockSize) {
    final String errorMessage =
        "Block size of " + blockSize + " bytes exceeds limit of " + maxRlpBlockSize + " bytes";
    var retval = new BlockProcessingResult(errorMessage);
    handleFailedBlockProcessing(block, retval, true, context);
    return retval;
  }
  // [...]
}
```

But in [MainnetBlockValidator.java:276-310](http://github.com/hyperledger/besu/blob/4d2d58548113459e5e07bf81b718127fac7d93f9/ethereum/core/src/main/java/org/hyperledger/besu/ethereum/MainnetBlockValidator.java#L276-L310), the sync validator never checks the size of block:
```java
public boolean validateBlockForSyncing(...) {
  // @audit Missing maxRlpBlockSize guard in whole path
  if (bodyValidationMode == BodyValidationMode.FULL) {
    throw new UnsupportedOperationException(
        "Full body validation is not supported for syncing blocks");
  }

  final BlockHeader header = block.getHeader();
  if (!blockHeaderValidator.validateHeader(header, context, headerValidationMode)) {
    String description = String.format("Failed header validation (%s)", headerValidationMode);
    context
        .getBadBlockManager()
        .addBadBlock(block, BadBlockCause.fromValidationFailure(description));
    return false;
  }

  if (bodyValidationMode == BodyValidationMode.NONE) {
    return true;
  }

  if (!blockBodyValidator.validateBodyLight(context, block, receipts, ommerValidationMode)) {
    context
        .getBadBlockManager()
        .addBadBlock(
            block, BadBlockCause.fromValidationFailure("Failed body validation (light)"));
    return false;
  }
  return true;
}
```

In [MainnetBlockImporter.java:77-97](https://github.com/hyperledger/besu/blob/4d2d58548113459e5e07bf81b718127fac7d93f9/ethereum/core/src/main/java/org/hyperledger/besu/ethereum/mainnet/MainnetBlockImporter.java#L77-L97), the importer appends the block immediately when that method returns true:
```java
public BlockImportResult importBlockForSyncing(...) {
  if (blockValidator.validateBlockForSyncing(
      context, block, receipts, headerValidationMode, ommerValidationMode, bodyValidationMode)) {
    if (importWithTxIndexing) {
      // @audit Oversized block persisted during sync
      context.getBlockchain().appendBlock(block, receipts);
    } else {
      context.getBlockchain().appendBlockWithoutIndexingTransactions(block, receipts);
    }
    return new BlockImportResult(true);
  }

  return new BlockImportResult(false);
}
```

This also breaks the [EIP-7934](https://eips.ethereum.org/EIPS/eip-7934) MUST rule:
> Any RLP-encoded block exceeding `MAX_RLP_BLOCK_SIZE` must be considered invalid.

### Internal Pre-conditions

1. Validator operator restarts or boots a Besu node so it performs fast sync.

### External Pre-conditions

1. Attacker crafts or relays a block whose RLP size is strictly greater than `MAX_RLP_BLOCK_SIZE`.

### Attack Path

1. Attacker peer serves the oversized block body via ETH block bodies during sync.
2. `validateBlockForSyncing` skips the size guard, so it returns true even though the block violates EIP-7934.
3. `importBlockForSyncing` appends the invalid block to the local chain head.
4. The node adopts the invalid block as head and it didn't converge back without a manual resync, so the validator remained stuck off the canonical chain.

### Impact

The Besu validator cannot produce or attest on the canonical chain until resync/reorg, so it drops offline. Because Besu supplies ~16 % of execution clients, this single ETH block-body response trivially brings down more than 5 % of the network, satisfying the Medium-severity DoS threshold.

### PoC

1. Create new file named `MainnetBlockValidatorSyncSizeLimitTest.java` in [ethereum/core/src/test/java/org/hyperledger/besu/ethereum](https://github.com/hyperledger/besu/tree/main/ethereum/core/src/test/java/org/hyperledger/besu/ethereum/) directory.
2. Paste the code from below.
3. Build and execute the test: `./gradlew :ethereum:core:test --tests 'org.hyperledger.besu.ethereum.MainnetBlockValidatorSyncSizeLimitTest.syncValidationAcceptsOversizedBlockAndImporterAppends'`.

#### Code
```java
package org.hyperledger.besu.ethereum;

import static org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThat;
import static org.mockito.ArgumentMatchers.any;
import static org.mockito.Mockito.mock;
import static org.mockito.Mockito.verify;
import static org.mockito.Mockito.when;

import org.hyperledger.besu.ethereum.chain.MutableBlockchain;
import org.hyperledger.besu.ethereum.BlockProcessingResult;
import org.hyperledger.besu.ethereum.BlockValidator;
import org.hyperledger.besu.ethereum.ProtocolContext;
import org.hyperledger.besu.ethereum.core.Block;
import org.hyperledger.besu.ethereum.core.BlockBody;
import org.hyperledger.besu.ethereum.core.BlockHeader;
import org.hyperledger.besu.ethereum.core.BlockHeaderTestFixture;
import org.hyperledger.besu.ethereum.core.TransactionReceipt;
import org.hyperledger.besu.ethereum.mainnet.BlockBodyValidator;
import org.hyperledger.besu.ethereum.mainnet.BlockHeaderValidator;
import org.hyperledger.besu.ethereum.mainnet.BlockImportResult;
import org.hyperledger.besu.ethereum.mainnet.BodyValidationMode;
import org.hyperledger.besu.ethereum.mainnet.HeaderValidationMode;
import org.hyperledger.besu.ethereum.mainnet.MainnetBlockImporter;
import org.hyperledger.besu.ethereum.mainnet.BlockProcessor;

import java.util.Collections;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.Optional;

import org.junit.jupiter.api.BeforeEach;
import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;

public class MainnetBlockValidatorSyncSizeLimitTest {

  private ProtocolContext protocolContext;
  private MutableBlockchain blockchain;
  private BlockHeaderValidator headerValidator;
  private BlockBodyValidator bodyValidator;
  private BlockProcessor blockProcessor;

  private static final int TEST_MAX_RLP_BLOCK_SIZE = 1024;

  private BlockValidator blockValidator;

  @BeforeEach
  public void setUp() {
    protocolContext = mock(ProtocolContext.class);
    blockchain = mock(MutableBlockchain.class);
    when(protocolContext.getBlockchain()).thenReturn(blockchain);

    headerValidator = mock(BlockHeaderValidator.class);
    bodyValidator = mock(BlockBodyValidator.class);
    blockProcessor = mock(BlockProcessor.class);

    blockValidator =
        new MainnetBlockValidator(headerValidator, bodyValidator, blockProcessor, TEST_MAX_RLP_BLOCK_SIZE);
  }

  private static Block makeBlockWithSize(final int size) {
    final BlockHeader header = new BlockHeaderTestFixture().buildHeader();
    final BlockBody body = new BlockBody(Collections.emptyList(), Collections.emptyList(), Optional.empty());
    return new Block(header, body, size);
  }

  @Test
  public void syncValidationAcceptsOversizedBlockAndImporterAppends() {
    final int oversized = TEST_MAX_RLP_BLOCK_SIZE + 100;
    final Block block = makeBlockWithSize(oversized);

    when(headerValidator.validateHeader(any(), any(), any())).thenReturn(true);
    when(bodyValidator.validateBodyLight(any(), any(Block.class), any(), any())).thenReturn(true);

    final boolean ok =
        blockValidator.validateBlockForSyncing(
            protocolContext,
            block,
            List.<TransactionReceipt>of(),
            HeaderValidationMode.FULL,
            HeaderValidationMode.NONE,
            BodyValidationMode.LIGHT);
    assertThat(ok).isTrue();

    final MainnetBlockImporter importer = new MainnetBlockImporter(blockValidator);
    final BlockImportResult importResult =
        importer.importBlockForSyncing(
            protocolContext,
            block,
            List.<TransactionReceipt>of(),
            HeaderValidationMode.FULL,
            HeaderValidationMode.NONE,
            BodyValidationMode.LIGHT,
            true);

    assertThat(importResult.isImported()).isTrue();
    verify(blockchain).appendBlock(block, List.of());
  }
}
```

### Mitigation

Apply the same `block.getSize() > maxRlpBlockSize` guard inside `validateBlockForSyncing`, or reject in the importer before appending.

### Summary

Missing validator custody scaling will cause a consensus split for Teku validators as a malicious proposer withholds an unsampled column while Teku samples only `max(initial_custody, samples_per_slot)` (8 by default).

### Root Cause

In [CustodyGroupCountManagerImpl.java:135-137](https://github.com/Consensys/teku/blob/ea93b7bfbd87b73c3659e0cdb029972632fa0182/ethereum/statetransition/src/main/java/tech/pegasys/teku/statetransition/datacolumns/CustodyGroupCountManagerImpl.java#L135-L137), the slot handler returns early whenever the prepared proposer map is empty:
```java
public void onSlot(final UInt64 slot) {
  // [...]
  // @audit Skip custody update when no prepared proposers
  if (!startSlotAtEpoch.equals(slot) || preparedValidators.isEmpty()) {
    return;
  }
  // [...]
}
```

In [CustodyGroupCountManagerImpl.java:193-202](https://github.com/Consensys/teku/blob/ea93b7bfbd87b73c3659e0cdb029972632fa0182/ethereum/statetransition/src/main/java/tech/pegasys/teku/statetransition/datacolumns/CustodyGroupCountManagerImpl.java#L193-L202), the computed custody relies solely on `preparedProposerInfo.keySet()`. Because `getSamplingGroupCount()` returns `max(custody_group_count, samples_per_slot)` (context: [MiscHelpersFulu.java:578](https://github.com/Consensys/teku/blob/ea93b7bfbd87b73c3659e0cdb029972632fa0182/ethereum/spec/src/main/java/tech/pegasys/teku/spec/logic/versions/fulu/helpers/MiscHelpersFulu.java#L578)), Teku never increases sampling when no prepared proposers exist:
```java
SafeFuture<Optional<Integer>> computeAndUpdateCustodyGroupCount(
    final Map<UInt64, PreparedProposerInfo> preparedProposerInfo) {
  final Optional<Integer> maybeCustodyGroupCount =
      combinedChainDataClient.getCustodyGroupCount().map(UInt64::intValue);
  return combinedChainDataClient
      .getBestFinalizedState()
      .thenApply(
          maybeState -> {
            if (maybeState.isEmpty()) {
              return Optional.empty();
            }

            final int computedCustody =
                miscHelpersFulu
                    .getValidatorsCustodyRequirement(
                        maybeState.get(), preparedProposerInfo.keySet()) // <-- Only prepared proposers counted
                    .intValue();
            final int custodyGroupCount =
                maybeCustodyGroupCount
                    .map(integer -> Math.max(computedCustody, integer))
                    .orElse(computedCustody);
            updateCustodyGroupCount(custodyGroupCount, maybeCustodyGroupCount);

            return Optional.of(custodyGroupCount);
          });
}
```

### Internal Pre-conditions

1. Validator operator does not call (or does not refresh every 3 epochs) `prepare_beacon_proposer`, so `preparedProposerInfo` remains empty.
2. Teku keeps its initial custody count, so sampling stays at `max(initial_custody, samples_per_slot)` (8 columns by default).
3. Attacker controls a Teku validator to obtain a block proposal slot.

### External Pre-conditions

1. Attacker controls the block producer for one slot.

### Attack Path

1. Malicious proposer constructs a valid block but withholds a single column that Teku is unlikely to sample (probability equals to 93.75% since Teku checks only 8/128 columns).
2. `DasSamplerBasic` reports success because the sampled columns are present.
3. Clients that follow validator-based scaling (e.g., [Lighthouse](https://github.com/sigp/lighthouse/blob/e5b4983d6baf85770fe4539a565d8a2dd462bc53/beacon_node/beacon_chain/src/validator_custody.rs#L68-L97)) request the missing column, fail to obtain it, and reject the block.
4. Teku validators attest and build on the block, while the rest of the network rejects it, creating a deterministic split.

### Impact

Teku validators (~21 % share) accept the bad block while other clients reject it, producing a consensus split that clearly exceeds the Medium threshold (>5 % of validators). Other clients avoid the issue because they track all attached validators and raise custody automatically.

### PoC

1. Create new file named `CustodySamplingTest.java` in [ethereum/statetransition/src/test/java/tech/pegasys/teku/statetransition/datacolumns](https://github.com/Consensys/teku/tree/master/ethereum/statetransition/src/test/java/tech/pegasys/teku/statetransition/datacolumns) directory.
2. Paste the code of the test.
3. Build and execute the test: `./gradlew :ethereum:statetransition:test --tests 'tech.pegasys.teku.statetransition.datacolumns.CustodySamplingTest.*'`.

#### Code
```java
package tech.pegasys.teku.statetransition.datacolumns;

import static org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThat;
import static org.mockito.ArgumentMatchers.any;
import static org.mockito.Mockito.mock;
import static org.mockito.Mockito.never;
import static org.mockito.Mockito.spy;
import static org.mockito.Mockito.verify;
import static org.mockito.Mockito.when;

import java.util.Map;
import java.util.Optional;
import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;
import tech.pegasys.teku.infrastructure.metrics.StubMetricsSystem;
import tech.pegasys.teku.infrastructure.async.SafeFuture;
import tech.pegasys.teku.infrastructure.unsigned.UInt64;
import tech.pegasys.teku.spec.Spec;
import tech.pegasys.teku.spec.SpecMilestone;
import tech.pegasys.teku.spec.TestSpecFactory;
import tech.pegasys.teku.spec.config.SpecConfigFulu;
import tech.pegasys.teku.spec.logic.versions.fulu.helpers.MiscHelpersFulu;
import tech.pegasys.teku.spec.util.DataStructureUtil;
import tech.pegasys.teku.statetransition.CustodyGroupCountChannel;
import tech.pegasys.teku.statetransition.forkchoice.ProposersDataManager;
import tech.pegasys.teku.storage.client.CombinedChainDataClient;

public class CustodySamplingTest {

  @Test
  public void samplingStaysAtSamplesPerSlotWhenNoPreparedProposers() {
    // Spec with Fulu defaults
    final Spec spec = TestSpecFactory.createMinimalFulu();
    final SpecConfigFulu specConfigFulu =
        SpecConfigFulu.required(spec.forMilestone(SpecMilestone.FULU).getConfig());

    final ProposersDataManager proposersDataManager = mock(ProposersDataManager.class);
    final CustodyGroupCountChannel custodyGroupCountChannel = mock(CustodyGroupCountChannel.class);
    final CombinedChainDataClient combinedChainDataClient = mock(CombinedChainDataClient.class);
    final StubMetricsSystem metrics = new StubMetricsSystem();
    final DataStructureUtil data = new DataStructureUtil(spec);

    final MiscHelpersFulu miscHelpersFulu =
        spy(MiscHelpersFulu.required(spec.forMilestone(SpecMilestone.FULU).miscHelpers()));

    // Initial custody from store smaller than samples_per_slot so sampling = samples_per_slot
    final int initialCustody = Math.max(1, specConfigFulu.getCustodyRequirement());
    when(combinedChainDataClient.getCustodyGroupCount())
        .thenReturn(Optional.of(UInt64.valueOf(initialCustody)));
    when(combinedChainDataClient.getBestFinalizedState())
        .thenReturn(SafeFuture.completedFuture(Optional.of(data.randomBeaconState())));

    // No prepared proposers
    when(proposersDataManager.getPreparedProposerInfo()).thenReturn(Map.of());

    final CustodyGroupCountManagerImpl manager =
        new CustodyGroupCountManagerImpl(
            spec,
            specConfigFulu,
            miscHelpersFulu,
            proposersDataManager,
            custodyGroupCountChannel,
            combinedChainDataClient,
            initialCustody,
            data.randomUInt256(),
            metrics);

    // Trigger onSlot at the start of an epoch with empty prepared proposers
    final UInt64 slot = spec.computeStartSlotAtEpoch(UInt64.ZERO);
    manager.onSlot(slot);

    // Assert sampling stays at samples_per_slot (since custody not raised)
    assertThat(manager.getSamplingGroupCount()).isEqualTo(specConfigFulu.getSamplesPerSlot());

    // Teku did not attempt to compute validator-based custody
    verify(miscHelpersFulu, never()).getValidatorsCustodyRequirement(any(), any());
  }
}
```

### Mitigation

Derive custody requirements from every attached or registered validator (e.g., validator registrations, active connections) instead of only prepared proposers.

### Summary

Missing migration of cached legacy blob sidecars will cause Osaka-era blob requests to return empty responses for execution clients as replayed pre-Osaka entries remain unconverted to the Osaka cell-proof format.

### Root Cause

After Osaka activates, the transaction pool validator’s `Missing` sidecar path only checks for the presence of a cached legacy EIP-4844 sidecar and never upgrades or purges it, so downstream components cannot construct the Osaka-compliant payload that `engine_getBlobsV2` expects to serve.

### Internal Pre-conditions

1. A blob transaction was previously validated and cached with a legacy EIP-4844 sidecar before Osaka activation.
2. Osaka activates without migrating or clearing the cached legacy entry.
3. The same transaction is reinjected or replayed, triggering the validator’s `Missing` sidecar branch and later queried through the engine API.

### External Pre-conditions

None; no external chain conditions or oracle movements are required.

### Attack Path

1. An operator or reorg replays a transaction whose blob sidecar was cached pre-Osaka.
2. The transaction pool validator accepts the cached legacy sidecar in the `Missing` branch without conversion once Osaka is active.
3. A consensus client calls `engine_getBlobsV2` for the blob hash and receives `Ok(None)` because the cache still holds the legacy variant instead of an Osaka-compliant sidecar.

### Impact

Engine API callers requesting Osaka-era blob data receive empty responses instead of the required Osaka cell proofs. This introduces an informational-level availability and interoperability gap—monitoring and tooling must rely on fallbacks, but no malformed data or direct economic loss occurs.

### PoC

Run commands (from the workspace root):

```bash
cargo test --features test-utils poc_need_evidence_that_cached_legacy_sidecars_resurface_post_osaka
cargo test poc_need_evidence_that_cached_legacy_sidecars_resurface_post_osaka_engine -- --nocapture
```

- Unit PoC source: `crates/transaction-pool/tests/poc_need_evidence_that_cached_legacy_sidecars_resurface_post_osaka.rs`
- Integration PoC source: `crates/rpc/rpc-engine-api/tests/poc_need_evidence_that_cached_legacy_sidecars_resurface_post_osaka_engine.rs`

#### Unit PoC — Transaction pool regression
