    final UInt64 slot3 = slot2.getSlot().plus(UInt64.ONE);
    final SignedBlockAndState b3Gen = cb.generateBlockAtSlot(slot3); // not persisted to store
    final SignedBeaconBlock b3 = b3Gen.getBlock();

    // Header and sidecar for slot 3
    final BeaconBlockHeader hdr =
            new BeaconBlockHeader(b3.getSlot(), b3.getProposerIndex(), b3.getParentRoot(), b3.getStateRoot(), b3.getBodyRoot());
    final SignedBeaconBlockHeader shdr = new SignedBeaconBlockHeader(hdr, b3.getSignature());
    final DataColumnSidecar sidecar = dataStructureUtil.randomDataColumnSidecar(shdr, UInt64.ZERO);

    // Real helper (rounds up vi a Math.round(0.5) == 1s) Spy to stub non-time paths only
    final GossipValidationHelper real = new GossipValidationHelper(spec, rcd);
    final GossipValidationHelper helper = spy(real);
    // Stub non-time dependencies to succeed
    doReturn(false).when(helper).isSlotFinalized(any(UInt64.class));
    doReturn(true).when(helper).currentFinalizedCheckpointIsAncestorOfBlock(any(), any());
    doReturn(true).when(helper).isBlockAvailable(any());
    doReturn(Optional.of(slot2.getSlot())).when(helper).getSlotForBlockRoot(any());
    final BeaconState head = SafeFutureAssert.safeJoin(rcd.getBestState().orElseThrow());
    doReturn(SafeFuture.completedFuture(Optional.of(head)))
            .when(helper).getParentStateInBlockEpoch(any(), any(), any());
    doReturn(true).when(helper).isProposerTheExpectedProposer(any(), any(), any());
    doReturn(true).when(helper).isSignatureValidWithRespectToProposerIndex(any(), any(), any(), any());
    // ^^ do NOT stub isSlotFromFuture(

    final DataColumnSidecarGossipValidator v =
            DataColumnSidecarGossipValidator.create(
                    spec, invalidBlocks, helper, miscHelpersFulu, kzg, metricsSystemStub, stubTimeProvider);

    // Move time FORWARD to (slot3Time - 1s): sidecar for slot 3 is exactly 1s early
    final UInt64 slot3Time = spec.computeTimeAtSlot(head, slot3);
    cu.setTime(slot3Time.minus(UInt64.ONE)); // forward-only, no revert

    // mock some irrelevant checks, for the sake of the test, so we ignore them
    when(miscHelpersFulu.verifyDataColumnSidecar(any())).thenReturn(true);
    when(miscHelpersFulu.verifyDataColumnSidecarInclusionProof(any())).thenReturn(true);
    when(miscHelpersFulu.verifyDataColumnSidecarKzgProofs(any(), any(DataColumnSidecar.class))).thenReturn(true);

    // teku rounds 500ms to 1s
    assertThat(helper.getMaxOffsetTimeInSeconds()).isEqualTo(UInt64.ONE);

    // Because of rounding, 1s-early sidecar is NOT "from future" -> ACCEPT
    SafeFutureAssert.assertThatSafeFuture(v.validate(sidecar))
            .isCompletedWithValueMatching(InternalValidationResult::isAccept);
  }
```

### Mitigation

Don't round up and accept the appropriately set value.

`createRecoveryTaskFromDataColumnSidecar` and `createRecoveryTaskFromBlock` bail out unless the payload’s slot exactly matches `getCurrentSlot()`, so once the local clock advances they refuse to create a new `recoveryTasks` entry 

https://github.com/Consensys/teku/blob/87dcf1733df59d12d4e68923849e3512cfa2498e/ethereum/statetransition/src/main/java/tech/pegasys/teku/statetransition/datacolumns/util/DataColumnSidecarELRecoveryManagerImpl.java#L215-L236

```java
if (!dataColumnSidecar.getSlot().equals(getCurrentSlot())) {
      return false;
    }
    makeRoomForNewTracker();
    return recoveryTasks.putIfAbsent(
            dataColumnSidecar.getSlotAndBlockRoot(),
            new RecoveryTask(
                DataColumnSidecarFulu.required(dataColumnSidecar).getSignedBlockHeader(),
                dataColumnSidecar.getKzgCommitments(),
                DataColumnSidecarFulu.required(dataColumnSidecar)
                    .getKzgCommitmentsInclusionProof()
                    .asListUnboxed(),
                Collections.newSetFromMap(new ConcurrentHashMap<>())))
        == null;
  }

  private boolean createRecoveryTaskFromBlock(final SignedBeaconBlock block) {
    final SlotAndBlockRoot slotAndBlockRoot = block.getSlotAndBlockRoot();
    if (recoveryTasks.containsKey(slotAndBlockRoot)) {
      return false;
    }
    if (!block.getSlot().equals(getCurrentSlot()))
```

`getCurrentSlot()` is overwritten on every slot event, so at slot S+1 it no longer equals a block or sidecar from slot S, even though the item still passes the pool’s age checks

https://github.com/Consensys/teku/blob/87dcf1733df59d12d4e68923849e3512cfa2498e/ethereum/statetransition/src/main/java/tech/pegasys/teku/statetransition/util/AbstractIgnoringFutureHistoricalSlot.java#L54-L100

Because those guards return false, `onFirstSeen` never runs and `fetchMissingBlobsFromLocalEL` is never scheduled, permanently skipping EL reconstruction for the affected block/sidecars

https://github.com/Consensys/teku/blob/87dcf1733df59d12d4e68923849e3512cfa2498e/ethereum/statetransition/src/main/java/tech/pegasys/teku/statetransition/datacolumns/util/DataColumnSidecarELRecoveryManagerImpl.java#L326-L379

The equality requirement contradicts the wider historical tolerance (320 slots) already enforced by `shouldIgnoreItemAtSlot`, so a proposer can delay gossiping until just after the boundary and reliably suppress DAS recovery for that slot.

The timing bug lets a proposer withhold sidecars until just after the slot boundary so Teku never reconstructs them. Because Teku’s share of the network means this can keep more than 5 % of validators from sampling those columns

## POC

Paste this test in `DataColumnSidecarELRecoveryManagerImplTest.java` and run

```java
@Test
 public void onNewBlock_whenSlotAlreadyAdvanced_doesNotTriggerLocalRecovery() {
    final UInt64 originalSlot = currentSlot;
    final SignedBeaconBlock block =
        dataStructureUtil.randomSignedBeaconBlock(originalSlot.longValue());

    dataColumnSidecarELRecoveryManager.onSlot(originalSlot);
    dataColumnSidecarELRecoveryManager.onSlot(originalSlot.plus(1));
    dataColumnSidecarELRecoveryManager.onNewBlock(block, Optional.empty());

    verify(executionLayer, never()).engineGetBlobAndCellProofsList(any(), any());
    assertThat(asyncRunner.hasDelayedActions()).isFalse();
  }
```

## Recommendation

Relax the slot check (e.g., allow items up to the historical tolerance behind) so recovery tasks are still created

### Summary

Given that heartbeat for subnet & peers discovery is hardcoded to 30s. And that the delay for effective CGC change is minimum of 2 slots, its possible that we could just start discovering them in the last seconds before the next epoch, which could result in not being able to retrieve columns for Data availability check, thus a lighthouse node could end up failing the DA validity, as there would be no time to discover peers + make attestation.

### Root Cause

2 main things should be tracked when we talk about CGC change. CGC & sampling size are the amount of columns a node should custody, this CGC amount is crucial for also calculating deterministically which columns we should custody.

Since we do data availability check every block, its crucial that every node is being able to attest and import their block and signal that they have the availability of the columns they should custody.

The problem here is that the behaviour guaranteeing that we should find peers + subscribe to the new columns custody topics in advance, is **in some case insufficient**, especially during increase of the sampling size/cgc value. ( note that changes are triggered via `register_validators` hook function, which just updates validators and their balance )

Focus is on the inner `register_validators` called in In `validator_custody.rs`
```rust
    /// Register a new validator index and updates the list of validators if required.
    /// Returns `Some((effective_epoch, new_cgc))` if the registration results in a CGC update.
    pub(crate) fn register_validators<E: EthSpec>(
        &mut self,
        validators_and_balance: ValidatorsAndBalances,
        current_slot: Slot,
        spec: &ChainSpec,
    ) -> Option<(Epoch, u64)> {
        for (validator_index, effective_balance) in validators_and_balance {
            self.validators
                .insert(validator_index, (current_slot, effective_balance));
        }
        self.validators
            .retain(|_, (slot, _)| *slot >= current_slot - VALIDATOR_REGISTRATION_EXPIRY_SLOTS);

        let validator_custody_units = self.validators.values().map(|(_, eb)| eb).sum::<u64>()
            / spec.balance_per_additional_custody_group;
        let validator_custody_requirement =
            get_validators_custody_requirement(validator_custody_units, spec);

        if Some(validator_custody_requirement) > self.latest_validator_custody_requirement() {
@>>         // Apply the change from the next epoch after adding some delay buffer to ensure
            // the node has enough time to subscribe to subnets etc, and to avoid having
            // inconsistent column counts within an epoch.
@>>         let effective_delay_slots =
                CUSTODY_CHANGE_DA_EFFECTIVE_DELAY_SECONDS / spec.seconds_per_slot;
@>>         let effective_epoch =
                (current_slot + effective_delay_slots).epoch(E::slots_per_epoch()) + 1;
@>>         self.epoch_validator_custody_requirements
                .entry(effective_epoch)
                .and_modify(|old_custody| *old_custody = validator_custody_requirement)
                .or_insert(validator_custody_requirement);
            Some((effective_epoch, validator_custody_requirement))
        } else {
            None
        }
```

Currently we:
1. Make sure that we enforce `CUSTODY_CHANGE_DA_EFFECTIVE_DELAY_SECONDS` before making the sampling size effective. Where if we have less or equal to `CUSTODY_CHANGE_DA_EFFECTIVE_DELAY_SECONDS / slot_time`, i.e. 2 slots until the next `epoch N+1`. we will actually activate the CGC/sampling change in `epoch + 2`
2. This gives time for the heartbeat ( hardcodedly called every 30s ) to update the peers & find new ones for the new columns.

**Root Core**: But since `CUSTODY_CHANGE_DA_EFFECTIVE_DELAY_SECONDS` is also `30`, but with the rounding down of `slot_time` becomes 2 slots and since heartbeat is `30s`, its possible to end up in a case where we are 2 slots behind the next epoch and if heartbeat was just called, we could end up in a case that the next heartbeat is called just ~6 or more seconds ( 30- 12x2 slots, where 12 is seconds per slot ) AFTER we already started processing the new slot, or a few seconds before that. So `-6 to 6+`. This is dangerous as this is not enough time to find proper peers, especially if the CGC update was BIG and we need a lot more peers/columns subnets to subscribe to.

Moreover heartbeat doesn't immediately find peers, it would take about 60s to properly discover, based on network conditions. Hearbeat just queues discovery.

See `heartbeat()` function in `src/peer_manager/mod.rs` which is responsible for maintaining proper peers for custody columns:
```rust
