### Attack Path

Given 32 slots in an epoch.
Starting from `Epoch N`, and assuming slot indexes start from 1.

1. CGC increase happens on slot 30, and the `effective_epoch` in `register_validators` is calculated as following `(current_slot + effective_delay_slots).epoch(E::slots_per_epoch()) + 1;` or `epoch N + 1`. Thus in the next epoch just after 2 slots or `24seconds`.
( The gate makes sure that if we are less than 2 slots away we wait one more epoch, or WHOLE `34` slots in total, but the border is very close here)
2. Assume Heartbeat just completes before register validators hook call which updated sampling. ( heartbeat is hardcoded at 30s, [reference here](https://github.com/sigp/lighthouse/blob/e5b4983d6baf85770fe4539a565d8a2dd462bc53/beacon_node/lighthouse_network/src/peer_manager/mod.rs#L51-L53) )
3. When we reach the slot 1 of `Epoch N+1` we already need in a very limited time period make sure we custody the data in the data availability flow checks ( which happen [data_availability_checker](https://github.com/sigp/lighthouse/blob/unstable/beacon_node/beacon_chain/src/data_availability_checker.rs) and in the inner logic [here](https://github.com/sigp/lighthouse/blob/e5b4983d6baf85770fe4539a565d8a2dd462bc53/beacon_node/beacon_chain/src/data_availability_checker/overflow_lru_cache.rs#L216) ) 
4. Since we could end up in a case where heartbeat was just called or isn't even currently called and will be in a few seconds, we cannot possibly guarantee in both cases that we have peers that custody those new columns we are supposed to custody.
5. This results in the inability of the Lighthouse CL client not being able to verify the data availability in time and attest and import the block.

### Impact

This is dangerous as this is not enough time to find proper peers, especially if the CGC update was BIG and we need a lot more peers/columns subnets to subscribe to.
Big one would be 1x 32ETH validator -> +127 validators to `4096ETH`. Or basically infinite amount of validators, we could also add 200 validators in one go, doesn't matter, the bigger the worse effectively as more validators are impacted. But we could still get to this issue, even with just +5-10 validators could be more than enough to cause the issue, depending on how much columns they add to the custody sampling size. ( based on their balance )

If peer fails DA check this could potentially result in wrong fork-choice/consensus split ( for the nodes upgrading CGC ) as data availability is crucial part of the fork-choice. We DON'T import block unless data availability is present, see `beacon_chain.rs` and we have time window until which we have to make attestation
```rust
    /// Checks if the provided data column can make any cached blocks available, and imports immediately
    /// if so, otherwise caches the data column in the data availability checker.
    async fn check_gossip_data_columns_availability_and_import(
        self: &Arc<Self>,
        slot: Slot,
        block_root: Hash256,
        data_columns: Vec<GossipVerifiedDataColumn<T>>,
        publish_fn: impl FnOnce() -> Result<(), BlockError>,
    ) -> Result<AvailabilityProcessingStatus, BlockError> {
        if let Some(slasher) = self.slasher.as_ref() {
            for data_colum in &data_columns {
                slasher.accept_block_header(data_colum.signed_block_header());
            }
        }

        let availability = self
            .data_availability_checker
            .put_gossip_verified_data_columns(block_root, slot, data_columns)?;

@>>     self.process_availability(slot, availability, publish_fn)
            .await
    }
```

All lighthouse nodes are vulnerable.

### PoC

Let's validate first with a quick PoC the numerical examples above ( add in `validator_custody.go` file's test suite ):
```rust
    #[test]
    fn custody_effective_epoch_should_be_next_epoch_with_30s_delay() {
        type E = MainnetEthSpec;

        let spec = E::default_spec();
        // lets verify that mainnet slot time is 12s + delay constant is 30s
        assert_eq!(spec.seconds_per_slot, 12, "unexpected seconds_per_slot");
        assert_eq!(
            CUSTODY_CHANGE_DA_EFFECTIVE_DELAY_SECONDS,
            30,
            "unexpected CUSTODY_CHANGE_DA_EFFECTIVE_DELAY_SECONDS"
        );

        // 30s / 12s = 2 slots, cuz rounding down
        let effective_delay_slots =
            CUSTODY_CHANGE_DA_EFFECTIVE_DELAY_SECONDS / spec.seconds_per_slot;
        assert_eq!(effective_delay_slots, 2, "delay should be 2 slots");

        // 32 slots per epoch, slot 30 is still in epoch N=0.

        //WE use 29 as the number, not 30 of slot because INDEX counting starts from 0.
        //So the range is slot 0 to slot 31 is epoch 0. Which is still 32 slots
        //but its equivalent to the example in attack path, its just easier, to understand it.

        let current_slot = Slot::new(29); //counting from 0 so this is 30th slot, with index 29
        let current_epoch = current_slot.epoch(E::slots_per_epoch());

        // Code under test:
        let effective_epoch =
            (current_slot + effective_delay_slots).epoch(E::slots_per_epoch()) + 1;

        // Should become *next* epoch (N+1), which is just after 2 slots ( 24s )
        assert_eq!(
            effective_epoch,
            current_epoch + 1,
            "effective_epoch should be next epoch (N+1), not N+2"
        );
    }

```


Let's validate that we don't add new peers, if cgc suddenly changes and heartbeat isn't called to trigger peer selection ( add this in `src/peer_manager/mod.rs`). 

Note: *In reality even heartbeat doesn't add them immediately it just queues discovery for missing peers, which makes the impact even bigger*
```rust

    #[tokio::test]
    async fn cgc_change_does_not_trigger_discovery_until_heartbeat() {
        use std::collections::HashSet;
        use types::{DataColumnSubnetId, MainnetEthSpec as E};

        // Build PeerManager with discovery enabled.
        let spec = Arc::new(E::default_spec());
        let network_config = Arc::new(NetworkConfig {
            target_peers: 10,
            ..Default::default()
        });
        let globals = NetworkGlobals::new_test_globals(vec![], network_config, spec);
        let cfg = config::Config {
            discovery_enabled: true,   // <— important
            target_peer_count: 10,
            ..Default::default()
        };
        let mut pm: PeerManager<E> = PeerManager::new(cfg, Arc::new(globals)).unwrap();

        // Simulate CGC/sampling change: update the sampling subnets the PM reads.
        *pm.network_globals
            .sampling_subnets
            .write() = HashSet::from([DataColumnSubnetId::new(0), DataColumnSubnetId::new(1)]);

        // BEFORE heartbeat, nothing should be queued.
        assert!(
            pm.events
                .iter()
                .all(|e| !matches!(e, PeerManagerEvent::DiscoverSubnetPeers(_))),
            "no discovery should be queued before heartbeat/maintain_custody_peers"
