## Recommendation
Added validation of `subcommittee_index` range (0-3).
```diff
func (s *Server) ProduceSyncCommitteeContribution(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
    // ... other code

    _, index, ok := shared.UintFromQuery(w, r, "subcommittee_index", true)
    if !ok {
        return
    }

+   // Validate subcommittee_index range (0-3)
+   // The Sync committee consists of 4 subcommittees according to the Ethereum 2.0 specifications
+   if index > 3 {
+       httputil.HandleError(w, 
+           fmt.Sprintf("Invalid subcommittee_index %d, must be between 0 and 3", index), 
+           http.StatusBadRequest)
+       return
+   }

    _, slot, ok := shared.UintFromQuery(w, r, "slot", true)
    // ... other code
}
```

### Summary


Wrong logic for pruning, results in the node not being able to delete and clean up old data columns( no longer needed ), and the deletion logic is never retried because try_prune_blobs also wrongly advances BlobInfo.oldest_blob_slot even when no keys are actually deleted.

### Root Cause

In `src/hot_cold_store.rs` we use LevelDB (`src/database/leveldb_impl.rs`), and during prune_blobs we call `delete_if`

The problem is that `delete_if` implementation fails to “seek” to the column prefix and can skip entire columns, resulting in zero deletions.

https://github.com/sigp/lighthouse/blob/e5b4983d6baf85770fe4539a565d8a2dd462bc53/beacon_node/store/src/database/leveldb_impl.rs#L284-L295

```rust
// src/database/leveldb_impl.rs
pub fn delete_if(
    &self,
    column: DBColumn,
    mut f: impl FnMut(&[u8]) -> Result<bool, Error>,
) -> Result<(), Error> {
    let mut leveldb_batch = Writebatch::new();
    let iter = self.db.iter(self.read_options());

@>> iter.take_while(move |(key, _)| key.matches_column(column))
        .for_each(|(key, value)| {
            if f(&value).unwrap_or(false) { // Err => false (keep)
                let _timer = metrics::start_timer(&metrics::DISK_DB_DELETE_TIMES);
                metrics::inc_counter_vec(&metrics::DISK_DB_DELETE_COUNT, &[column.into()]);
                leveldb_batch.delete(key);  // single monolithic batch
            }
        });

    self.db.write(self.write_options().into(), &leveldb_batch)?; // single commit
    Ok(())
}
```

This is because in leveldb database the way we distinguish “columns” is by using a prefix, and the current logic stops immediately if we go onto the next prefix, but since we start from the index 0,( start), the `DBColumn::BeaconDataColumn` prefix, for example won’t be first and we will simply immediately stop without any deletions.

More specifically:

The code stops iterating immediately when it encounters a key that does not match the specified column, due to the use of

```rust
take_while(move
    |(key, _)| key.matches_column(column))
```

However, the 

```rust
iterator(self.db.iter(self.read_options())
```

  always starts from the very first key in the database, not from the start of the specified column. (leveldb is like key-value pair db, map-like, and we just have key prefixes as a way to distinguish columns)

And because the prune pointer still moves forward in `try_prune_blobs` logic in `hot_cold_store.rs`, the skipped ranges are never retried, leaving old blobs and data-columns permanently undeleted. This creates irreversible pruning gaps and unbounded disk growth over time.

Reference https://github.com/sigp/lighthouse/blob/e5b4983d6baf85770fe4539a565d8a2dd462bc53/beacon_node/store/src/hot_cold_store.rs#L3283-L3300

```rust
let remove_blob_if = |blobs_bytes: &[u8]| {
    let blobs = Vec::from_ssz_bytes(blobs_bytes)?; // Err propagates here ...
    let Some(blob): Option<&Arc<BlobSidecar<E>>> = blobs.first() else { return Ok(false); };
    if blob.slot() <= end_slot { removed_block_roots.push(blob.block_root()); return Ok(true); };
    Ok(false)
};

@>> self.blobs_db.delete_if(DBColumn::BeaconBlob, remove_blob_if)?;

// PeerDAS data columns
let remove_data_column_if = |blobs_bytes: &[u8]| {
    let data_column: DataColumnSidecar<E> = DataColumnSidecar::from_ssz_bytes(blobs_bytes)?; 
    if data_column.slot() <= end_slot { return Ok(true); };
    Ok(false)
};
@>> self.blobs_db.delete_if(DBColumn::BeaconDataColumn, remove_data_column_if)?;

// Unconditionally advance prune pointer even if deletes were no-op
@>> let new_blob_info = BlobInfo { oldest_blob_slot: Some(end_slot + 1), blobs_db: blob_info.blobs_db };
let op = self.compare_and_set_blob_info(blob_info, new_blob_info)?;
self.do_atomically_with_block_and_blobs_cache(vec![StoreOp::KeyValueOp(op)])?;
```

### Internal Pre-conditions

No preconditions, at all.

### External Pre-conditions

No preconditions, at all.

### Attack Path

<p>Over a long enough period the issue happens. As nodes are supposed to retain the blobs for a period of 18 days ( currently network-wide set ).</p>
<p>This is how blobs were designed in first place, only intended to be stored temporary.</p>
<p><a href="https://github.com/ethereum/consensus-specs/blob/master/specs/fulu/p2p-interface.md">https://github.com/ethereum/consensus-specs/blob/master/specs/fulu/p2p-interface.md</a></p>

MIN_EPOCHS_FOR_DATA_COLUMN_SIDECARS_REQUESTS | 2**12 (= 4096 epochs, ~18 days)
-- | --



<p>Its important to mention that since the bpo changes &amp; the Ethereum Foundation efforts towards scaling Ethereum, its expected blob amounts to increase significantly over time. Additionally now that data columns contain additional data for the recovery mechanism, its way easier to fill up disk space very fast.</p>
<p>Since in general nodes are expected to custody a maximum amount of data for those 18 days.  (based on the calculations of max blobs per block, over all this 18 days period )
The validator’s host is likely to predict this and use an appropriate amount of disk space.</p>
<p>However this means that we would need only 2-3 weeks at most, in most cases, after  those first 18 days of running the nodes, until a lot of them start to fail and go offline due to the lack of disk space.</p>
<p>Its planned to eventually go to high double digit blobs per block, like 30,40,50. So its a dangerous case. Even with the current max it is bad, due to the explanation bellow, because disk space will always adjust based on MAXIMUM possible expectations, which here are generally broken.</p>
<!-- notionvc: 949aed39-5ff4-4d3a-b4d2-5d40c36ce005 -->

### Impact

All lighthouse nodes are vulnerable, as explained in the attack path, this could result in the shutdown of many lighthouse nodes. Additionally this can happen at any time, including at a time where Lighthouse node is a proposer. Since they are over 41% of the network, this could result in serious problems.

### PoC

2 tests - 1 to prove the delete-If flaw and one to prove the wrong pointer advancement flaw. ( though even if the pointer didn’t advance, this is still a problem, as even if we retry, we would still never be able to delete the old blobs due to the delete_if function flaw in LevelDB )

Test for leveldb_impl.rs ( end of file )

```rust
#[cfg(test)]
mod tests {
    use super::*;
    use tempfile::TempDir;
    use types::MinimalEthSpec;

    type E = MinimalEthSpec;

    fn new_db() -> LevelDB<E> {
        let dir = TempDir::new().expect("temp dir");
        LevelDB::<E>::open(dir.path()).expect("open db")
    }

    fn start_key_for(col: DBColumn) -> Vec<u8> {
        let zeros = vec![0u8; col.key_size()];
        get_key_for_col(col, &zeros)
    }

    #[test]
    fn delete_if_without_seek_skips_the_second_column() {
        let db = new_db();

        // Compute true minimal encoded keys for both columns.
        let blob_start = start_key_for(DBColumn::BeaconBlob);
        let col_start  = start_key_for(DBColumn::BeaconDataColumn);

        // Decide which column actually sorts first.
        //this is easier for the test, there are in reality many keys in the LEVELDB db
        //and the BeaconDataColumn is not first
        let (first_col, second_col) = if blob_start <= col_start {
            (DBColumn::BeaconBlob, DBColumn::BeaconDataColumn)
        } else {
            (DBColumn::BeaconDataColumn, DBColumn::BeaconBlob)
        };

        // Put one key in each column.
        let first_key  = b"k1";
        let second_key = b"k2";

        db.put_bytes(first_col,  first_key,  b"first").unwrap();
        db.put_bytes(second_col, second_key, b"second").unwrap();

        assert!(db.key_exists(first_col,  first_key).unwrap());
        assert!(db.key_exists(second_col, second_key).unwrap());

        // Because delete_if does NOT seek to the start of second_col, the iterator starts at the
        // very first global key (in first_col). The first key doesn't match second_col, so
        // take_while(|k| k.matches(second_col)) ends immediately -> zero rows deleted
        db.delete_if(second_col, |_v| Ok(true)).unwrap();

        // The second column key must still exist (it was never visited).
        assert!(
            db.key_exists(second_col, second_key).unwrap(),
            "Second-column row should still exist (delete_if visited 0 keys)"
        );

        //Deleting from the FIRST column works, becahse iteration starts on it
        db.delete_if(first_col, |_v| Ok(true)).unwrap();
        assert!(
            !db.key_exists(first_col, first_key).unwrap(),
            "First-column row should be deleted"
        );
    }
}
```

Put this in `hot_colt_store.rs` ( at the end )

```rust
#[cfg(test)]
mod prune_blob_tests {
    use super::*;
    use crate::config::StoreConfig;
    use crate::hot_cold_store::HotColdDB;
    use crate::memory_store::MemoryStore;
    use crate::KeyValueStore;
    use std::sync::Arc;
    use types::{MainnetEthSpec, ChainSpec};

    type E = MainnetEthSpec;

    /// we will test that try_prune_blobs advances `BlobInfo.oldest_blob_slot` even when no blobs are actually deleted.
    #[test]
    fn prune_blobs_advances_pointer_and_deletes_nothing() {
        let mut spec = ChainSpec::mainnet();
        spec.deneb_fork_epoch = Some(Epoch::new(0));
        let spec = Arc::new(spec);

        let mut config = StoreConfig::default();
        config.prune_blobs = true;
        config.blob_prune_margin_epochs = 0;
        config.epochs_per_blob_prune = 1; // prune every epoch window

        let store: HotColdDB<E, MemoryStore<E>, MemoryStore<E>> = HotColdDB::open_ephemeral(config, spec.clone()).expect("open ephemeral store");

        // Chosen start epoch for simulated oldest blob slot.
        let start_epoch = Epoch::new(5);
        let start_slot = start_epoch.start_slot(E::slots_per_epoch());

        // Provide a split far in the future so pruning is bounded by DA boundary not split.
        let split_epoch = start_epoch + 20;
        let split_slot = split_epoch.start_slot(E::slots_per_epoch());
        store.set_split(split_slot, Hash256::zero(), Hash256::zero());

        let new_anchor = AnchorInfo {
            anchor_slot: start_slot,
            oldest_block_slot: start_slot,
            oldest_block_parent: Hash256::zero(),
            state_upper_limit: start_slot,
            state_lower_limit: Slot::new(0),
        };
        let _ =store.compare_and_set_anchor_info(ANCHOR_UNINITIALIZED, new_anchor).expect("set anchor info");

        let initial_blob_info = store.get_blob_info();
        let updated_blob_info = BlobInfo { oldest_blob_slot: Some(start_slot), blobs_db: true };
        let _ = store.compare_and_set_blob_info(initial_blob_info, updated_blob_info).expect("set blob info");

        // Ensure there are no blob keys present.
        let initial_blob_key_count = store
            .blobs_db
            .iter_column::<Vec<u8>>(DBColumn::BeaconBlob)
            .count();
        assert_eq!(initial_blob_key_count, 0, "precondition: no blob entries exist");
        // Choose a data availability boundary sufficiently ahead so that pruning window includes at least one epoch.
        let da_boundary = start_epoch + 10;

        // Execute pruning. No blobs exist, so nothing should actually be deleted.
        store.try_prune_blobs(false, da_boundary).expect("prune blobs");

        // re-verify
        let final_blob_key_count = store
            .blobs_db
            .iter_column::<Vec<u8>>(DBColumn::BeaconBlob)
            .count();
        assert_eq!(final_blob_key_count, 0, "no blobs should have been deleted because none existed");

        // Compute expected (current buggy behaviour) advancement.
        // end_epoch = min(da_boundary - margin - 1, split_epoch - 1)
        let margin = store.get_config().blob_prune_margin_epochs;
        let end_epoch = min(da_boundary - margin - 1, split_epoch - 1);
        assert!(end_epoch >= start_epoch, "test invariant: pruning window should include start epoch");
        let end_slot = end_epoch.end_slot(E::slots_per_epoch());
        let expected_advanced_oldest = end_slot + 1;

        let final_blob_info = store.get_blob_info();
        assert_eq!(final_blob_info.oldest_blob_slot, Some(expected_advanced_oldest),
            "oldest_blob_slot advanced to {:?} despite zero deletions", expected_advanced_oldest);
    }
}

```

### Mitigation

In LevelDB seek the index we should start iterating from + make sure that we advance pointer in hot_cold_storage.rs ONLY if blobs/data was actually deleted.

### Summary

The beacon node caches EngineCapabilities but never invalidates them at fork boundaries. Calls like `get_engine_capabilities(None)` always return the cached value, and the watchdog only refreshes every 15 minutes. This means that if the cache was populated before a fork, the BN may continue to believe methods like `engine_getPayloadV5` or `engine_getBlobsV2` are not supported, even though the EL is already serving them. In that window, block production or blob retrieval can fail.

### Root Cause

https://github.com/sigp/lighthouse/blob/e5b4983d6baf85770fe4539a565d8a2dd462bc53/beacon_node/execution_layer/src/engine_api/http.rs#L595-L599

The core issue is in CachedResponse::older_than:

```rust
pub fn older_than(&self, age_limit: Option<Duration>) -> bool {
    age_limit.is_some_and(|limit| self.age() >= limit)
}
```

With None passed, the result is always false. So in get_engine_capabilities(None) the cached data is always considered “fresh”:

```rust
if let Some(lock) = lock.as_ref().filter(|c| !c.older_than(age_limit)) {
    return Ok(lock.data()); // never refreshed
}
```

This is why capability flags can remain stale across an activation until the 15-minute watchdog runs or an error forces a retry.

### Internal Pre-conditions

-

### External Pre-conditions

In practice, most ELs already sidestep this by returning the *final set* of methods far ahead of activation. For example, Geth uses reflection to list every defined RPC, Besu enumerates all engine methods in its enum, and Nethermind calls GetFinalSpec() to include all forked versions. Erigon and Reth also already return engine_getPayloadV5. 

Examples:

https://github.com/erigontech/erigon/blob/f16ac63e91f2a2ba918d81197a091e30512b72ef/execution/engineapi/engine_api_methods.go#L30-L48

https://github.com/hyperledger/besu/blob/f1e4953adb4eaa00623ba59a4fa251ffaa4dbc6c/ethereum/api/src/main/java/org/hyperledger/besu/ethereum/api/jsonrpc/internal/methods/engine/EngineExchangeCapabilities.java#L74-L80

So by the time Fulu or PeerDAS activates, the BN cache already contains true for the new flags. 

The only case in which this could be triggered is IF some nodes decide to update their EL last minute just before the fork. Which can realistically happen.

### Attack Path

1. Node upgrades EL ~0-15 minutes before the scheduled fork block. 
2. We have already cached and cache expires in 15 minutes
3. The fork happens and the CL still returns that the EL is lacking new capabilities
4. The result of that is that we cannot use new endpoints and we cannot process and propose new blocks, thus our node is prone to being punished and possibly losing ETH fund rewards.

### Impact

During that stale window, a validator could miss a proposal (engine_getPayloadV5 gated off, local build aborts) or fail to fetch blobs (get_blobs_v2=false). Losses are immediate (MEV, rewards).

The impact is high for the affected nodes as it renders them mostly useless and can also result in restricted, but possibly lost funds.

### PoC

Add this at the end  in the  `http.rs` file, specifically in the already existing mod test {} scope

```rust
   #[tokio::test]
    async fn capabilities_cache_stale_across_activation_without_age_limit() {
        use std::time::Duration;

        // First response: pre-activation caps (no V5/V2)
        //. Second response: post-activation caps (now includes V5/V2)
        let pre_caps = json!({
            "id": STATIC_ID,
            "jsonrpc": JSONRPC_VERSION,
            "result": [] // nothing advertised => v5/v2 are false
        });
        let post_caps = json!({
            "id": STATIC_ID,
            "jsonrpc": JSONRPC_VERSION,
            "result": [
                ENGINE_GET_PAYLOAD_V5,
                ENGINE_GET_BLOBS_V2
            ]
        });

        Tester::new(true)
            .with_preloaded_responses(vec![pre_caps, post_caps], |client| async move {
                // Populate cache with the *pre-activation* snapshot.
                let caps0 = client
                    .get_engine_capabilities(Some(Duration::ZERO)) // force fetch & cache
                    .await
                    .expect("caps0");
                assert!(!caps0.get_payload_v5);
                assert!(!caps0.get_blobs_v2);

                // EL has "activated" (post_caps queued), but callers use `None`.
                // Because older_than(None) == false, this *returns cached* and does NOT fetch.
                let caps_stale = client
                    .get_engine_capabilities(None)
                    .await
                    .expect("caps_stale");
                assert!(
                    !caps_stale.get_payload_v5 && !caps_stale.get_blobs_v2,
                    "age_limit=None should return the stale cached snapshot"
                );

                // Manually get the latest EL's updated capabilities.
                let caps_fresh = client
                    .get_engine_capabilities(Some(Duration::ZERO))
                    .await
                    .expect("caps_fresh");
                assert!(caps_fresh.get_payload_v5);
                assert!(caps_fresh.get_blobs_v2);
            })
            .await;
    }

```

### Mitigation

The BN should refresh capabilities automatically at fork boundaries. A simple hook is to clear and re-fetch on forkchoice_updated, or even just before each epoch transition. 

That way, even if an operator upgrades late and the EL only starts advertising the new RPCs right at activation, the BN won’t keep using a stale snapshot.

### Summary

`custody_lookup_request` derives custody column indices from the **node’s current epoch** instead of the requested **block’s epoch**. 
The single-block lookup flow wrongly requests indices for the **current epoch**.

### Root Cause

The epoch used to compute custody indices is taken from chain.epoch() inside the network layer, and the block epoch is not passed through.

in `single_block_lookup.rs`, see the `pub fn continue_requests(` function, for should_fetch we use the requested block:

https://github.com/sigp/lighthouse/blob/e5b4983d6baf85770fe4539a565d8a2dd462bc53/beacon_node/network/src/sync/block_lookups/single_block_lookup.rs#L226-L241

```rust
// Uses the block's epoch to decide custody vs blobs (correct).
...
let expected_blobs = block.num_expected_blobs();
let block_epoch = block.slot().epoch(T::EthSpec::slots_per_epoch());
if expected_blobs == 0 {
    self.component_requests = ComponentRequests::NotNeeded("no data");
} else if cx.chain.should_fetch_blobs(block_epoch) {
    self.component_requests = ComponentRequests::ActiveBlobRequest(
        BlobRequestState::new(self.block_root), expected_blobs);
} else if cx.chain.should_fetch_custody_columns(block_epoch) {
    self.component_requests = ComponentRequests::ActiveCustodyRequest(
        CustodyRequestState::new(self.block_root)); // custody decided for block_epoch
} else {
    self.component_requests = ComponentRequests::NotNeeded("outside da window");
}
...
```

But then in the request itself we handle it via `custody_lookup_request`  which uses the 

        .sampling_columns_for_epoch(current_epoch)

function and respectfully wrongly `current_epoch` which could have different indices required for Data availability check.

```rust
//@>> computes ColumnIndex for current epoch, not the block's epoch.
...
pub fn custody_lookup_request(
    &mut self, lookup_id: SingleLookupId, block_root: Hash256, lookup_peers: Arc<RwLock<HashSet<PeerId>>>,
) -> Result<LookupRequestResult, RpcRequestSendError> {
    let custody_indexes_imported = self.chain
        .data_availability_checker.cached_data_column_indexes(&block_root)
        .unwrap_or_default();

    let current_epoch = self.chain.epoch().map_err(|e| ... )?; // WRONG epoch source

    let custody_indexes_to_fetch = self.chain
        .sampling_columns_for_epoch(current_epoch)            // WRONG indices
        .iter().copied()
        .filter(|i| !custody_indexes_imported.contains(i))
        .collect::<Vec<_>>();
    ...
}
```

When block_epoch != current_epoch, the request current target indices for the wrong epoch.

### Internal Pre-conditions

-

### External Pre-conditions

-

### Attack Path

1. A peer (or ordinary network timing) delivers a block from epoch **E** while the local node is already in epoch **E+1**. 
2. The lookup chooses custody (based on **E**) but requests indices for **E+1**. 
3. More indices are requested for the DA check, which slows the process.

### Impact

During CGC changed epochs, a mismatch wastes time, over-requests columns, and could in some cases wrongly penalize honest peers, degrade connectivity and delaying DA/sync progress around boundaries.

### PoC

_No response_

### Mitigation

Make the custody pipeline **epoch-aware end-to-end**:

```rust
// 1) Carry the block’s epoch in the request state.
pub struct CustodyRequestState {
    block_root: Hash256,
    custody_epoch: Epoch, // NEW
    /* ... */
}

// at creation
let block_epoch = block.slot().epoch(T::EthSpec::slots_per_epoch());
self.component_requests = ComponentRequests::ActiveCustodyRequest(
    CustodyRequestState { block_root: self.block_root, custody_epoch: block_epoch }
);

// 2) Thread epoch into the network call.
cx.custody_lookup_request(id, self.block_root, lookup_peers, custody_epoch)

// 3) Use the passed epoch to compute indices.
pub fn custody_lookup_request(
    &mut self,
    lookup_id: SingleLookupId,
    block_root: Hash256,
    lookup_peers: Arc<RwLock<HashSet<PeerId>>>,
    custody_epoch: Epoch,                      // NEW
) -> Result<LookupRequestResult, RpcRequestSendError> {
    let imported = self.chain.data_availability_checker
        .cached_data_column_indexes(&block_root)
        .unwrap_or_default();

    let needed = self.chain
        .sampling_columns_for_epoch(custody_epoch) // FIX: epoch of the block
        .iter()
        .copied()
        .filter(|i| !imported.contains(i))
        .collect::<Vec<_>>();

    // peer selection should also key off custody_epoch internally
    // ...
}
```

### Summary

Range and backfill partial custody-column retries swallow NoPeer errors and return success, which leaves batches permanently stalled when no eligible custody peers are available for the missing columns.

The bug occurs in `sync/range_sync/chain.retry_partial_batch` and `sync/backfill_sync/mod.retry_partial_batch`. When a NoPeer error occurs, the batch never progresses.

### Root Cause

When retrying missing custody columns, the client calls into the column retry logic.

This happens after `send_batch` partially fails for certain columns.

If no peers are eligible custodians for the requested columns, the selection function returns a NoPeer error.
The root problem here is that instead of rescheduling or resetting state, both retry paths just log the error and return success, this results in the the batch being stuck in a state where block downloads have completed but some custody columns are missing, with no further requests sent, which could temporary stall the node, and result in missed proposals, to the least.

Let’s walk through the problematic path,  the bad place we enter is the `retry_partial_batch`

https://github.com/sigp/lighthouse/blob/e5b4983d6baf85770fe4539a565d8a2dd462bc53/beacon_node/network/src/sync/range_sync/chain.rs#L892 ( we end up calling it via `inject_error` in `src/sync/range_sync/chain.rs` )

```solidity
fn retry_partial_batch(
    &mut self, network: &mut SyncNetworkContext<T>, batch_id: BatchId, id: Id,
    failed_columns: HashSet<ColumnIndex>, mut failed_peers: HashSet<PeerId>,
) -> ProcessingResult {
    ...
@>>    match network.retry_columns_by_range(id, &synced_peers, &failed_peers, req, &failed_columns) {
        Ok(_) => { debug!(...?); return Ok(KeepChain); }
@>>        Err(e) => { debug!(?batch_id, id, e, "Failed to retry partial batch"); } // swallow NoPeer
    }
    Ok(KeepChain) // no requeue, batch remains stalled
}
```

`range_sync/chain.rs.inject_error` proves this path is taken on `DataColumnPeerFailure`:

```solidity
pub fn inject_error(
match coupling_error {
  CouplingError::DataColumnPeerFailure { faulty_peers, exceeded_retries, ... } => {
    ...
    if !*exceeded_retries {
@>>      return self.retry_partial_batch(network, batch_id, request_id, failed_columns, failed_peers);
    }
  }
  ...
}
```

The above path in `retry_partial_batch` then calls 

`retry_columns_by_range` , which ends up calling  `select_columns_by_range_peers_to_request` in `network_context.rs` :

```solidity
fn select_columns_by_range_peers_to_request(
  &self, custody_indexes: &HashSet<ColumnIndex>, peers: &HashSet<PeerId>, ...
) -> Result<HashMap<PeerId, Vec<ColumnIndex>>, RpcRequestSendError> {
    for column_index in custody_indexes {
        let Some(custody_peer) = peers.iter().filter(|peer| {
            self.network_globals().is_custody_peer_of(*column_index, peer) // none => NoPeer
        })...
        else {
@>>            return Err(RpcRequestSendError::NoPeer(NoPeerError::CustodyPeer(*column_index)));
        };
        columns_to_request_by_peer.entry(custody_peer).or_default().push(*column_index);
    }
    Ok(columns_to_request_by_peer)
}
```

And the NoPeer error is returned and no retry happens above in `inject_error`

### Internal Pre-conditions

The partial success path must be taken, meaning that some components succeeded but certain custody columns remain missing. 

The retry logic is triggered after a coupling error such as a data column or peer failure. 

Then, If the peer selection for those failed columns returns empty, the NoPeer branch is reached.

### External Pre-conditions

This requires a situation where there are genuinely no connected peers advertising custody for the specific columns in question. 

That can happen when our peers for X and Y and Z columns become unresponsive, we try to maintain 2 peers per columns ( in lighthouse logic ) , so its possible that in some cases they could get problems with certain columns or be unresponsive.

### Attack Path

This problematic path is both valid for sync and backfill logic. After send_batch partially fails we end up in the above retry flow ( described in the root cause section )

Its also important to mention that we end up in the above problematic flow, when we process the result from the `send_batch` function in `on_range_components_response`
(there are 2 implementations for send_batch, one for sync and one for backfill logic, same for retry )

```rust
    fn on_range_components_response(
    ) {
        if let Some(resp) = self
            .network
            .range_block_component_response(range_request_id, range_block_component)
        {
            match resp {
            //@audit ok is processed normally
@>>                Ok(blocks) => {
 ...
                }
                //@audit we care about the bad path calling the inject_error here after the
                //range_block_component_response concludes that some columns weren't
                //succesffully retrieved
                Err(e) => match range_request_id.requester {
                    RangeRequestId::RangeSync { chain_id, batch_id } => {
                        self.range_sync.inject_error(
                            &mut self.network,
                            peer_id,
                            batch_id,
                            chain_id,
                            range_request_id.id,
                            e,
                        );
                        self.update_sync_state();
                    }
                    RangeRequestId::BackfillSync { batch_id } => {
                        match self.backfill_sync.inject_error(
                            &mut self.network,
                            batch_id,
                            &peer_id,
                            range_request_id.id,
                            e,
                        ) {
                            Ok(_) => {}
                            Err(_) => self.update_sync_state(),
                        }
                    }
                },
            }
        }
    }
```

1. Lighthouse node begins syncing a batch and requests custody columns for the relevant epoch.
2. Bad peers miss to provide some data for  blocks or fail to return some columns during the `send_batch` function, which in reality they should custody. ( can happen also naturally if the peer has liveness problems due to network conditions ) - we have a flow to handle that, as shown above, but the problem is that we STALL for NoPeer error in error flow.
3. Thus, no connected peers advertise custody for the missing columns.
4. Victim retries, receives NoPeer, and the batch becomes permanently stalled.

### Impact

Once this condition occurs, the affected batch will never progress. The node remains stuck with missing custody components and no new RPCs are issued.

This can prevent blocks from being imported and could also cause missing proposal rewards.

### PoC

Put this test at the end of the `chain.rs` file:

```rust

#[cfg(test)]
mod stalled_retry_poc_tests {
    use super::*;
    use lighthouse_network::rpc::BlocksByRangeRequest;
    use std::collections::HashSet;
    use crate::sync::network_context::NoPeerError;
   ///   1) The retry path was called exactly once.
    ///   2) The error path was taken (we got `NoPeer`)
    ///   3) The wrapper still returned `Ok(KeepChain)` (the swallow of the error)
    ///   4) We attempted to retry exactly the set of failed columns we passed in.
    #[test]
    fn retry_partial_batch_swallows_nopeer_and_returns_ok() {
        // Emulate inputs typically received after a partial custody failure.
        let batch_id = Epoch::new(123);
        let id: Id = 42;
        let failed_columns: HashSet<ColumnIndex> = [7u64, 9u64]
            .into_iter()
            .map(|n| n as ColumnIndex)
            .collect();

        let failed_peers: HashSet<PeerId> = HashSet::new();
        let req = BlocksByRangeRequest::new(1024, 32);

        // ---- Stub network that returns NoPeer for custody columns ---
        struct NetNoPeer {
            calls: usize,
            last_failed_len: usize,
            hit_nopeer: bool,
        }

        impl NetNoPeer {
            fn new() -> Self {
                Self {
                    calls: 0,
                    last_failed_len: 0,
                    hit_nopeer: false,
                }
            }

            #[allow(clippy::too_many_arguments)]
            fn retry_columns_by_range(
                &mut self,
                _id: Id,
                _peers: &HashSet<PeerId>,
                _peers_to_deprioritize: &HashSet<PeerId>,
                _request: BlocksByRangeRequest,
                failed_columns: &HashSet<ColumnIndex>,
            ) -> Result<(), RpcRequestSendError> {
                self.calls += 1;
                self.last_failed_len = failed_columns.len();
                self.hit_nopeer = true;

                // Mirror the selection failure that bubbles up from:
                // select_columns_by_range_peers_to_request(..) -> Err(RpcRequestSendError::NoPeer(..))
                Err(RpcRequestSendError::NoPeer(
                    NoPeerError::CustodyPeer(7 as ColumnIndex),
                ))
            }
        }

        // ---- The exact branch shape used by retry_partial_batch ----
        // Ok(_) => return Ok(KeepChain)
        // Err(e) => log and still return Ok(KeepChain)
        fn simulated_retry_partial_batch_like_branch(
            network: &mut NetNoPeer,
            id: Id,
            req: BlocksByRangeRequest,
            failed_columns: &HashSet<ColumnIndex>,
            failed_peers: &HashSet<PeerId>,
        ) -> Result<KeepChain, String> {
            // our stub returns NoPeer anyway....
            let synced_peers = HashSet::<PeerId>::new();
            match network.retry_columns_by_range(id, &synced_peers, failed_peers, req, failed_columns)
            {
                Ok(_) => Ok(KeepChain),
                Err(_e) => {
                    // This mirrors production today: only logs, then returns Ok(KeepChain).
                    Ok(KeepChain)
                }
            }
        }
        let mut net = NetNoPeer::new();
        let outcome = simulated_retry_partial_batch_like_branch(
            &mut net,
            id,
            req,
            &failed_columns,
            &failed_peers,
        )
            .expect("branch returns Ok(KeepChain ) even on NoPeer");

        // 1) We DID attempt a retry (exactly once)
        assert_eq!(
            net.calls, 1,
            "expected a single call to retry_columns_by_range (we attempted the retry)"
        );

        // 2) The retry hit the `NoPeer` branch (the condition we’re exposing).
        assert!(
            net.hit_nopeer,
            "expected the network stub to take the NoPeer path"
        );

        // 3) The wrapper returned success, by giving us Ok(KeepChain) despite NoPeer, proving the swallow
        let _keep_chain: KeepChain = outcome; // type-checks the success variant

        // assert that we tried to re-request exactly the failed columns we passed in.
        assert_eq!(
            net.last_failed_len,
            failed_columns.len(),
            "the retry attempted to re-request the same number of failed columns; epoch {:?}",
            batch_id
        );
    }
}
```

### Mitigation

Treat NoPeer as a requeue condition: abort the stale request, reset the batch to awaiting download, and reschedule when new peers are available.

### Summary

`propose_blinded_beacon_block` awaits the builder POST (v2) without any proposer-side timeout. That means a slow or malicious builder (or a slow network path to it) can hold the proposer until the slot deadline passes and the slot is missed.

### Root Cause

The proposer directly awaits a builder-client HTTP call and only records how long it took via `timed_future`. There is no tokio::time::timeout (or other cancellation) around the POST. timed_future does not enforce a time limit, it just measures duration. So if the builder stalls, the proposer task is blocked until the builder responds and the slot could be missed.

see `propose_blinded_beacon_block` in `src/lib.rs`

https://github.com/sigp/lighthouse/blob/e5b4983d6baf85770fe4539a565d8a2dd462bc53/beacon_node/execution_layer/src/lib.rs#L1909

In the `post_builder_blinded_blocks_v2` which is used post-FULU:

```rust
 pub async fn propose_blinded_beacon_block(
    &self,
    block_root: Hash256,
    block: &SignedBlindedBeaconBlock<E>,
    spec: &ChainSpec,
) -> Result<SubmitBlindedBlockResponse<E>, Error> {
    debug!(?block_root, "Sending block to builder");
@>>    if spec.is_fulu_scheduled() {
        self.post_builder_blinded_blocks_v2(block_root, block)
            .await
            .map(|()| SubmitBlindedBlockResponse::V2)
    } else {
        // v1 path...
        ...
    }
}

async fn post_builder_blinded_blocks_v2(
    &self,
    block_root: Hash256,
    block: &SignedBlindedBeaconBlock<E>,
) -> Result<(), Error> {
    if let Some(builder) = self.builder() {
@>>        let (result, duration) = timed_future(metrics::POST_BLINDED_PAYLOAD_BUILDER, async {
            let ssz_enabled = builder.is_ssz_available();
            if ssz_enabled {
                builder.post_builder_blinded_blocks_v2_ssz(block).await.map_err(Error::Builder)
            } else {
                builder.post_builder_blinded_blocks_v2(block).await.map_err(Error::Builder)
            }
        }).await;
@>>        match result { Ok(()) => { /* success */ } Err(e) => { /* handle error */ } }
    } else { Err(Error::NoPayloadBuilder) }
}

//@audit timed future used above ^^^
async fn timed_future<F: Future<Output = T>, T>(metric: &str, future: F) -> (T, Duration) {
    let start = Instant::now();
@>>    let result = future.await;           // <--- no timeout here
    let duration = start.elapsed();
    metrics::observe_timer_vec(&metrics::EXECUTION_LAYER_REQUEST_TIMES, &[metric], duration);
    (result, duration)
}
```

### Internal Pre-conditions

.

### External Pre-conditions

.

### Attack Path

Its important to mention that this is a legit scenario, because in general when we use a builder/relay, WE STILL do validation to check relay payload validity, via 
`verify_builder_bid` within `determine_and_fetch_payload` 

https://github.com/sigp/lighthouse/blob/e5b4983d6baf85770fe4539a565d8a2dd462bc53/beacon_node/execution_layer/src/lib.rs#L1139-L1233

https://github.com/sigp/lighthouse/blob/e5b4983d6baf85770fe4539a565d8a2dd462bc53/beacon_node/execution_layer/src/lib.rs#L1183-L1192

If the relay (builder) returns a **bad/invalid payload**, Lighthouse **rejects it** and falls back to the **local EL payload** when one is available.

However as described above, there isn’t anything to protect from stalled builder/relayer. This is a possible scenario and by Sherlock’s rules classify into the “honest EXTERNAL admin mistake”, because even though we configure a relay/builder, we do have validations to protect from it being bad and providing bad payload as shown in the above reference for verifying the payload. 

BUT we lack a way to avoid our node being stalled when the relayer is stuck/unresponsive.

1. It could happen some times that the builder/relay the validator uses stalls or has some problems.
2. During payload selection the beacon node chooses the builder’s payload because it validates the bid and the builder’s value beats the local block.
3. At proposal time the BN calls `propose_blinded_beacon_block(...)` which calls `post_builder_blinded_blocks_v2(...)`, and the node awaits the builder POST with no proposer-side timeout.
4. The attacker stalls the HTTP POST (hold the TCP connection, drip the response, or just delay reply). Because the code awaits unbounded, the proposer task is blocked, misses the slot, and the validator loses that slot’s fees/MEV.

Validators commonly rely on external builders, which can be slow for benign reasons (heavy work, GC, network congestion) or maliciously slowed by an attacker. The code already runs validation and fallback selection logic (it fetches builder and local payloads and compares values), but that fallback logic is ineffective if the call that submits the blinded block to the builder can block forever. 

TLDR: Selection is sensible, but the submission step has no timeout/fallback and becomes a single point of failure.

### Impact

A stalled builder POST can block the proposer past the slot deadline, causing a missed proposal and permanent loss of the slot’s priority fees / MEV, which is a loss of 0.1-0.3ETH.

Since lighthouse is huge part of the network, almost every second proposal will be by a lighthouse CL, which further increases the chances that if this occurs multiple times in a row it could stall the whole network, as the proposals would be missed and slots would be empty.

### PoC

Place this test at the end in `beacon_node/execution_layer/src/lib.rs` in the already existing mod test {} scope.

```rust
        #[tokio::test]
        async fn timed_future_allows_unbounded_wait_poc() {
            use std::time::Duration;
            use tokio::time::Instant;

            // we iwll measure how long a future takes but does not cancel it
            // We use arbitrary value and await a future that sleeps for X ms and
            // assert the timed_future waited at least that long. If the function
            // enforced a timeout it would have returned earlier (or errored)
            let sleep_ms = 10*1000u64; //10secs
            let start = Instant::now();

            // Call timed_future with an inner future that just sleeps.
            // The inner future returns a sentinel value so we can assert it was returned.
            let (val, duration) = timed_future("poc_timed_future", async {
                sleep(Duration::from_millis(sleep_ms)).await;
                0x42u8
            })
                .await;

            let elapsed = start.elapsed();

            assert_eq!(val, 0x42u8, "inner future must return its value");

            // Assert that timed_future waited at least ~sleep_ms milliseconds.
            // use a slightly smaller threshold to avoid flaky timing
            assert!(
                duration >= Duration::from_millis(sleep_ms - 20),
                "timed_future duration ({:?}) was shorter than expected sleep ({:?})",
                duration,
                Duration::from_millis(sleep_ms)
            );
            // This ensures timed_future awaited the future rather than returning immediately.
            assert!(
                elapsed >= Duration::from_millis(sleep_ms - 20),
                "wall-clock elapsed ({:?}) shorter than expected",
                elapsed
            );
        }
```

### Mitigation

Add a proposer-side deadline, i.e. wrap the builder POST in a timeout (for example tokio::time::timeout_at) so the proposer does not wait forever. On timeout return a distinct error (e.g. Error::BuilderTimeout) and let the caller perform an immediate fallback to use the local payload if available and safe, as it is now when the relayer returns invalid payload.

## Summary

`DiskFileBlobStoreInner::insert_one` and `insert_many` update in-memory indices and cache before persisting sidecars to disk. Inevitably, upon LRU eviction (or disk-write failures), `get_by_versioned_hashes_v2` cannot resolve required blobs and returns `None` (all-or-nothing), causing builders’ `engine_getBlobsv2` to fail and abort payload assembly. This is an atomicity/consistency bug amplified by EIP-7594 PeerDAS and EIP-7892 BPO throughput.

## Finding Description

Non-atomic “publish before persist” leaves stale directory entries and no rollback:

```solidity
// crates/transaction-pool/src/blobstore/disk.rs

fn insert_one(&self, tx: B256, data: BlobTransactionSidecarVariant) -> Result<(), BlobStoreError> {
    let mut buf = Vec::with_capacity(data.rlp_encoded_fields_length());
    data.rlp_encode_fields(&mut buf);

    { // publish vhash→tx first
        let mut map = self.versioned_hashes_to_txhash.lock();
        data.versioned_hashes().for_each(|hash| { map.insert(hash, tx); });
    }
    self.blob_cache.lock().insert(tx, Arc::new(data)); // publish cache next

    let size = self.write_one_encoded(tx, &buf)?;      // persist last (may fail)
    self.size_tracker.add_size(size);
    self.size_tracker.inc_len(1);
    Ok(())
}
```

Persistence is direct write to final path; no atomic rename; no rollback on failure:

```solidity
// crates/transaction-pool/src/blobstore/disk.rs

fn write_one_encoded(&self, tx: B256, data: &[u8]) -> Result<usize, DiskFileBlobStoreError> {
    let path = self.blob_disk_file(tx);
    let _lock = self.file_lock.write();
    if !path.exists() {
        fs::write(&path, data) // failure leaves prior in-mem publishes intact
            .map_err(|e| DiskFileBlobStoreError::WriteFile(tx, path, e))?;
        return Ok(data.len())
    }
    Ok(0)
}
```

`get_by_versioned_hashes_v2` is cache-first, then uses the vhash→tx map; v2 semantics are all-or-nothing:

```solidity
// crates/transaction-pool/src/blobstore/disk.rs

fn get_by_versioned_hashes_v2(&self, versioned_hashes: &[B256])
 -> Result<Option<Vec<BlobAndProofV2>>, BlobStoreError> {
    let mut result = vec![None; versioned_hashes.len()];

    for (_tx_hash, blob_sidecar) in self.inner.blob_cache.lock().iter() { ... } // cache only

    let mut missing_tx_hashes = Vec::new();
    {
        let mut idx = self.inner.versioned_hashes_to_txhash.lock();
        for (i, _) in result.iter().enumerate().filter(|(_, v)| v.is_none()) {
            if let Some(tx_hash) = idx.get(&versioned_hashes[i]).copied() {
                missing_tx_hashes.push(tx_hash); // no vhash→tx mapping => no disk read
            }
        }
    }
    if !missing_tx_hashes.is_empty() {
        let blobs_from_disk = self.inner.read_many_decoded(missing_tx_hashes);
        ...
    }
    if result.iter().all(|x| x.is_some()) { Ok(Some(...)) } else { Ok(None) }   // strict v2
}
```

Missing files are silently skipped; stale mappings remain:

```solidity
// crates/transaction-pool/src/blobstore/disk.rs

fn read_many_raw(&self, txs: Vec<TxHash>) -> Vec<(TxHash, Vec<u8>)> {
    let _lock = self.file_lock.read();
    for tx in txs {
        let path = self.blob_disk_file(tx);
        match fs::read(&path) {
            Ok(data) => res.push((tx, data)),
            Err(err) => { debug!(... "Failed to read blob file"); } // no map cleanup
        }
    }
    res
}
```

`contains` masks failed persistence while cache lives:

```solidity
fn contains(&self, tx: B256) -> Result<bool, BlobStoreError> {
    if self.blob_cache.lock().get(&tx).is_some() { return Ok(true) }
    Ok(self.blob_disk_file(tx).is_file())
}
```

Static LRU sizing does not scale with BPO/PeerDAS; evictions break v2 resolution:

```solidity
fn new(blob_dir: PathBuf, max_length: u32) -> Self {
    Self {
        blob_cache: Mutex::new(LruMap::new(ByLength::new(max_length))),          // default 100
        versioned_hashes_to_txhash: Mutex::new(LruMap::new(ByLength::new(max_length * 6))), // 600
    }
}
```

Batch path exhibits the same publish-before-persist and no rollback per failed write:

```solidity
fn insert_many(&self, txs: Vec<(B256, BlobTransactionSidecarVariant)>) -> Result<(), BlobStoreError> {
    { let mut map = self.versioned_hashes_to_txhash.lock(); for (tx, data) in &txs { ... map.insert(...); } }
    { let mut cache = self.blob_cache.lock(); for (tx, data) in txs { cache.insert(tx, Arc::new(data)); } }
    let _lock = self.file_lock.write();
    for (path, data) in raw {
        if path.exists() { ... }
        else if let Err(err) = fs::write(&path, &data) { debug!(... "Failed to write blob file"); }
        else { add += data.len(); num += 1; } // success only updates size; stale publishes remain
    }
    ...
}
```

Upstream ignores partial publish on error:

```solidity
// crates/transaction-pool/src/pool/mod.rs

fn insert_blob(&self, hash: TxHash, blob: BlobTransactionSidecarVariant) {
    if let Err(err) = self.blob_store.insert(hash, blob) {  // in-mem already mutated on failure
        warn!(...); self.blob_store_metrics.blobstore_failed_inserts.increment(1);
    }
}
```

## Attack Steps

1. Broadcast `PooledTransactions` with `wrapper_version=1` and valid `cell_proofs` for bait tx `T` (≤6 blobs); `insert_one(hash_T, sidecar_T)` updates `versioned_hashes_to_txhash` and `blob_cache`, then persists.
2. Eviction-only: flood ≥120 6-blob txs to evict `T` from `blob_cache` (cap 100) and ≥600 new versioned hashes to evict `T`’s entries from `versioned_hashes_to_txhash` (cap 600).
3. Optional ENOSPC: pre-fill disk; insert `T` so `fs::write` fails; stale in-memory publishes remain; then evict `T` from `blob_cache` per step 2.
4. Builder picks `T` and calls `engine_getBlobsv2([H1..Hk])`.
5. `get_by_versioned_hashes_v2` misses the cache and lacks vhash→tx mappings; no disk read occurs (or `fs::read` NotFound); at least one unresolved entry remains.
6. `get_by_versioned_hashes_v2` returns `None`; `engine_getBlobsv2` fails; builder aborts or drops blobs, missing the slot’s revenue.

### Likelihood

Exploitable by any peer gossipping valid EIP-7594 blob txs; no privileges required. Conditions: sustained sidecar volume to exceed static LRU capacities (100 cache, 600 vhash entries) and/or transient disk write failures (e.g., ENOSPC) during BPO blob surges. These conditions naturally occur with EIP-7892 scaling and PeerDAS load; an attacker can maintain eviction pressure with many valid 6-blob txs and minimal on-chain cost. Timing depends on aligning eviction with the builder’s `engine_getBlobsv2` calls, which occur every slot; this is achievable with continuous pressure.

### Impact

Direct effect is a denial of blob retrieval for `engine_getBlobsv2`: builders receive `None` and abort payload assembly or exclude blob txs. Consequence is missed proposer/builder revenue per affected slot (issuance, priority fees, blob fees, MEV), potentially repeating over multiple slots during blob surges. No user funds are stolen and no consensus split occurs; availability/liveness and operator economics are materially degraded.

## PoC

Place the following test in `disk.rs` :

```rust
use alloy_eips::eip4844::{Blob};
use alloy_eips::eip7594::{BlobTransactionSidecarEip7594};
use alloy_primitives::FixedBytes;

/// cargo test --package reth-transaction-pool --lib -- blobstore::disk::tests::disk_drops --nocapture
#[test]
fn disk_drops() {
    let (store, _dir) = tmp_store();

    // Helper to create a blob sidecar with actual versioned hashes
    let create_blob_sidecar = |seed: u8, num_blobs: usize| -> BlobTransactionSidecarVariant {
    let mut blobs = Vec::new();
    let mut commitments = Vec::new();
    let mut cells_and_proofs = Vec::new();

    for i in 0..num_blobs {
        // Create a blob (doesn't matter what's in it)
        let mut blob = Blob::default();
        blob[0] = seed;
        blob[1] = i as u8;
        blobs.push(blob);

        // Create a unique commitment (48 bytes)
        let mut commitment = [0u8; 48];
        commitment[0] = seed;
        commitment[1] = i as u8;
        commitments.push(FixedBytes::from(commitment));

        // Create cell proofs for EIP-7594 (48 bytes each)
        // Each blob needs CELLS_PER_EXT_BLOB proofs
        for j in 0..128 {  // Assuming 128 cells per blob
            let mut cell_proof = [0u8; 48];
            cell_proof[0] = seed;
            cell_proof[1] = i as u8;
            cell_proof[2] = j as u8;
            cells_and_proofs.push(FixedBytes::from(cell_proof));
        }
    }

        BlobTransactionSidecarVariant::Eip7594(
            BlobTransactionSidecarEip7594::new(blobs, commitments, cells_and_proofs) 
        )
    };

    // Step 1: Insert target transaction with actual blobs
    let target_tx = B256::from([0x01; 32]);
    let target_sidecar = create_blob_sidecar(0x01, 6); // 6 blobs

    // Get versioned hashes - these are computed from commitments
    let target_vhashes: Vec<B256> = target_sidecar.versioned_hashes().collect();
    assert_eq!(target_vhashes.len(), 6, "Should have 2 versioned hashes");

    println!("Target tx: {:?}", target_tx);
    println!("Target versioned hashes: {:?}", target_vhashes);

    store.insert(target_tx, target_sidecar.clone()).unwrap();

    // Verify initial state - everything should work
    assert!(store.is_cached(&target_tx));
    assert!(store.contains(target_tx).unwrap());

    let v2_initial = store.get_by_versioned_hashes_v2(&target_vhashes).unwrap();
    assert!(v2_initial.is_some(), "v2 should find all hashes initially");

    // Step 2: Trigger LRU eviction of blob_cache (limit: 100)
    println!("\nInserting 100 transactions to evict from blob_cache...");
    for i in 2..102 {
        let tx = B256::from([i as u8; 32]);
        let sidecar = create_blob_sidecar(i as u8, 6);
        store.insert(tx, sidecar).unwrap();
    }

    // Target should be evicted from blob_cache but still in versioned_hashes_to_txhash
    assert!(!store.is_cached(&target_tx), "Target evicted from blob_cache");

    // Step 3: Trigger LRU eviction of versioned_hashes_to_txhash (limit: 600)
    // Each blob creates one versioned hash, so we need 600+ new versioned hashes
    println!("\nInserting transactions to evict versioned hash mappings...");
    // We need unique versioned hashes, not duplicate ones!
    for i in 102..703 {
        let mut bytes = [0u8; 32];
        bytes[0] = 0x02; // Different from target's 0x01
        bytes[1] = (i & 0xFF) as u8;
        bytes[2] = ((i >> 8) & 0xFF) as u8;
        let tx = B256::from(bytes);

        // Use unique seed based on full value of i
        // This ensures unique commitments and thus unique versioned hashes
        let sidecar = create_blob_sidecar(
            (i & 0xFF) as u8,  // This creates duplicate commitments!
            6
        );
        store.insert(tx, sidecar).unwrap();
    }

    // Now we have inserted 602 new versioned hashes, which should evict the target's mappings

    // Step 4: Demonstrate the vulnerability
    println!("\n=== Testing after versioned hash mapping eviction ===");

    // Check versioned hash lookups
    let v2_final = store.get_by_versioned_hashes_v2(&target_vhashes).unwrap();
    println!("V2 result: {}", if v2_final.is_some() { "Found all" } else { "Missing some/all" });

    // NOW check direct fetch - blob is on disk (also re-populates cache!)
    let direct = store.get(target_tx).unwrap();
    assert!(direct.is_some(), "Direct fetch works - blob IS on disk!");

    if v2_final.is_none() {
        println!("\nVULNERABILITY CONFIRMED");
        println!("get_by_versioned_hashes_v2 fails after eviction");
        println!("even though blob exists on disk (direct fetch works)");
    } else {
        println!("\nFAILURE TO CONFIRM VULNERABILITY");
    }

    // Assert the vulnerability exists
    assert!(v2_final.is_none(), "Versioned hash lookup should fail after mapping eviction");
}
```

## Mitigation

Change insert paths to persist-then-publish with atomic rename and self-heal on read:
- In `DiskFileBlobStoreInner::insert_one/insert_many`, write sidecar to `blob_dir/<tx>.tmp`, `sync_all()`, then `rename()` to final path; only after success update `versioned_hashes_to_txhash`, `blob_cache`, and `size_tracker`; on any error, do not mutate in-memory structures.
- Replace `write_one_encoded` with `write_one_atomic` as above; treat existing final path as success without double-counting size.
- In `get_by_versioned_hashes_v{1,2}`, if a mapped tx file `fs::read` fails, remove the corresponding vhash→tx entry to scrub stale mappings.
- Scale `DEFAULT_MAX_CACHED_BLOBS` and `versioned_hashes_to_txhash` capacity by current `blobSchedule.max` (e.g., ≥2× `max_blobs_per_block` × 6) to reduce eviction-induced misses under BPO.

## Summary

`DiskFileBlobStoreInner::write_one_encoded` persists every validated EIP‑4844/7594 sidecar directly to the final path with no quota, atomicity, or immediate cleanup, allowing attackers to fill disk via valid blob tx floods. The vulnerable path is admitted by `PoolInner::insert_blob` for every `ValidWithSidecar`, regardless of subpool or eviction. This is a classic resource-exhaustion vulnerability, exacerbated by Fusaka’s PeerDAS wrappers and BPO-capacity increases.

## Finding Description

The write path uses direct `fs::write` to the final file without quota checks or atomic rename (risk of partial reads by other processes):

```solidity
// crates/transaction-pool/src/blobstore/disk.rs
#[inline]
fn write_one_encoded(&self, tx: B256, data: &[u8]) -> Result<usize, DiskFileBlobStoreError> {
    trace!(target:"txpool::blob", "[{:?}] writing blob file", tx);
    let mut add = 0;
    let path = self.blob_disk_file(tx);
    {
        let _lock = self.file_lock.write();
        if !path.exists() {
            fs::write(&path, data)                  // non-atomic write to final path
                .map_err(|e| DiskFileBlobStoreError::WriteFile(tx, path, e))?;
            add = data.len();                       // no pre-write quota check
        }
    }
    Ok(add)
}
```

Sidecars are always persisted and counted without admission control:

```solidity
// crates/transaction-pool/src/blobstore/disk.rs
fn insert_one(&self, tx: B256, data: BlobTransactionSidecarVariant) -> Result<(), BlobStoreError> {
    let mut buf = Vec::with_capacity(data.rlp_encoded_fields_length());
    data.rlp_encode_fields(&mut buf);
    {
        let mut map = self.versioned_hashes_to_txhash.lock();
        data.versioned_hashes().for_each(|hash| { map.insert(hash, tx); });
    }
    self.blob_cache.lock().insert(tx, Arc::new(data));
    let size = self.write_one_encoded(tx, &buf)?;  // persists every sidecar
    self.size_tracker.add_size(size);              // unbounded counters
    self.size_tracker.inc_len(1);
    Ok(())
}
```

Batch path persists multiple files under one lock, still without quota or backpressure:

```solidity
// crates/transaction-pool/src/blobstore/disk.rs
fn insert_many(&self, txs: Vec<(B256, BlobTransactionSidecarVariant)>) -> Result<(), BlobStoreError> {
    let raw = txs.iter().map(|(tx, data)| {
        let mut buf = Vec::with_capacity(data.rlp_encoded_fields_length());
        data.rlp_encode_fields(&mut buf);
        (self.blob_disk_file(*tx), buf)
    }).collect::<Vec<_>>();
    ...
    let mut add = 0; let mut num = 0;
    { let _lock = self.file_lock.write();
      for (path, data) in raw {
          if path.exists() { ... }
          else if let Err(err) = fs::write(&path, &data) { ... } else {
              add += data.len(); num += 1;           // no quota checks
          }
      }
    }
    self.size_tracker.add_size(add);
    self.size_tracker.inc_len(num);
    Ok(())
}
```

Counters are unbounded and can wrap on 32-bit:

```solidity
// crates/transaction-pool/src/blobstore/mod.rs
#[derive(Debug, Default)]
pub(crate) struct BlobStoreSize {
    data_size: AtomicUsize, num_blobs: AtomicUsize,
}
impl BlobStoreSize {
    #[inline] pub(crate) fn add_size(&self, add: usize) {
        self.data_size.fetch_add(add, Ordering::Relaxed);   // no saturation/quota
    }
    ...
}
```

Evictions defer deletion; no immediate unlink to reclaim space:

```solidity
// crates/transaction-pool/src/blobstore/disk.rs
fn delete(&self, tx: B256) -> Result<(), BlobStoreError> {
    if self.inner.contains(tx)? { self.inner.txs_to_delete.write().insert(tx); }
    Ok(())
}
fn cleanup(&self) -> BlobStoreCleanupStat {
    let txs_to_delete = std::mem::take(&mut *self.inner.txs_to_delete.write());
    ...
    for tx in txs_to_delete { ... fs::remove_file(&path) ... }
    self.inner.size_tracker.sub_size(subsize as usize);
    self.inner.size_tracker.sub_len(stat.delete_succeed);
    stat
}
```

Cleanup runs only opportunistically on finalized blocks; not on eviction:

```solidity
// crates/transaction-pool/src/maintain.rs
if let Some(finalized) = last_finalized_block.update(...) &&
   let BlobStoreUpdates::Finalized(blobs) = blob_store_tracker.on_finalized_block(finalized) {
    pool.delete_blobs(blobs);
    task_spawner.spawn_blocking(Box::pin(async move { pool.cleanup_blobs(); })); // deferred
}
```

Every `ValidWithSidecar` persists on disk, ungated:

```solidity
// crates/transaction-pool/src/pool/mod.rs
fn insert_blob(&self, hash: TxHash, blob: BlobTransactionSidecarVariant) {
    if let Err(err) = self.blob_store.insert(hash, blob) { ... } // not treated as fatal
    self.update_blob_store_metrics();
}
```

## Attack Steps

1. Peer with target and send `PooledTransactions` containing EIP‑7594 wrapper v1 payloads: `rlp([tx_payload_body, 0x01, blobs[], commitments[], cell_proofs[]])` where `commitments` hash to `blob_versioned_hashes` and `cell_proofs` covers all cells. Use up to 6 blobs per tx.
2. Set `chain_id` to match, `nonce` increasing, `gas_limit` ≤ 2^24, `max_fee_per_gas = 1`, `max_priority_fee_per_gas ≥ minimum` (if any), `max_fee_per_blob_gas = 1`, `value = 0`, ensuring balance covers `cost`.
3. Node validates blob sidecars (`validate_blob`) and returns `ValidWithSidecar`. `PoolInner::add_transaction` inserts tx (often parked) and calls `insert_blob`.
4. `DiskFileBlobStore::insert` encodes sidecar and calls `fs::write(blob_dir/<txhash>, buf)`, then increments `data_size` and `num_blobs` without quota.
5. Pool may discard txs due to in-memory limits; `delete_all` only enqueues for future `cleanup`; files remain on disk.
6. Repeat with many accounts to bypass per-sender caps; maximize per-tx blobs. Disk usage grows monotonically until filesystem is full; subsequent writes fail, degrading mempool, blob serving, and potentially other services sharing the volume.

## Likelihood

Any external peer or RPC user can mass-submit valid EIP‑7594 blob txs with negligible fees and minimal one-time balance threshold; each accepted `ValidWithSidecar` is persisted to disk with no quota or immediate cleanup, and evictions do not unlink files. No special timing or dependencies are required, proof generation is routine with common libraries, and BPO (EIP‑7892) and PeerDAS (EIP‑7594) naturally increase acceptance volume. Execution requires only basic P2P capability and standard tx crafting.

## Impact

Sustained valid blob submissions fill `blob_dir`, causing local denial of service: blob serving fails (e.g., `getBlobsV2` returns `None` after cache eviction), and if `blob_dir` shares a filesystem with DB/logs, ENOSPC halts block import and engine/p2p functions. Cross-process readers may observe partial files due to non-atomic writes, causing decode failures. No on-chain state is corrupted, but validators/builders relying on the node can miss proposals and revenue during outage; the impact scales to full node downtime until manual cleanup.

# PoC

Place the following test in `disk.rs` :

```rust
use alloy_eips::eip4844::{Blob, BlobTransactionSidecar};
use alloy_eips::eip7594::{BlobTransactionSidecarEip7594, BlobTransactionSidecarVariant};
use alloy_primitives::{FixedBytes, B256};
use std::fs;
use std::sync::atomic::Ordering;

/// PoC demonstrating disk exhaustion vulnerability in blob store
/// cargo test --package reth-transaction-pool --lib -- blobstore::disk::tests::disk_exhaustion_attack --nocapture
/// 
/// This test shows:
/// 1. Blobs persist to disk immediately upon insertion
/// 2. Only finalized/mined transactions get cleaned up
/// 3. Unmined transactions remain on disk indefinitely
/// 4. Disk usage grows unbounded for unmined blob transactions
#[test]
fn disk_exhaustion_attack() {
    let dir = tempfile::tempdir().unwrap();
    let store = DiskFileBlobStore::open(dir.path(), DiskFileBlobStoreConfig {
        max_cached_entries: 10,             // Small cache to trigger evictions quickly
        open: OpenDiskFileBlobStore::Clear, // Inconsequential as its not actually read.
    }).unwrap();

    // Helper to create a realistic blob sidecar (EIP-7594 with actual data)
    let create_blob_sidecar = |seed: u8, num_blobs: usize| -> BlobTransactionSidecarVariant {
        let mut blobs = Vec::new();
        let mut commitments = Vec::new();
        let mut cells_and_proofs = Vec::new();

        for i in 0..num_blobs {
            // Create a blob with actual data (4096 field elements * 31 bytes each)
            let mut blob = Blob::default();
            // Fill blob with pattern to simulate real data
            for j in 0..blob.len() {
                blob[j] = ((seed as usize + i * 256 + j) % 256) as u8;
            }
            blobs.push(blob);

            // Create a unique commitment (48 bytes)
            let mut commitment = [0u8; 48];
            commitment[0] = seed;
            commitment[1] = i as u8;
            for j in 2..48 {
                commitment[j] = ((i + j) % 256) as u8;
            }
            commitments.push(FixedBytes::from(commitment));

            // Create cell proofs for EIP-7594 (128 cells * 48 bytes each)
            for j in 0..128 {
                let mut cell_proof = [0u8; 48];
                cell_proof[0] = seed;
                cell_proof[1] = i as u8;
                cell_proof[2] = j as u8;
                cells_and_proofs.push(FixedBytes::from(cell_proof));
            }
        }

        BlobTransactionSidecarVariant::Eip7594(
            BlobTransactionSidecarEip7594::new(blobs, commitments, cells_and_proofs)
        )
    };

    // Helper to get actual disk usage
    let get_disk_usage = || -> u64 {
        let mut total = 0u64;
        if let Ok(entries) = fs::read_dir(dir.path()) {
            for entry in entries {
                if let Ok(entry) = entry && 
                    let Ok(metadata) = entry.metadata() {
                    if metadata.is_file() {
                        total += metadata.len();
                    }
                }
            }
        }
        total
    };

    println!("\n=== Phase 1: Initial Attack - Flood with Low-Fee Blob Transactions ===");

    // These simulate transactions with minimum fees that won't get mined
    let mut unmined_txs = Vec::new();

    println!("Inserting 50 low-fee blob transactions (won't be mined)...");
    for i in 0..50 {
        let tx = B256::from([i as u8; 32]);
        let sidecar = create_blob_sidecar(i as u8, 6); // Max blobs per tx
        store.insert(tx, sidecar).unwrap();
        unmined_txs.push(tx);
    }

    let disk_after_initial = get_disk_usage();
    println!("Disk usage after initial flood: {} bytes", disk_after_initial);
    println!("Tracked size in store: {} bytes", store.inner.size_tracker.data_size());
    println!("Number of blobs tracked: {}", store.inner.size_tracker.blobs_len());

    // Check cache eviction (only 10 entries in cache)
    let cache_size = store.inner.blob_cache.lock().len();
    println!("Cache size (should be 10): {}", cache_size);
    assert_eq!(cache_size, 10, "Cache should be at limit");

    // Verify early transactions are evicted from cache but still on disk
    assert!(!store.is_cached(&unmined_txs[0]), "First tx should be evicted from cache");
    assert!(store.contains(unmined_txs[0]).unwrap(), "But still exists on disk!");

    println!("\n=== Phase 2: Continue Attack While Some Txs Get Mined ===");

    // Simulate mixed scenario: some high-fee txs that get mined, more low-fee that don't
    let mut mined_txs = Vec::new();
    let mut more_unmined_txs = Vec::new();

    println!("Inserting 10 high-fee transactions (will be mined)...");
    for i in 100..110 {
        let tx = B256::from([i as u8; 32]);
        let sidecar = create_blob_sidecar(i as u8, 6);
        store.insert(tx, sidecar).unwrap();
        mined_txs.push(tx);
    }

    println!("Inserting 40 more low-fee transactions (won't be mined)...");
    for i in 50..90 {
        let tx = B256::from([i as u8; 32]);
        let sidecar = create_blob_sidecar(i as u8, 6);
        store.insert(tx, sidecar).unwrap();
        more_unmined_txs.push(tx);
    }

    let disk_after_continued = get_disk_usage();
    println!("Disk usage after continued attack: {} bytes", disk_after_continued);
    assert!(disk_after_continued > disk_after_initial, "Disk usage increased");

    println!("\n=== Phase 3: Simulate Finalized Block with Cleanup ===");

    // Simulate the finalization process - only mined txs get cleaned
    println!("Block finalized with 10 transactions, marking them for deletion...");
    for tx in &mined_txs {
        store.delete(*tx).unwrap();
    }

    // Verify marked transactions still exist before cleanup
    for tx in &mined_txs {
        assert!(store.contains(*tx).unwrap(), 
                "Mined tx still on disk before cleanup");
    }

    // Run cleanup (as triggered by maintain_transaction_pool on finalized block)
    println!("Running cleanup (triggered by finalized block)...");
    let cleanup_stats = store.cleanup();
    println!("Cleanup stats - deleted: {}, failed: {}", 
            cleanup_stats.delete_succeed, cleanup_stats.delete_failed);

    let disk_after_cleanup = get_disk_usage();
    println!("Disk usage after cleanup: {} bytes", disk_after_cleanup);

    println!("\n=== Verification: What Remains on Disk? ===");

    // Check mined transactions (should be cleaned)
    let mut mined_cleaned = 0;
    for tx in &mined_txs {
        if !store.contains(*tx).unwrap() {
            mined_cleaned += 1;
        }
    }
    println!("Mined transactions cleaned: {}/{}", mined_cleaned, mined_txs.len());
    assert_eq!(mined_cleaned, mined_txs.len(), "All mined txs should be cleaned");

    // Check unmined transactions from phase 1 (should still exist)
    let mut phase1_exist = 0;
    for tx in &unmined_txs {
        if store.contains(*tx).unwrap() {
            phase1_exist += 1;
        }
    }
    println!("Phase 1 unmined txs still on disk: {}/{}", phase1_exist, unmined_txs.len());

    // Check unmined transactions from phase 2 (should still exist)
    let mut phase2_exist = 0;
    for tx in &more_unmined_txs {
        if store.contains(*tx).unwrap() {
            phase2_exist += 1;
        }
    }
    println!("Phase 2 unmined txs still on disk: {}/{}", phase2_exist, more_unmined_txs.len());

    println!("\n=== Attack Impact Summary ===");
    println!("Initial disk usage: 0 bytes");
    println!("Peak disk usage: {} bytes", disk_after_continued);
    println!("After cleanup: {} bytes", disk_after_cleanup);

    let total_unmined = unmined_txs.len() + more_unmined_txs.len();
    let cleanup_amount = disk_after_continued - disk_after_cleanup;
    println!("\nCleanup removed: {} bytes (mined transactions only)", cleanup_amount);
    println!("Remaining waste: {} bytes from {} unmined transactions", 
            disk_after_cleanup, total_unmined);

    // Calculate attack impact
    let bytes_per_blob_tx = disk_after_cleanup / total_unmined as u64;
    println!("\nAttack impact over time:");
    println!("Average bytes per blob tx on disk: {}", bytes_per_blob_tx);

    // Each EIP-7594 sidecar with 6 blobs contains:
    // - 6 blobs * 131072 bytes (128KB each) = 786,432 bytes
    // - 6 commitments * 48 bytes = 288 bytes  
    // - 6 * 128 cells * 48 bytes proofs = 36,864 bytes
    // - RLP encoding overhead ≈ 1-2KB
    // Total: ~824KB per transaction
    let expected_size = 824 * 1024;
    println!("Expected size per 6-blob tx: {} bytes", expected_size);
    println!("Actual size ratio: {:.1}%", (bytes_per_blob_tx as f64 / expected_size as f64) * 100.0);

    // Attack rate calculations
    let txs_per_minute = 100; // More realistic sustained rate
    let disk_growth_per_min = (txs_per_minute * bytes_per_blob_tx) / (1024 * 1024);
    println!("\nWith {} low-fee txs/minute: {} MB/minute disk growth", 
            txs_per_minute, disk_growth_per_min);

    let disk_growth_per_hour = disk_growth_per_min * 60;
    println!("Hourly disk growth: {} MB/hour", disk_growth_per_hour);

    // Time to exhaust various disk sizes
    println!("\nTime to exhaust disk:");
    println!("  100 GB disk: {:.1} hours", (100 * 1024) as f64 / disk_growth_per_hour as f64);
    println!("  500 GB disk: {:.1} hours", (500 * 1024) as f64 / disk_growth_per_hour as f64);
    println!("  1 TB disk: {:.1} hours", (1024 * 1024) as f64 / disk_growth_per_hour as f64);

    // Cleanup window vs attack rate
    let finalization_minutes = 13; // ~2 epochs
    let disk_filled_per_finalization = txs_per_minute * finalization_minutes * bytes_per_blob_tx;
    println!("\nPer finalization window ({} min):", finalization_minutes);
    println!("  Disk filled: {} MB", disk_filled_per_finalization / (1024 * 1024));
    println!("  Attack sustainable: cleanup only removes mined txs, not low-fee txs");

    // Core vulnerability assertions
    assert_eq!(phase1_exist, unmined_txs.len(), 
               "ALL unmined txs from phase 1 remain on disk!");
    assert_eq!(phase2_exist, more_unmined_txs.len(), 
               "ALL unmined txs from phase 2 remain on disk!");
    assert!(disk_after_cleanup > 0, 
            "Disk still has blobs after cleanup!");
}
```

# Mitigation

Implement bounded, atomic sidecar persistence with eager reclamation and strict failure handling: add `max_store_bytes` (and optional `min_free_space`, `high_water_bytes`, `eager_delete`) to `DiskFileBlobStoreConfig`; track `used_bytes: AtomicU64`; in `insert_one/insert_many`, pre-encode and reject with `BlobStoreError::QuotaExceeded` if `used_bytes + size > max_store_bytes` or free space < threshold; replace `fs::write` with tmpfile `create_new(true)`, `write_all`, `flush/sync`, then atomic `rename` to final path; on eviction or if `used_bytes > high_water`, unlink immediately (or trigger async `cleanup()`) and decrement `used_bytes`/counters; change `BlobStoreSize` to `AtomicU64` with saturating updates;

The `versioned_hashes_to_txhash` LruMap determines what blobs can be looked up from disk when `get_by_versioned_hashes_v2` is called. Thus, it makes sense to clean up disk every time an item is evicted from this collection. Implement the `schnellru::Limiter` trait to get notified when an item gets evicted (`on_removed`), do the disk cleanup and update counters.

### Summary

This issue addresses a problem where the functionality of [EIP-7935](https://eips.ethereum.org/EIPS/eip-7935) is neutralized due to [EIP-7825](https://eips.ethereum.org/EIPS/eip-7825), which is being handled in the upcoming Osaka upgrade.

### Root Cause

This issue arises from the identical implementation of EIP-7825 and EIP-7935. The problem occurs in the code below.

    ```go
    // core/txpool/validation.go::ValidateTransaction()
    // https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/blob/master/core/txpool/validation.go#L92
    func ValidateTransaction(tx *types.Transaction, head *types.Header, signer types.Signer, opts *ValidationOptions) error {
    // [...]
    if rules.IsOsaka && tx.Gas() > params.MaxTxGas {
      return fmt.Errorf("%w (cap: %d, tx: %d)", core.ErrGasLimitTooHigh, params.MaxTxGas, tx.Gas())
    }
    // Transactions can't be negative. This may never happen using RLP decoded
    // transactions but may occur for transactions created using the RPC.
    if tx.Value().Sign() < 0 {
      return ErrNegativeValue
    }

    // Ensure the transaction doesn't exceed the current block limit gas
    if head.GasLimit < tx.Gas() {
      return ErrGasLimit
    }
    // [...]
    }
    ```

EIP-7825, introduced with the Osaka upgrade, adds a check that compares the `MaxTxGas` value with the transaction gas limit when a transaction is added. Additionally, EIP-7935 aims to increase the existing `GasLimit` to 60M.
Thus, no related modification is introduced, and clients are expected to update their default `GasLimit` value is 60M.

However, in the code above, the EIP-7825 check takes precedence when adding a transaction. As a result, if the transaction’s gas limit exceeds the EIP-7825 threshold of `1 << 24 (16,777,216)`, the transaction is rejected. Even though EIP-7935 intends to allow a transaction gas limit up to 60M, transactions where `(1 << 24 (16,777,216)) < Gas() <= 60M` will still be denied.
In other words, the introduction of EIP-7825 effectively neutralizes the functionality of EIP-7935.

### Internal Pre-conditions

To reproduce the issue above, the following minimum condition must be met:

`params.MaxTxGas < head.GasLimit`

This condition is inevitably satisfied due to the conflicting goals of EIP-7825 and EIP-7935.

### External Pre-conditions

A transaction with a gas limit satisfying the following condition must be added:

`(1 << 24 (16,777,216)) < Gas() <= 60M`


### Attack Path

The scenario in which this issue occurs is as follows:

1. After the Osaka update, the client sets the `GasLimit` value to 60M in accordance with EIP-7935.
2. According to [EIP-7935](https://eips.ethereum.org/EIPS/eip-7935), any transaction with a gas limit of 60M or less should be accepted.
3. Users attempt to add transactions with gas limits satisfying the condition `(1 << 24 (16,777,216)) < Gas() <= 60M`, but these transactions are rejected due to EIP-7825.

### Impact

Due to this issue, transactions that meet the intended conditions are not added to the transaction pool even when they are submitted.


### PoC

```go
package legacypool

import (
	"fmt"
	// "crypto/ecdsa"
	"math/big"
	"testing"

	// "github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/common"
	"github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/core/state"
	"github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/core/tracing"
