### Summary

Broken assembly of inputs to `VerifyCellKZGProofBatch` in `crypto/kzg4844/kzg4844_ckzg_cgo.go` means the client does not satisfy the EIP-7594 PeerDAS verification rules for cell proofs. As it is now, the CKZG path can misalign `cells/indices/commitments` and fail the spec’s required `(blob i, cell j)` mapping.

### Root Cause

In `crypto/kzg4844/kzg4844_ckzg_cgo.go`, the batch verifier builds mismatched slices for `cells`, `cellIndices`, `commitments`, and `proofs`, violating the strict 1:1 alignment required by EIP-7594:
- the code misaligns `(blob i, cell j)`mappings — reindexing `cellIndices` per-blob without offset and duplicating commitments without preserving correspondence to individual cells. 

https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/blob/b87581f2977393c842123d18c6e29e268f9b26cb/crypto/kzg4844/kzg4844_ckzg_cgo.go#L154-L192
```go
func ckzgVerifyCellProofBatch(blobs []Blob, commitments []Commitment, cellProofs []Proof) error {
	ckzgIniter.Do(ckzgInit)
	var (
		proofs      = make([]ckzg4844.Bytes48, len(cellProofs))
		commits     = make([]ckzg4844.Bytes48, 0, len(cellProofs))
		cellIndices = make([]uint64, 0, len(cellProofs))
		cells       = make([]ckzg4844.Cell, 0, len(cellProofs))
	)
	// Copy over the cell proofs
	for i, proof := range cellProofs {
		proofs[i] = (ckzg4844.Bytes48)(proof)
	}
	// Blow up the commitments to be the same length as the proofs
	for _, commitment := range commitments {
		for range gokzg4844.CellsPerExtBlob {
			commits = append(commits, (ckzg4844.Bytes48)(commitment))
		}
	}
	// Compute the cells and cell indices
	for i := range blobs {
		cellsI, err := ckzg4844.ComputeCells((*ckzg4844.Blob)(&blobs[i]))
		if err != nil {
			return err
		}
		cells = append(cells, cellsI[:]...)
		for idx := range len(cellsI) {
			cellIndices = append(cellIndices, uint64(idx))
		}
	}

	valid, err := ckzg4844.VerifyCellKZGProofBatch(commits, cellIndices, cells, proofs)
	if err != nil {
		return err
	}
	if !valid {
		return errors.New("invalid proof")
	}
	return nil
}
```


As per EIP-7594
https://eips.ethereum.org/EIPS/eip-7594#networking

```text
In other words, cell_proofs[i * CELLS_PER_EXT_BLOB + j] is the proof for cell j of compute_cells(blobs[i]), where compute_cells(blob) outputs all cells of blob, including the extension cells.
```

```text
cell_proofs contains exactly CELLS_PER_EXT_BLOB * len(blobs) cell proofs
The KZG commitments hash to the versioned hashes, i.e. kzg_to_versioned_hash(commitments[i]) == tx_payload_body.blob_versioned_hashes[i]
The KZG commitments match the corresponding blobs and cell_proofs. This requires computing the extension cells for all blobs (e.g. via compute_cells), and verifying all cell_proofs. (Note: all cell proofs can be batch verified at once, e.g. via verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch)
```

In the code above, this requirement is violated because:
- `commitments`: duplicated in a flat loop per blob.
- `cells` and `cellIndices`: flattened per blob.

This creates mismatches between the (blob i, cell j) tuple and its corresponding commitment and proof.

### Impact

The batch verifier may verify a proof for the wrong (blob i, cell j) pair, leading to false positives or negatives in proof validation.

It also breaks the EIP as it fails to uphold the invariant that c`ell_proofs[i * CELLS_PER_EXT_BLOB + j]` must correspond exactly to the proof for `compute_cells(blobs[i])[j]`. 

## Mitigation

Replace `ckzgVerifyCellProofBatch` with the logic below, which enforces strict 1:1 alignment across `commitments`, `indices`, `cells`, `proofs`.


```diff
//crypto/kzg4844/kzg4844_ckzg_cgo.go

func ckzgVerifyCellProofBatch(commitments []Commitment, zs []CellIndex, ys []Cell, proofs []CellProof) bool {
    // Inputs must be 1:1 aligned and equal length.
    if len(commitments) != len(zs) || len(zs) != len(ys) || len(ys) != len(proofs) {
        useCKZG.Store(false)
        return false
    }

    commits := make([]*ckzg4844.KZGCommitment, len(commitments))
    cells   := make([]*ckzg4844.Bytes48,     len(ys))
    indices := make([]uint64,                len(zs))
    protfs  := make([]*ckzg4844.KZGProof,    len(proofs))
    for i := 0; i < len(commitments); i++ {
        commits[i] = (*ckzg4844.KZGCommitment)(&commitments[i])
        indices[i] = uint64(zs[i])
        cells[i]   = (*ckzg4844.Bytes48)(&ys[i])
        protfs[i]  = (*ckzg4844.KZGProof)(&proofs[i])
    }

    ok, err := ckzg.VerifyCellKZGProofBatch(commits, indices, cells, protfs)
    useCKZG.Store(err == nil && ok)
    return err == nil && ok
}
```

### Summary
All nodes except besu doesn't process blobs from previous version (V1, after fulu/osaka we have V2 with the data columns and cell proofs), so boundary blocks could be problematic with data availability if besu is a proposer

### Root Cause

If there is a leftout V1 blob tx in mempool in nethermind,geth,reth & etc, we don't use them and we just ignore them ( this could be verified in their codebases, for example geth: https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/blob/5c6ba6b40042bf6fdf7a36d2620b658d041bd3ee/miner/worker.go#L488-L492 ) - they don't use it for the new getPayloadV5 and getBlobsV2

For besu however, we support conversion: https://github.com/hyperledger/besu/blob/531bfa6e4d599a3ba8027ec210e67044e971c9a4/ethereum/core/src/main/java/org/hyperledger/besu/ethereum/core/kzg/CKZG4844Helper.java#L46

It supports conversion from V1 to V2 in 2 cases, when:
- V1 is received after osaka in the mempool.
- V1 exists in the mempool prior to osaka and is needed for a proposal ( via getPayloadV5 )
`EngineGetPayloadV5` when called eventually ends up in `BlobsBundleV2.mapBlobWithCommitments` because it directly uses it, which  automatically makes it V1 -> V2
https://github.com/hyperledger/besu/blob/531bfa6e4d599a3ba8027ec210e67044e971c9a4/ethereum/api/src/main/java/org/hyperledger/besu/ethereum/api/jsonrpc/internal/results/BlobsBundleV2.java#L98-L107

However: Besu doesn't return V1s sitting in the mempool after osaka, when getBlobsV2 is called ( they need to be already be converted, because we filter by this ), reference: 
https://github.com/hyperledger/besu/blob/531bfa6e4d599a3ba8027ec210e67044e971c9a4/ethereum/api/src/main/java/org/hyperledger/besu/ethereum/api/jsonrpc/internal/methods/engine/EngineGetBlobsV2.java#L115-L130
```java
  @Override
  public JsonRpcResponse syncResponse(final JsonRpcRequestContext requestContext) {
.......
    for (VersionedHash hash : versionedHashes) {
      final BlobProofBundle bundle = transactionPool.getBlobProofBundle(hash);
      if (bundle == null) {
        LOG.trace("No BlobProofBundle found for versioned hash: {}", hash);
        missingBlobs++;
        continue;
      }
//old version in mempool
@>>   if (bundle.getBlobType() == BlobType.KZG_PROOF) {
        LOG.trace("Unsupported blob type KZG_PROOF for versioned hash: {}", hash);
        unsupportedBlobs++;
        continue;
      }
      validBundles.add(bundle);
    }
    // count how many of the requested blobs are actually available
    availableCounter.inc(validBundles.size());
```

GetBlobsV2 is crucial for data availability in the new model, because CL is supposed to call the EL and retrieve faster the blobs if it has them.

This means that if 1 Besu node makes a proposal IT would be able to retrieve V1 and convert them to V2, but all other EL<->CL pairs won't be able to use the GetBlobsV2 call to do it, including OTHER besu nodes itself because besu itself also doesn't support old blobs from mempool via `GetBlobsV2`

### Internal Pre-conditions

- 
### External Pre-conditions

-
### Attack Path

1. Besu node makes a proposal on block boundary after fusaka and includes multiple V1 blobs, which it converts
2. In the mempool of all other nodes ( including besu ) those txs still sit as versionhashes blobs linked to V1s.
3. During the DA check required by every node, `GetBlobsV2` is not able to retrieve the wanted blobs linked to versionhashed txs with V1, submitted prior to fusaka.
4. Even though those TX sit in every client's mempool they are un-fetchable.
5. DA check could fail or struggle to make it in the attest time, which could penalize wrongly a besu node.
### Impact

Since we need to check data availability for every slot for every client, this would make it significantly harder to distribute the whole DA checks, which could potentially result in not all nodes being able to retrieve columns in time and the proposer ( besu ) potentially wrongly losing owed funds for the proposal and getting wrongly penalized.

### PoC

Add this test in `EngineGetBlobsV2Test.java` un besu and run it, to verify that we don't return the old KZG_PROOF version post-fusaka.
```java
